<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Helen Mirren Praised for 'Passion' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- You expect her to be kind of tough. Guarded.  
Grave. 
</P>
<P>
	After all, for years you followed her as Jane Tennison, the  
driven Scotland Yard detective on public television's ``Prime 
Suspect.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now you find her playing novelist-philosopher Ayn Rand, the  
relentless author of those objectivist doorstops, ``The 
Fountainhead'' and ``Atlas Shrugged.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A pair of formidable women!  
</P>
<P>
	Yet here you are, positively charmed by Helen Mirren, your lunch  
companion, who, when you confess that you've arrived without your 
glasses and can't read the menu, recommends her sure-fire system: 
Go to the drugstore and buy dozens of those inexpensive glasses and 
stash them everywhere. Then you'll never be without. 
</P>
<P>
	She fishes in her purse to show you one of her countless pairs,  
only to find them missing. She dissolves into laughter. 
</P>
<P>
	You don't need your glasses to see that Mirren disappears into a  
role, be it in one of her many features or on the stage with 
Britain's Royal Shakespeare Company. Indeed, some of her best work 
is invisible, the way she somehow intimates Tennison's 
vulnerability, however fiercely it's hidden from the world. 
</P>
<P>
	Mirren demonstrates her powers once again in ``The Passion of  
Ayn Rand,'' premiering on Showtime at 8 p.m. EDT Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The film begins in Los Angeles in 1951, shortly after the  
publication of Rand's best-selling novel ``The Fountainhead.'' A 
UCLA psychology student, Nathaniel Branden (Eric Stoltz), arranges 
to meet her to discuss her philosophy of objectivism. 
</P>
<P>
	Branden and his fiancee Barbara (Julie Delpy) form an almost  
instant bond with Rand and her pliant, flower-growing husband Frank 
O'Connor (Peter Fonda). But the connection isn't purely 
intellectual. Soon, Branden and Rand, despite the quarter-century 
that separates their ages, initiate a lengthy love affair -- having 
logically arranged the consent of their spouses. 
</P>
<P>
	So goes objectivism.  
</P>
<P>
	A half-century later, Rand has legions of admirers (from college  
freshmen to Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan) who have 
absorbed her doctrine of unfettered capitalism, her conviction that 
selfishness is a virtue and altruism a vice. 
</P>
<P>
	But Helen Mirren, who was born in London 53 years ago, tells you  
she had scarcely heard of Ayn (rhymes with ``sign'') Rand before 
the project came her way. 
</P>
<P>
	No matter. ``It was quickly apparent that here was an incredible  
character of the 20th century, one who happens to be woman, which 
makes it better, and one who happens to be a dumpy little 
unattractive woman -- even better!'' 
</P>
<P>
	She laughs at maybe having oversimplified.  
</P>
<P>
	``Ayn could be charming, girly, twinkly,'' Mirren adds. ``She  
wasn't -- what do you call it? -- a battle-ax. Although she could be. 
She could be ferocious. There are some fabulous contradictions 
there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To inhabit the Russian-born Rand, she affected a cigarette  
holder and trilled her R's. Her blond hair went brunet. Even her 
blue eyes were transformed. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wore black contact lenses, because she had these very black,  
shiny eyes. Everyone who saw her talked about how extraordinary 
they were, and I thought that was important. But then I was playing 
the whole thing through this dark, blurry haze: 'Is that Peter 
Fonda over there? I THINK so.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Impersonation was only the beginning. ``To me, that's not  
acting. Acting is something more'' -- and, with delight, she borrows 
a word she heard Roberto Benigni coin -- ``more mysterical! 
Mysterical, isn't that a great word? I'm going to use it for the 
rest of my life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although Mirren concedes an inability to slog through Rand's  
novels -- ``I'm so impressed with American education that 
19-year-olds here can read this stuff!'' -- she found a key to the 
role in one of Rand's early diaries. There, in private, Rand 
resolved always to keep her feelings in check. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that was what she was doing her whole life: trying to  
control emotions that were so huge, much bigger than with most of 
us. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ayn was very honest about herself, yet at the same time, very  
un-self-aware,'' Mirren says. ``For someone who deconstructed and 
examined and tried to control everything, there was this enormous 
weight of humanity within her that she couldn't deconstruct or 
control.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This unintended passion is what sparked her affair with  
Nathaniel Brand. And that, in turn, begat some steamy scenes in the 
film. 
</P>
<P>
	``I asked for them to be put in, actually. Because they weren't  
in the original script. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's awful having to do them, especially if you're not  
unbelievably gorgeous,'' Mirren confides with cheery dread. ``But 
here, for once, it was intrinsic to the story.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even without glasses, you can see what she means. The mysterical  
Helen Mirren is that kind of actress. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in television ...  
</P>
<P>
	`20/20': ``Over the years, people have asked me what the most  
memorable interview I have ever done was,'' says Barbara Walters. 
``It is not a president or a king or a movie star. It is a man I 
interviewed more than 25 years ago. He was a teacher and a poet, 
and the most inspirational person I have ever met.'' On tonight's 
``20/20,'' Walters revisits Robert Smithdas, who is now married to 
a woman who, like him, is deaf and blind. The report airs at 10 
p.m. EDT on ABC. Also, correspondent Arnold Diaz advises consumers 
to read the fine print in advertising. Looking closely at several 
print and television spots, he demonstrates how some offers that 
seem too good to be true often are. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Frazier Moore can be reached at fmoore ``at'' ap.org  
</P>
</TEXT>
