<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Botha Appeals in Truth Panel Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) -- Lawyers for P.W. Botha, white  
South Africa's last hard-line president, began an appeal Friday 
against his conviction for ignoring a summons to appear before a 
panel probing apartheid atrocities. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year Botha was fined the equivalent of $1,575 and given a  
one-year suspended jail sentence for failing to show up at a 
hearing of the Truth and Reconciliation Commission which wanted to 
grill him on his 11 years in power. 
</P>
<P>
	Botha's lawyer Lappe Laubscher said the appeal would be based on  
technicalities that invalidated the subpoena issued by the Truth 
Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	Repeating arguments put forward in the original court case,  
Laubscher said the panel had not followed its own rules in drawing 
up the summons. 
</P>
<P>
	``You cannot convict a person on the basis of an invalid  
subpoena,'' he said ``That is just going too far.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Botha, who lives in retirement in a coastal village about 310  
miles from Cape Town, was not present at the hearing, which is 
expected to last at least two days. 
</P>
<P>
	Botha ruled with an iron fist until 1989, when he was ousted in  
an internal party struggle after he suffered a stroke and was 
replaced by the more liberal F.W. de Klerk. 
</P>
<P>
	Though the Truth Commission has completed its work and there is  
no chance Botha will testify before it, the panel did succeed in 
turning his case into a forum for confronting him with evidence of 
horrific abuses committed during his rule. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
