<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Prosecutors Rest in Torture Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Abner Louima says there were two police officers  
in the stationhouse bathroom where he was tortured. Justin Volpe 
has admitted he was one. But who was the other? 
</P>
<P>
	That question hangs heavily over the federal courtroom where  
four officers still face charges in connection with the attack that 
seriously injured the Haitian immigrant two summers ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The prosecution rested Thursday after a month-long case  
featuring testimony by 50 witnesses and one dramatic guilty plea. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, with the jury off, Volpe admitted publicly for the  
first time that he rammed a stick into a handcuffed Louima's 
rectum, pulled it out and put it up to his face in a fit of rage. 
</P>
<P>
	Volpe, 27, said he believed -- mistakenly -- that the Haitian  
immigrant had punched him when police tried to quell a disturbance 
outside a Brooklyn nightclub on Aug. 9, 1997. He also said a second 
police officer in the bathroom ``saw what was going on and did 
nothing to stop it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Volpe, who is now in federal custody awaiting sentencing, wasn't  
required to name the officer. Nor was the jury told of his 
statements, but were notified that he pleaded guilty. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors say Officer Charles Schwarz held Louima, 32, down  
during the bathroom assault. 
</P>
<P>
	Schwarz is also accused, along with Officers Thomas Wiese and  
Thomas Bruder, of beating Louima in a patrol car en route to the 
station after his arrest on false charges he punched Volpe. Sgt. 
Michael Bellomo, their supervisor, is charged with covering up the 
incident. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Eugene Nickerson dismissed motions by all the defendants  
Thursday to throw out the case based on insufficient evidence. Two 
of the four defense attorneys also rested; the others are expected 
to conclude their cases sometime next week. The trial resumes 
Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
