<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Market Softens for Internet Mergers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- GeoCities Inc. shareholders said yes Friday to  
merging their company with Yahoo! Inc., but they're getting a lot 
less than they once thought. 
</P>
<P>
	Yahoo!, a leading Internet search and directory service, is  
acquiring GeoCities, a company that helps consumers create their 
own Web pages, by issuing 27.4 million shares of stock. 
</P>
<P>
	However, since the deal was announced in January, Internet  
stocks have plunged. That means the Yahoo! shares that were once 
worth $5.04 billion are now valued at $4.06 billion, a 19 percent 
drop. 
</P>
<P>
	The bear market in Internet shares has sharply reduced the value  
of a handful of mergers in the works. Web companies have fallen 29 
percent since mid-April, causing many investors and executives to 
re-think their options. The downward price pressure could put some 
deals in jeopardy and change the structure of future mergers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Small deals will definitely happen, but the big deals, north  
of $200 million, they will slow down for the very short term to see 
where the market's going,'' said Alan Braverman, a senior managing 
director at Banc of America Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Companies with weak stocks and balance sheets may be forced into  
mergers, while stronger companies go bargain hunting using cash 
instead of shares. Investors, for their part, will be looking 
closer at the value of the shares they're getting. 
</P>
<P>
	Yahoo! is already moving to prove to investors there are  
synergies in Friday's deal. Yahoo! is dismissing about 200 
employees from GeoCities, or two-thirds of the company's staff, and 
is moving the headquarters from Los Angeles to Yahoo!'s base in 
Santa Clara, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	``The opportunity for shareholders of GeoCities remains  
strong,'' said Steve Hansen, chief operating officer of GeoCities. 
``Yahoo is a terrific currency to own.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Of course Internet stocks are known to swing wildly, and not all  
Internet deals have lost ground. 
</P>
<P>
	Shareholders of Excite Inc., another Internet search and  
directory service, on Friday approved the company's merger with At 
Home Corp., which delivers high-speed Internet access. 
</P>
<P>
	Excite investors will receive 61 million shares of At Home's  
stock, worth $7.06 billion, or $700 million more than when the deal 
was announced in January. 
</P>
<P>
	Nevertheless, many industry watchers expect Internet stocks to  
swoon throughout the summer. The flood of new Internet companies is 
spreading investment dollars thin, while some money managers 
traditionally dump volatile stocks during vacation months when 
trading volumes drop and it is harder to buy and sell shares. 
</P>
<P>
	And next month, the Russell 2000 small company stock index will  
kick out several Internet companies because they've grown too big. 
Mutual funds that track the index are expected to sell up to $68 
billion worth of Internet stocks, according to L. Keith Mullins, 
emerging growth strategist for Salomon Smith Barney. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies have not been identified, but could include the  
brokers e-Trade Group Inc. and Ameritrade Holding Corp., the 
audio/video company RealNetworks Inc. and the advertising company 
DoubleClick Inc., among others. 
</P>
<P>
	If Internet stocks keep falling, skittish investors, many of  
them buying stocks with borrowed money, may scatter. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Theory of Crowds says everybody will run the other way,  
and suddenly no one will see any value,'' said John ``Hans'' 
Morris, who heads the mergers and acquisitions practice at Salomon 
Smith Barney. 
</P>
<P>
	Small investors could play a critical role in the direction of  
future mergers and acquisitions. They have already shown their 
power. 
</P>
<P>
	Two weeks ago, media entrepreneur Barry Diller called off plans  
to combine his Home Shopping Network with Lycos Inc., another 
Internet search and directory service, after investors pounded the 
stock and criticized the deal in Internet chat groups and message 
boards. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, the announced mergers are expected to get shareholder  
approval, although some investors are concerned about their losses. 
</P>
<P>
	On one stock message board on the Internet, known as Raging  
Bull, investors in Broadcast.com are looking at the drop in 
Yahoo!'s stock with wide eyes. 
</P>
<P>
	Yahoo! offered to buy Broadcast.com, which distributes audio and  
video programing over the Internet, in April for $6.11 billion. On 
Friday, that deal was worth $5.03 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	One Broadcast.com investor, known as sueg10077, had looked  
forward to getting shares in Yahoo! 
</P>
<P>
	``I convinced my husband to keep this, because of Yahoo, when we  
could have made some big bucks (by selling after the deal was 
announced),'' she wrote. ``Give me some consolation. Please!!!'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
