<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 11:31:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Tries To Keep Majority United </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Republicans bumped up against the  
reality of their slender majority this week, and the results were 
stark. Two bills were derailed, two more postponed and several GOP 
lawmakers broke ranks on campaign finance. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any time six people get up in the morning and decide they  
don't like what the leadership's doing we've got a real problem,'' 
Rep. Ray LaHood, R-Ill., said after the rank and file held a long 
closed-door meeting on Thursday afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a hard job,'' he added.  
</P>
<P>
	The Republican majority is 222-211, with one independent who  
customarily votes with the Democrats and one vacancy. That means 
that on any issue, five GOP defections can deadlock the House and a 
sixth can deliver control of the floor to the Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	And Democrats, eager to underscore every Republican weakness in  
hopes of gaining control of the House in 2000, aren't likely to 
help much. That's particularly true on GOP-drafted spending bills, 
about which Democratic leader Dick Gephardt said recently, ``This 
is their budget and I assume they're going to implement it. If they 
want to change it, we're happy to go to the floor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In public, Republicans seek to shift the focus to their one  
solid accomplishment of the past week, passage of a measure to 
safeguard Social Security surpluses. They also blame some of the 
week's problems on the Democrats, who they say reneged on promises 
to deliver votes. 
</P>
<P>
	But inside the closed-door meeting, according to several sources  
who spoke on condition of anonymity, the Republicans discussed the 
need to work cohesively to save their majority. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. George Nethercutt of Washington reminded everyone that he  
was in Congress because he had defeated former Rep. Thomas Foley, 
then speaker in a Democratic-controlled House. 
</P>
<P>
	One lawmaker who attended the meeting said Nethercutt cautioned  
that if they weren't careful, Republicans would end up ``creating 
the media appearance that the leadership is ineffective.'' That, 
Nethercutt said, was precisely what allowed him to beat Foley six 
years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The GOP whip, Tom DeLay of Texas, according to several  
participants, said punishment of rebels isn't feasible. But these 
participants said he added that any chairman who defies the 
leadership on a range of key procedural votes should resign his or 
her committee or subcommittee chairmanship. 
</P>
<P>
	That comment seemed aimed, in part at least, at the six who  
broke ranks and signed onto the Democratic effort to force campaign 
finance legislation to the floor. Most of them hold subcommittee 
chairmanships; no offers of resignation were reported. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the six, Chris Shays of Connecticut, said earlier in the  
week that DeLay had offered to help anyone who decided to challenge 
him in a Republican primary. DeLay's office denied it. 
</P>
<P>
	The situation on the floor seemed to lurch from one problem to  
another for the Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	A spending bill for agriculture was pulled after two days of  
delaying tactics by a small group of conservatives. 
</P>
<P>
	``Leadership believes it is more important to stick to the  
calendar, even when that may mean sacrificing good policy 
(controlling spending) and great politics (saving 100% of Social 
Security),'' Tom Coburn of Oklahoma wrote fellow Republicans in 
explanation of his actions. 
</P>
<P>
	GOP moderates worry about the spending bills yet to come, but  
their concern is there won't be enough money. 
</P>
<P>
	Reps. Mike Castle of Delaware and John Porter of Illinois wrote  
the president and the House GOP leadership suggesting that ``talks 
begin immediately on a budget and appropriations agreement for this 
year to avoid a likely impasse'' this fall. 
</P>
<P>
	Spending bills aside, a major defense measure was shelved when  
it became clear the GOP leaders couldn't prevail on a routine 
parliamentary vote to set rules for floor debate. 
</P>
<P>
	As approved in committee, the bill would cut off money for the  
air war in Kosovo after Sept. 30. Clinton threatened a veto, and 
Hastert agreed to remove the offending provision without a debate. 
</P>
<P>
	That infuriated GOP critics of the Yugoslavia campaign. In  
addition, some Western Republicans were angry that the leaders had 
accommodated environmental-minded lawmakers on another part of the 
bill. 
</P>
<P>
	And some Democrats complained that they wouldn't be allowed a  
vote on a proposal for dealing with alleged Chinese espionage. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, a measure designed to showcase Republican resolve  
in beefing up the military was put off until later in the year. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll have a long discussion and debate on Kosovo and a debate  
on China'' when Congress returns in June, Hastert said. 
</P>
<P>
	Given the events of the week, two other minor measures that  
Republicans had hoped to pass never made it to the floor. 
</P>
<P>
	On campaign finance, Shays and five other Republicans defied the  
leadership and signed a Democratic-drafted petition to force 
legislation to the floor as soon as possible. 
</P>
<P>
	Hastert offered a date of mid-September, but advocates of the  
measure say that will be too late to allow them to exert enough 
pressure in the Senate to overcome a threatened filibuster. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
