<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Officer Honored in China Spy Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- An intelligence officer who raised concerns in  
1995 about China's alleged theft of nuclear secrets and contends 
now he was thwarted by superiors received a special award Friday 
from Energy Secretary Bill Richardson. 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson, in a brief ceremony, described the official, Notra  
Trulock, as ``a man who was persistent and most importantly 
contributed to the national security of this country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The award for ``a special act of service'' included a check for  
$10,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Trulock, deputy director of the Energy Department's Office of  
Intelligence, had praise for Richardson. ``His leadership and 
courage really did turn this thing around for us and got us onto 
the path we're on today,'' said Trulock. 
</P>
<P>
	Trulock last week told a Senate hearing that for much of 1997 he  
had been thwarted by senior Energy Department officials in trying 
to press his case for tougher security at nuclear weapons labs. He 
also said he had been blocked from testifying before Congress on 
his analysis on Chinese espionage at the labs. 
</P>
<P>
	He testified that as recently as late 1998 some administration  
officials continued to ``discredit'' his analysis that China had 
obtained significant nuclear secrets from the weapons labs. 
</P>
<P>
	``These officials sought to discredit the analysis ... as  
pessimistic,'' said Trulock, adding that be believed some of the 
critics ``had been motivated by a desire to limit the political 
damage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson took over as energy secretary in September of 1998.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
