<DOCNO> APW19990528.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 13:11:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Just Where IS Silicon Valley? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- There's no road sign reading ``Welcome  
to Silicon Valley.'' No arch spans the highway leading into the 
region. Even those Internet map systems can't locate it exactly. 
</P>
<P>
	While everybody knows pretty much what you mean when you mention  
the high-tech region south of San Francisco, it's driving 
cartographers nuts. 
</P>
<P>
	Compass Maps, a Modesto, Calif., company, is taking a shot at  
drawing a line around the region, and plans to release a new map as 
early as next year. 
</P>
<P>
	But it has been a struggle.  
</P>
<P>
	Does Silicon Valley include Menlo Park? Or Santa Cruz? Or the  
Sunol Grade? What about Union City or Milpitas or Morgan Hill? 
</P>
<P>
	The company's current Silicon Valley map, introduced in 1993, is  
still available. Unfortunately, in a region that shifts like the 
desert sands, it's sadly out of date. 
</P>
<P>
	Compass is talking with city and county planners about new  
streets, and also with business groups, chambers of commerce and 
other agencies with a stake in what makes up Silicon Valley. 
</P>
<P>
	Business traveler Jim Austin, waiting for a flight at San Jose  
International Airport,'' says he doesn't really care what the area 
is called. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just tell me where the meeting is and how to get there.''  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990528.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 15:48:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hillary Readies for New York </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Hold on to your hats, New Yorkers! If  
Hillary Rodham Clinton enters the Senate race, it could be the 
state's wildest ever -- a sitting first lady pitted against New York 
City's mayor in a campaign that one political veteran predicts 
would be ``the all-time meanest, nastiest race ever in New York.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What started as a lark several months ago for Mrs. Clinton has  
taken wing as an almost-ready-for-prime-time campaign for the 
Senate seat being vacated next year by Democrat Daniel Patrick 
Moynihan. 
</P>
<P>
	She already has called 200 New York politicians for  
heart-to-hearts, is learning the difference between Owego and 
Oswego, has had New York luminaries for sleepovers in the Lincoln 
Bedroom and apparently wants to spend her summer vacation in the 
wilds of the Adirondacks or the windswept vistas of eastern Long 
Island. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton has gone so far as to ask state Democratic  
Chairwoman Judith Hope to scout out living rooms in rural upstate 
New York where the folks might want to share coffee and cookies 
with a first lady. 
</P>
<P>
	President and Mrs. Clinton are vacationing in Florida over the  
Memorial Day weekend. When they return, top advisers say, she will 
either announce she is not running or press ahead, forming an 
exploratory committee in late June or early July and kicking off a 
full-fledged candidacy sometime in the fall or later. 
</P>
<P>
	Hope and other advisers expect the Yale Law School-educated  
woman -- who has never worked, lived or studied in New York -- to 
enter the race, which could pit her against the quintessential New 
Yorker -- New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani. 
</P>
<P>
	His fans, and enemies, say he is as tough as they come -- a  
former federal prosecutor not known for his social skills. 
</P>
<P>
	``Giuliani, because of his nature, will throw every vile charge  
he can dream up at her,'' said former New York City Mayor Edward 
Koch, a Democrat. ``I think she can beat him, but it will be a very 
tough race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other prominent New York Democrats agree with Koch.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think Rudy and company will fight a pretty nasty battle,''  
said former New York City Mayor David Dinkins, who beat Giuliani in 
1989 only to lose to him in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	``It could be the all-time meanest, nastiest race ever in New  
York,'' state Comptroller H. Carl McCall said. 
</P>
<P>
	New York's last Senate race, in 1998, was called one of the  
ugliest the state has seen, marked by negative advertising and 
name-callling. The Republican incument, Alfonse D'Amato, called his 
Democratic opponent, Charles Schumer a ``putzhead.'' Schumer, who 
repeatedly challenged D'Amato's ethics, won that contest. 
</P>
<P>
	Should Mrs. Clinton run, New York's political pros say she will  
not only face a brutal campaign, but could wind up hurting 
Democrats elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	And, on the Republican side, one veteran GOP operative thinks  
the price of beating her may be so high as to leave any GOP winner 
with a ``Pyrrhic victory.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``She's going to take advantage of how she's perceived right  
now, which is as first lady, mother, wronged wife, feminist 
champion, humanitarian, martyr. She's going to run as St. Joan of 
Arc ... Eleanor Roosevelt reincarnated,'' GOP consultant Jay 
Severin said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The sobering news for Republicans is that anybody who plans to  
beat her is going to have to knock her off every one of those 
pedestals ... and the cost of doing that is very high,'' the 
Republican strategist added. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to being attacked as a carpetbagger, Mrs. Clinton  
will face questions again over Whitewater, Travelgate, her good 
fortune investing in cattle futures, the billing practices of her 
old law firm and her husband's infidelity. 
</P>
<P>
	She got a taste of that Wednesday when CBS' Dan Rather asked her  
what she would answer when asked: ``Why are you still with this 
man?'' 
</P>
<P>
	She noted they had been married for almost 24 years.  
</P>
<P>
	There is also talk among some party stalwarts that by running a  
high-profile and expensive race in heavily Democratic New York, 
Mrs. Clinton could damage Vice President Al Gore's chances of 
moving up to the White House and even the party's chances of taking 
back Congress. She is considered one of the party's most effective 
campaigners. 
</P>
<P>
	``New York is one place where he needs her less,'' McCall said.  
``He'd rather have her in Nebraska.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the carpetbagger charges will almost force her to stay in  
New York, William Cunningham, a former Moynihan campaign manager, 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``If she runs in New York, she will not be available to campaign  
in other critical states and districts. That affects not only Gore, 
but the whole effort to take back the House,'' Cunningham 
concluded. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican Severin said he expects a ``horribly fascinating''  
show that will draw plenty of attention. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like a car wreck. You don't want to look, but you can't  
help it,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990528.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 14:31:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jailed Teen Says Cop Fathered Baby </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OCALA, Fla. (AP) -- A 17-year-old mother was jailed for eight  
hours until she identified the father of her baby. 
</P>
<P>
	The girl had been called into court to answer questions about a  
police officer charged with having sex with her while she was 
underage. 
</P>
<P>
	At first, she told the judge it was none of his business who  
fathered her 5-month-old daughter. Circuit Judge Carven Angel found 
her in contempt of court Wednesday and ordered her jailed for 179 
days or until she answered whether 36-year-old Cpl. Salvador 
Armando Garcia was the father. 
</P>
<P>
	She finally identified Garcia as the father. She said she  
relented because prosecutors had implied she could lose custody of 
her child. 
</P>
<P>
	The girl said that her relationship with Garcia was consensual  
and that she led him to believe she was 19. 
</P>
<P>
	Garcia's lawyer had no comment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990528.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 14:01:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hillary Readies for New York </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Hold on to your hats, New Yorkers! If  
Hillary Rodham Clinton enters the Senate race, it could be the 
state's wildest ever -- a sitting first lady pitted against New York 
City's mayor in a campaign that one political veteran predicts 
would be ``the all-time meanest, nastiest race ever in New York.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What started as a lark several months ago for Mrs. Clinton has  
taken wing as an almost-ready-for-prime-time campaign for the 
Senate seat being vacated next year by Democrat Daniel Patrick 
Moynihan. 
</P>
<P>
	She already has called 200 New York politicians for  
heart-to-hearts, is learning the difference between Owego and 
Oswego, has had New York luminaries for sleepovers in the Lincoln 
Bedroom and apparently wants to spend her summer vacation in the 
wilds of the Adirondacks or the windswept vistas of eastern Long 
Island. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton has gone so far as to ask state Democratic  
Chairwoman Judith Hope to scout out living rooms in rural upstate 
New York where the folks might want to share coffee and cookies 
with a first lady. 
</P>
<P>
	President and Mrs. Clinton are vacationing in Florida over the  
Memorial Day weekend. When they return, top advisers say, she will 
either announce she is not running or press ahead, forming an 
exploratory committee in late June or early July and kicking off a 
full-fledged candidacy sometime in the fall or later. 
</P>
<P>
	Hope and other advisers expect the Yale Law School-educated  
woman -- who has never worked, lived or studied in New York -- to 
enter the race, which could pit her against the quintessential New 
Yorker -- New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani. 
</P>
<P>
	His fans, and enemies, say he is as tough as they come -- a  
former federal prosecutor not known for his social skills. 
</P>
<P>
	``Giuliani, because of his nature, will throw every vile charge  
he can dream up at her,'' said former New York City Mayor Edward 
Koch, a Democrat. ``I think she can beat him, but it will be a very 
tough race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other prominent New York Democrats agree with Koch.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think Rudy and company will fight a pretty nasty battle,''  
said former New York City Mayor David Dinkins, who beat Giuliani in 
1989 only to lose to him in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	``It could be the all-time meanest, nastiest race ever in New  
York,'' state Comptroller H. Carl McCall said. 
</P>
<P>
	New York's last Senate race, in 1998, was called one of the  
ugliest the state has seen, marked by negative advertising and 
name-callling. The Republican incument, Alfonse D'Amato, called his 
Democratic opponent, Charles Schumer a ``putzhead.'' Schumer, who 
repeatedly challenged D'Amato's ethics, won that contest. 
</P>
<P>
	Should Mrs. Clinton run, New York's political pros say she will  
not only face a brutal campaign, but could wind up hurting 
Democrats elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	And, on the Republican side, one veteran GOP operative thinks  
the price of beating her may be so high as to leave any GOP winner 
with a ``Pyrrhic victory.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``She's going to take advantage of how she's perceived right  
now, which is as first lady, mother, wronged wife, feminist 
champion, humanitarian, martyr. She's going to run as St. Joan of 
Arc ... Eleanor Roosevelt reincarnated,'' GOP consultant Jay 
Severin said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The sobering news for Republicans is that anybody who plans to  
beat her is going to have to knock her off every one of those 
pedestals ... and the cost of doing that is very high,'' the 
Republican strategist added. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to being attacked as a carpetbagger, Mrs. Clinton  
will face questions again over Whitewater, Travelgate, her good 
fortune investing in cattle futures, the billing practices of her 
old law firm and her husband's infidelity. 
</P>
<P>
	She got a taste of that Wednesday when CBS' Dan Rather asked her  
what she would answer when asked: ``Why are you still with this 
man?'' 
</P>
<P>
	She noted they had been married for almost 24 years.  
</P>
<P>
	There is also talk among some party stalwarts that by running a  
high-profile and expensive race in heavily Democratic New York, 
Mrs. Clinton could damage Vice President Al Gore's chances of 
moving up to the White House and even the party's chances of taking 
back Congress. She is considered one of the party's most effective 
campaigners. 
</P>
<P>
	``New York is one place where he needs her less,'' McCall said.  
``He'd rather have her in Nebraska.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the carpetbagger charges will almost force her to stay in  
New York, William Cunningham, a former Moynihan campaign manager, 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``If she runs in New York, she will not be available to campaign  
in other critical states and districts. That affects not only Gore, 
but the whole effort to take back the House,'' Cunningham 
concluded. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican Severin said he expects a ``horribly fascinating''  
show that will draw plenty of attention. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like a car wreck. You don't want to look, but you can't  
help it,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
