<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sinatra Kidnapper Appeal Shot Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A man who kidnapped Frank Sinatra's son in  
1963 cannot make any money from a movie about the crime, a state 
appeals court ruled. 
</P>
<P>
	In a 3-0 ruling, the 2nd District Court of Appeal on Thursday  
rejected Barry Keenan's challenge to a 1986 California law that 
requires convicted felons to pay their victims when they sell their 
stories. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling was issued only a day after the case was argued.  
</P>
<P>
	Frank Sinatra Jr.'s lawyer, Richard Specter, said he was  
gratified by the speed and unanimity of the ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	``It demonstrates that the Legislature knew what it was doing,''  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Keenan was the leader of three kidnappers who abducted a  
19-year-old Sinatra from Harrah's Casino at Lake Tahoe in 1963. He 
was released unharmed after a ransom payment. All three kidnappers 
were caught and convicted. 
</P>
<P>
	Keenan, who blamed his actions on drugs and alcohol, spent less  
than five years in prison and now is a land developer in 
Mississippi. 
</P>
<P>
	After a magazine interview with Keenan was published last year,  
he and the writer sold the movie rights to Columbia Pictures. But 
Sinatra sued the kidnappers, the writer and Columbia and got a 
court order preventing the studio from paying Keenan. 
</P>
<P>
	The court ruling bars the studio from paying Keenan and requires  
it to set any payments aside for his victim. The court rejected 
Keenan's argument that the law violates free speech by suppressing 
criminals' accounts of their past. 
</P>
<P>
	Keenan's lawyer, Stephen Rohde, was not available for comment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
