<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> PG&AMP;E Eettles Pacific Blackout Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Pacific Gas &AMP; Electric Co. will pay  
$440,000 to operators of an electric grid system to settle charges 
connected with the massive power failure that blacked out San 
Francisco December 8. 
</P>
<P>
	The quasi-public state Independent System Operator's board  
approved the settlement on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The money will go to ISO's operating budget and will help fund  
studies to devise improvements to the high-voltage system serving 
San Francisco, the Peninsula and San Diego, areas with transmission 
problems. 
</P>
<P>
	As an interim measure, PG&AMP;E has agreed to make improvements in  
employee training, equipment maintenance and operating procedures 
suggested by the ISO. 
</P>
<P>
	The $440,000 fine is the most the year-old ISO was authorized to  
fine the utility. It soon will ask the Federal Energy Regulatory 
Commission for greater fining authority. 
</P>
<P>
	The state Public Utilities Commission also has investigated the  
blackout and issued its own report, although it has so far not 
sought to levy any penalty against PG&AMP;E. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
