<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> ''Topkapi'' Dagger on Display in DC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Actor Peter Ustinov won an Oscar for his  
performance, but a centuries-old, jeweled dagger was the real star 
of the movie ``Topkapi'' 35 years ago -- and will be the centerpiece 
of a Turkish art show visiting the United States next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Clothes and jewelry will join paintings, rare carpets and other  
works of art from Topkapi Palace, once the center of the 700-year 
Ottoman empire and now a major tourist attraction in Istanbul. 
</P>
<P>
	The exhibit, called ``Palace of Gold and Light,'' will open in  
the Corcoran Gallery of Art, Washington's oldest art museum, on 
March 1, 2000. Then it goes on to the San Diego Museum of Art and 
the Museum of Art in Fort Lauderdale, Fla., where it will stay 
until Jan. 14, 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many of the objects have never left Turkey,'' said Richard C.  
Barkley, former U.S. ambassador to Ankara, announcing the show 
Thursday at the Turkish Embassy in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	The dagger itself has previously made a brief trip to this  
country. 
</P>
<P>
	Some film lovers still remember the look in Melina Mercouri's  
eyes as she gazed at the giant emeralds in the dagger's handle. 
There's also an eight-sided emerald cover at the top that conceals 
a small watch, and there are two rows of diamonds on both sides. 
</P>
<P>
	It was made as a fitting gift for the Persian King Nadir Shah,  
who had a taste for jewels. He invaded India, sacked Delhi and 
returned with the Peacock Throne and the Koh-i-Noor diamond. But 
assassins got him before the dagger could be presented in 1747. 
Half a century of civil war followed in what is now Iran. 
</P>
<P>
	In the film the dagger was the object of thrilling but  
ultimately failed burglary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
