<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> United Customer Service OKs Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- United Airlines' 19,000 newly organized customer  
service employees have overwhelmingly ratified a contract that 
provides pay raises and signing bonuses. 
</P>
<P>
	About 70 percent of those voting during the past few weeks  
approved the one-year pact the airline negotiated with the 
International Association of Machinists and Aerospace Workers, 
United spokesman Joe Hopkins said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement, which was reached last month, covers ticket  
counter workers, reservationists, air freight agents and others. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are pleased that this contract has been ratified,'' United  
chairman and CEO Gerald Greenwald said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the agreement, the airline will eliminate one of its lower  
wage tiers. That will mean an immediate 14.5 percent pay increase 
for nearly half of the 19,000 workers. Other workers will get a 
$750 bonus when the contract is signed. 
</P>
<P>
	All of the workers will get a 5.5 percent pay increase next  
April 13. 
</P>
<P>
	The passenger service employees voted last July to join the  
machinists union, which also represents United's mechanics and ramp 
employees. 
</P>
<P>
	A machinists union official did not immediately return a  
telephone message Friday seeking comment. 

</P>
</TEXT>
