<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cleveland Voucher Plan Struck Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- In a partial victory for the state's  
teachers' unions, the Ohio Supreme Court has struck down 
Cleveland's school voucher program because of a technicality in the 
way the program was written into law. 
</P>
<P>
	But the ruling Thursday also gave backers of school vouchers  
cause for hope -- the court said the program does not breach the 
separation of church and state, as union leaders had argued. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll take any victory the court will give us,'' said Michael  
Billirakis, president of the 108,000-member Ohio Education 
Association, which was joined by the Ohio Federation of Teachers in 
opposing the voucher program. 
</P>
<P>
	The program provides tax-funded scholarships to poor students in  
Cleveland so they can attend private schools, including religious 
schools. This year, it provided aid to about 4,000 children. 
</P>
<P>
	In striking down the program, the high court said its creation  
in 1995 violated the Ohio Constitution's ``single-subject rule,'' 
which requires the Legislature to address only one issue in each 
bill. The legislation establishing the voucher program was included 
in the state's 1995 general spending bill. 
</P>
<P>
	That budget bill contained 383 amendments, and the court has  
allowed various subjects to be combined in a single bill for 
``practical, rational or legitimate reasons.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But a program that could prove contentious or raise  
constitutional questions needed to be the subject of a separate 
bill, the court ruled. 
</P>
<P>
	The court ruled that for the most part, the program doesn't  
violate the separation of church and state. 
</P>
<P>
	``We conclude that the school voucher program has a secular  
legislative purpose, does not have the primary effect of advancing 
religion, and does not excessively entangle government with 
religion,'' Justice Paul Pfeifer wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Bob Taft said he would support reinstating the program --  
which would involve having lawmakers rewrite the legislation to 
abide by the court's ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have supported the Cleveland scholarship program as a pilot  
project and do not believe it should be terminated due to a 
procedural flaw in legislation,'' Taft said in a prepared release. 
</P>
<P>
	But Billirakis, who argues that the voucher program siphons  
money from public schools, said the unions would fight any attempt 
to revive the program in the Legislature. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they come back with separate piece of legislation, we will  
hold them accountable. It's something we will vehemently oppose 
legally, legislatively, anyway we can,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	House Speaker Jo Ann Davidson said Davidson, R-Reynoldsburg,  
said the Legislature would have to act soon if it chooses to set up 
another program. Lawmakers want to recess in July after finishing 
work on the $39.55 billion budget. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers created the voucher program amid public concern about  
Cleveland public schools' high dropout rates and low student test 
scores. 
</P>
<P>
	In April, Florida became the nation's only statewide program to  
let students attend private schools at taxpayer expense. Vermont 
has allowed tax dollars to be spent for private school tuition in 
rural areas for more than a century, while Maine has a similar 
program. Milwaukee also has started a voucher program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
