<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IRA Reveals Secretly Buried Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- The Irish Republican Army began  
revealing the whereabouts of nine secretly buried victims on 
Friday, a gesture designed to quell the protests of long-suffering 
relatives and build good will at a critical moment in peacemaking. 
</P>
<P>
	At dawn in a medieval graveyard on the Irish Republic's border  
with Northern Ireland, police found what they thought were the 
remains of Eamon Molloy -- a Belfast IRA member who disappeared in 
1975 after being branded an informer. 
</P>
<P>
	The remains, evidently dug up from their original resting place,  
were left in a new casket lying behind shrubs amid the 
lichen-covered headstones. 
</P>
<P>
	Irish police also began searching other remote border locations  
after a victims' remains commission, formally established Friday by 
the British and Irish governments, confirmed it had received 
precise information from the IRA via Catholic priests and other 
intermediaries. 
</P>
<P>
	The IRA has promised to reveal the resting places of nine people  
the outlawed organization killed between 1972 and 1981, all 
Catholics. 
</P>
<P>
	A group of relatives, Families for the Disappeared, have  
demanded this since the IRA called its first lengthy cease-fire in 
1994. The IRA's current truce has lasted 22 months. 
</P>
<P>
	``This day is far, far too long in coming. You feel like you can  
finally start to grieve,'' said Helen McKendry, whose mother Jean -- 
the widowed parent of 10 children -- was abducted by the IRA from 
their Belfast home in 1972 and killed. Her children, who initially 
thought their mother had abandoned them, ended up in separate 
foster homes. 
</P>
<P>
	But McKendry and her husband, Seamus, waited in vain Friday for  
a phone call from the police. Seamus McKendry founded Families of 
the Disappeared on behalf of 19 families who believe the IRA killed 
their vanished relatives. The IRA denies responsibility for the 10 
other people. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this week, the British and Irish parliaments passed laws  
ensuring that no evidence connected with the graves could be used 
to convict IRA members. 
</P>
<P>
	A Catholic priest counseling the Molloy family, the Rev. Patrick  
McCafferty, said few of the families of the missing were angered by 
this amnesty. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those who killed these nine people may have escaped justice in  
this world, but they will come to meet their maker,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The IRA has moved on this long-simmering issue at a time when  
the British and Irish governments and the Ulster Unionists, 
Northern Ireland's major pro-British Protestant party, have been 
demanding that the IRA start to disarm in support of the 1998 peace 
accord. 
</P>
<P>
	Because the IRA refuses, the Ulster Unionists are refusing to  
form a new Protestant-Catholic government that would include the 
IRA-linked Sinn Fein party. The British government has set what it 
calls an ``absolute deadline'' of June 30 for local politicians to 
form the government. 
</P>
<P>
	Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams emphasized Friday that he  
considered the IRA's initiative a matter of ``correcting a human 
rights wrong,'' and hoped it showed people that the entire Sinn 
Fein-IRA movement was committed to reconciliation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
