<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 05:11:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft Calls Caldera Claim Bogus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Neither consumers nor personal computer  
makers were hurt by Microsoft's licensing practices for the MS-DOS 
operating system in the early 1990s, a Microsoft attorney argued. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard Klapper said Thursday that the contention by Caldera  
Inc. of Orem, Utah, that Microsoft deliberately used licensing to 
quash the competing DR-DOS system is bogus. 
</P>
<P>
	``Where was competition hurt here?'' he asked U.S. District  
Court Judge Dee Benson, who is hearing Caldera's antitrust case 
against the much bigger software company. 
</P>
<P>
	Caldera now owns DR-DOS, an operating system that in the late  
1980s and early 1990s was gaining a toehold against MS-DOS in the 
personal computer market. An operating system controls the basic 
functions of a computer. 
</P>
<P>
	Retail customers could have bought DR-DOS in stores, Klapper  
said. ``It was pretty clear they didn't want DR-DOS.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And manufacturers chose one of three kinds of MS-DOS licenses  
from Microsoft rather than DR-DOS, a product of DRI and later 
Novell, he said. ``They had choices and they made them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft is asking the judge to dismiss Caldera's claim that it  
kept a stranglehold on the personal computer operating system 
market with its licenses. 
</P>
<P>
	The licensing claim is one of nine aspects of Caldera's case  
that Microsoft has asked the judge to throw out. Benson is hearing 
arguments on the nine motions this week and during June. 
</P>
<P>
	Caldera, financed by former Novell chairman Ray Noorda, bought  
DR-DOS from Novell in 1996 and promptly filed the antitrust 
lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	Novell had stopped selling DR-DOS for personal computers in  
1994, but Caldera chief executive Bryan Sparks says he and Noorda 
wanted Microsoft held accountable for what they claim was 
anticompetitive behavior by a monopolist. 
</P>
<P>
	Caldera claims that personal computer manufacturers -- the  
biggest customers for operating systems -- were coerced to buy only 
Microsoft's MS-DOS. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the most economical licensing arrangement, manufacturers  
had to pay Microsoft a royalty whether they loaded MS-DOS or not, 
which made purchases of DR-DOS unlikely, Caldera says. 
</P>
<P>
	And the Redmond, Wash., company also used tactics that resulted  
in manufacturers ending their MS-DOS licensing periods with large 
account balances that could only be erased by renewing the 
licenses, Caldera alleges. 
</P>
<P>
	``A customer who had any crazy ideas about going with a  
competitor knew that his account was in jeopardy,'' Caldera 
attorney Stephen Susman argued on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Few manufacturers that signed Microsoft's restrictive licenses  
ever did business with DR-DOS, Caldera says. 
</P>
<P>
	Susman told the judge that it's silly for Microsoft to claim  
consumers could have bought DR-DOS if they preferred it over MS-DOS 
since retail sales are almost all software upgrades. Since the 
computers originally came with MS-DOS, consumers were unlikely to 
upgrade with DR-DOS. 
</P>
<P>
	Klapper said the fact Microsoft offered three kinds of licenses  
indicates it was not trying to crush DR-DOS. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, more than half of the licenses required manufacturers  
to pay only for each copy of Microsoft's operating system that they 
put in PCs or a line of PCs, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	DRI and Novell had frequent chances to go after manufacturing  
customers as their Microsoft licenses expired, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Klapper said Microsoft was using its licensing practices before  
and after DR-DOS was a competitive threat, but the judge was 
dubious. 
</P>
<P>
	He noted that the per-processor licenses -- the ones Caldera  
claims were anticompetitive -- made up the vast majority of 
Microsoft's MS-DOS licenses in precisely the years DR-DOS was 
competing against it. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge suggested that evidence alone may be sufficient for  
him to reject Microsoft's motion to dismiss and instead allow a 
jury to hear the evidence. 
</P>
<P>
	A jury trial is scheduled for January.  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990528.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 15:43:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Racer Stewart Going for the Double </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Imagine driving from Los Angeles to Denver  
in one day. In heavy traffic, with other drivers tailgating and 
zigzagging every which way. In a car with no air conditioning or 
power steering. And no bathroom breaks. 
</P>
<P>
	Welcome to Tony Stewart's world.  
</P>
<P>
	Stewart, a former Indy Racing League champion who's now NASCAR's  
hottest rookie, will try to become the first driver to complete the 
Indianapolis 500 and the Coca-Cola 600 in Concord, N.C., on the 
same day. 
</P>
<P>
	That's 1,100 miles in under 12 hours, 600 laps and a  
mind-numbing 2,400 left turns. 
</P>
<P>
	``I like staying busy and I like being in race cars,'' he said.  
``The more I'm in a race car, the happier I am.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 28-year-old driver switched to NASCAR's Winston Cup circuit  
after three years of racing full time in the IRL, and has done 
better than anyone expected. He's had five top-10 finishes in his 
first 12 races, won one poll and is seventh in the point standings. 
</P>
<P>
	But there's something about Indy that keeps drawing him back.  
He's always had a fast car in the 500 -- he started on the pole as a 
rookie in 1996 and has led a total of 109 laps -- but he has been 
knocked out early by mechanical problems. 
</P>
<P>
	It's his hometown track, too. He grew up 45 miles south in  
Columbus, Ind. 
</P>
<P>
	``To have the opportunity to run at the Indianapolis Motor  
Speedway and try to win the Indianapolis 500, I wasn't going to 
pass that up,'' he said. ``If we don't win it this year, I 
guarantee we'll probably do it again next year. I'm not giving up 
until we win the Indianapolis 500.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A year or two of this might make him reconsider, though.  
</P>
<P>
	First, there's the schedule. He's flown between Indianapolis and  
Concord so much the past two weeks he's practically on a first-name 
basis with the air traffic controllers. He's missed practices at 
each track, and didn't even have enough time to take photos with 
his crew after qualifying at Indy. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, he'll start from the eighth row in the Indy 500 and  
pray for clear skies and a clean race because he's out of there at 
3:30 p.m. CDT no matter what. 
</P>
<P>
	A helicopter will take him to the Indianapolis airport where The  
Home Depot, his sponsor, will have its private jet waiting for the 
50-minute flight to North Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	He'll get intravenous fluids on the plane and maybe squeeze in a  
little nap. When he touches down in Charlotte, N.C., he'll be 
whisked to another helicopter for the ride to Lowe's Motor 
Speedway. 
</P>
<P>
	Then he'll jump into his stock car and start in the 27th spot  
for another five hours of driving. 
</P>
<P>
	``If anybody's capable of doing it and has the endurance to do  
it, it's Tony,'' said Andy Card, one of the co-owners of Stewart's 
IRL team. 
</P>
<P>
	Only two other drivers have attempted the double. John Andretti  
was the first in 1994, but he crashed in the Coca-Cola 600 and 
didn't finish the race. Robby Gordon's attempt in 1997 was rained 
out in Indianapolis. 
</P>
<P>
	Even if he can survive the punishing schedule, Stewart still has  
to change cars. Driving an Indy car and a stock car isn't like 
switching between a Ford and Honda -- it's more like a Ferrari and 
an 18-wheeler. 
</P>
<P>
	``In this day and age, it's more specialized. Every race car  
driver in every series is a specialty driver now,'' Stewart said. 
``You don't see the A.J. Foyts and the Mario Andrettis, the guys 
that used to do it all. That day is long gone and there are only a 
couple of us that ever try to do it anymore.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart is used to pulling double duty, though. Quadruple duty  
even. When he was racing in USAC, he once drove in four events in 
one day. There were countless weekends when he'd run a midget car 
on Friday night, a sprint car Saturday and a silver-crown car on 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The more he gets to do it, the sharper his skills are,'' said  
Larry Curry, crew chief of Stewart's Indy team. ``He is an absolute 
legitimate contender to win both of these races.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If he wins at Indianapolis, though, the party will have to wait.  
Stewart said he'll have time to take the traditional swig of milk, 
a few photos and that's about it before he takes off for Charlotte. 
</P>
<P>
	That's OK, Card and Curry said. They'll whoop it up for him.  
</P>
<P>
	``I told Tony I'd stay in Victory Lane until Monday,'' Card  
said. ``And if he wins this thing, they better look out in 
Charlotte because here he comes.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
