<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Suit Threatens $200M in Dairy Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A dispute between New Mexico dairy farmers and  
the Agriculture Department over a $200 million aid package could 
jeopardize scores of emergency payments for dairy farmers across 
the country. 
</P>
<P>
	The New Mexico farmers last week filed a lawsuit in federal  
court in Albuquerque to stop the distribution of the payments. 
Specifically, they want USDA to change the formula it used to 
determine the payments, asserting the larger producers, like those 
in New Mexico, should get larger payments. 
</P>
<P>
	Payments are capped at $5,000 for the country's 116,000 dairy  
farmers. 
</P>
<P>
	The debate comes at a time when dairy farmers have seen their  
prices slip. Several pieces of legislation are pending in hopes of 
preventing the industry from undergoing the price slump that hit 
commodities and hogs last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The dispute also pits large scale farmers against smaller  
farmers at a time when many have complained about the erosion of 
small family farms. 
</P>
<P>
	``The secretary kind of divided us between two different  
categories of dairy industry,'' Sharon Lombardi, executive director 
of the Dairy Producers of New Mexico said Thursday. ``We should all 
be treated equally.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We really have no desire to hurt producers of any size,''  
added Ben Yale, an Ohio lawyer representing the New Mexico farmers. 
``We're concerned that the secretary without authorization from 
Congress is starting to create a whole new dairy policy that 
threatens the type of dairy that goes on in the West.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The $200 million in aid for dairy farmers was included in a $6  
billion farm bailout package passed by Congress last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Sign-up for the payments ended last Friday, and the agency was  
expected to soon announce the disbursement of checks. It is unclear 
how the latest legal action will affect those plans. 
</P>
<P>
	USDA spokesman Andy Solomon said the agency could not comment on  
pending legal action, but said ``we structured this program so that 
it could be of maximum help to small and medium dairy producers in 
need. We believe we did the right thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under USDA's guidelines for issuing the payments, farmers can  
get paid a maximum of $5,000. That amount is the equivalent to the 
approximate production of a 150-cow herd. 
</P>
<P>
	The dispute arose because the 155 dairy farmers in New Mexico  
produce significantly more milk than that. The average farmer has a 
1,100-cow herd. Collectively, the New Mexico farmers, who rank 10th 
in milk production, produce about 4.2 billion pounds annually of 
the 160 billion pounds of milk produced nationwide, Yale said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dairy farmers pay federally mandated assessments according to  
the amount they produce so the aid payments shouldn't be different, 
Yale said. 
</P>
<P>
	As for the smaller producing farms, ``it would reduce some of  
their payments but the amount isn't going to make or break the 
survival of the small dairy farmer,'' Yale said. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Milk Producers Federation, while offering no  
comment on the lawsuit, had recommendations similar to USDA's final 
rule. The NMPF wanted to cap payments at $6,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
