<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Elf Aquitaine Bids for Saga Petroleum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OSLO, Norway (AP) -- The French energy concern Elf Aquitaine  
today made a $2.16 billion cash buyout offer for Norway's Saga 
Petroleum ASA, which already is considering an all-stock bid from 
state-controlled Norsk Hydro ASA. 
</P>
<P>
	The offer from Elf Aquitane came a day after Norsk Hydro made a  
deal with Saga's largest shareholder, the Norwegian state oil 
company Statoil ASA, that would split Saga Petroleum's assets 
between them as part of a takeover. 
</P>
<P>
	Elf is offering about 17 billion kroner, or $2.16 billion, in  
cash while Norsk Hydro wants to swap one of its own shares for 
three Saga shares. 
</P>
<P>
	Norsk Hydro's offer was valued at about $2.18 billion when it  
was announced May 10, but Elf Aquitane said its offer is 8 percent 
higher than the current value of Norsk Hydro's bid. 
</P>
<P>
	Elf Aquitane, France's largest industrial company, entered the  
bidding with the blessing of Saga's management, which had wanted 
alternatives to Norsk Hydro's offer. Saga had objected to political 
pressures to keep the company in Norwegian hands, saying its 
shareholders had the right to the best possible offers. 
</P>
<P>
	Norsk Hydro would not immediately comment on Elf's counteroffer.  
Norsk Hydro's offer was contingent on 90 percent of Saga's 
shareholders accepting the bid, while Elf will settle for 67 
percent acceptance. 
</P>
<P>
	Elf, which has operated in Norway since 1965, would allow Saga  
Petroleum to continue to operate under its own name, and with 
considerable autonomy. 
</P>
<P>
	Saga employs about 4,000 people, but had announced plans for  
tough austerity measures after reporting losses for 1998 and the 
first quarter of 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	Norsk Hydro, the largest company listed on the Oslo Stock  
Exchange, employs about 40,000 people worldwide. It expects to cut 
about 800 jobs if the takeover goes through. 
</P>
</TEXT>
