<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Online Investigations, Case by Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Some recent cases in which police sought access to the online  
activities of suspects or victims: 
</P>
<P>
	--The stabbing death of a Decatur, Ala., woman who police say was  
using her computer around the time of the attack and was still 
signed on to America Online when her body was discovered. 
</P>
<P>
	--A Mishawaka, Ind., woman, posing as a man online, who formed a  
relationship with a 15-year-old Iowa girl. 
</P>
<P>
	--A man charged with aggravated murder in the shooting death of  
Penny Chang, 15, of Shaker Heights, Ohio, who had received 60 pages 
of threatening e-mail and been harassed on the phone. 
</P>
<P>
	--The custodian of an Alexandria, La., cathedral charged in a  
church arson. Police were testing his alibi that he was online when 
the fire started. 
</P>
<P>
	--A San Bernardino, Calif., sheriff's department dispatcher who  
police say was in collusion with a suspect. 
</P>
<P>
	--A youth in Sterling, Va., who received threatening e-mails,  
including one saying: ``I'm going to (expletive) kill you if you 
don't call me. ... You see, my friend, I like to call this a little 
game. A game of cat and mouse. I have been watching you for some 
time now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--A masseur found dead with his computer missing in his Las Vegas  
apartment. Police believe he met clients in chat rooms. 
</P>
<P>
	--A Hamden, Conn., woman who received a string of threatening and  
obscene e-mails, one saying: ``Everyone has to die someday. 
Unfortunately your time is near.'' Police say the sender at one 
point ``said he was a 12-year-old boy from California and was 
sorry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--A Eugene, Ore., man suspected in inciting a ``riot'' at a Nike  
store. 
</P>
<P>
	--A northern Virginia pediatrician posing as a 16-year-old girl,  
charged this week with possessing child pornography that police say 
they found in his e-mail. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
