<DOCNO> APW19990528.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 10:21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Details of Clinton Approval Ratings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	A year-by-year breakdown of President Clinton's job approval  
ratings in the CNN/USA Today/Gallup poll: 
</P>
<P>
	--1993: 58 percent job approval after inauguration, but drops to  
37 percent by June after problems choosing an attorney general 
candidate and decision on dropping ban on gays in the military. By 
December, rate climbs to 54 percent after successes with Brady Bill 
restricting handgun sales and the North American Free Trade 
Agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	--1994: Starts year at 54 percent in January, but public sours on  
health care reform plan and job approval slips to 39 percent by 
September, with 54 percent not approving. Republicans sweep to 
power in Congress in November. 
</P>
<P>
	--1995: Starts at 47 percent in January and stays in the 40s much  
of the year, but edges back to 53 percent in December after 
confrontation with Republicans over government shutdown. 
</P>
<P>
	--1996: Approval at 58 percent to start year, moves to 62 percent  
by mid-January, stays in the high 50s and low 60s much of the year, 
though dipping to 52 percent in mid-August. 
</P>
<P>
	--1997: Rating starts at 58 percent in January and stays in the  
high 50s and low 60s all year. 
</P>
<P>
	--1998: Approval jumps to 69 percent after the first news of the  
Monica Lewinsky investigation. It stays in the 60s throughout the 
year and spikes to 73 percent in December after the House votes for 
impeachment. 
</P>
<P>
	--1999: Job approval is 63 percent in January and stays in mid to  
high 60s during impeachment trial. By April, rating is at 60 
percent and it slips to 53 percent in late May as the Kosovo 
conflict drags on, lowest approval rating since August 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990528.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 20:01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Graduation at School Shooting Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONYERS, Ga. (AP) -- The Heritage High School Class of 1999  
graduated Friday night and came together one last time in the 
school commons where six fellow students were wounded by a 
classmate who opened fire eight days earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	While none of those wounded were among the 275 seniors, the  
violence that seemed to shatter their lives last week brought them 
together at graduation, said Steven Brown, a school counselor. 
</P>
<P>
	``Usually they never hang out this long after graduation. This  
never happens,'' Brown said after the ceremony ended and students 
remained in the commons area for 45 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	Seniors went back to the commons to cheer, hug and celebrate  
their accomplishments. 
</P>
<P>
	``They bounced back real quick and they didn't let it faze  
them,'' Brown said. 
</P>
<P>
	All six students who were wounded May 20 when a student began  
shooting in the commons area were released from the hospital after 
being treated for gunshot wounds. 
</P>
<P>
	The suspect, T.J. Solomon, 15, faces 20 counts of aggravated  
assault, cruelty to children and weapons charges. District Attorney 
Richard Read has said he will ask a juvenile court judge to allow 
Solomon to be tried as an adult. 
</P>
<P>
	``For the last eight days, Heritage has been known worldwide for  
a single incident -- a tragedy,'' Shaffiq Welgi said during his 
speech in the packed gym. ``My 13 years of schooling, however, have 
made me look at that day's events as a single occurrence, minuscule 
in appearance of the achievements of our class of 1999.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Extra officers patrolled the ceremony, which parents and  
teachers tried to focus on achievements rather than a rehash of the 
shooting. 
</P>
<P>
	``Forget about the past, we are the future,'' Class President  
Martin Humphrey said as the ceremony came to a close. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
