<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Faults Japan on Computer Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- U.S. computer companies continue to face obstacles  
in the Japanese government market and Japan should work harder to 
give them better access, U.S. officials said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``U.S. computer hardware and software companies, which are  
global technology leaders with long-term commitments to the 
Japanese market, continue to encounter difficulties in gaining full 
access to the Japanese government market,'' the U.S. Embassy said 
in a news release. 
</P>
<P>
	The statement came after an annual review of implementation of  
measures related to Japanese government procurement of computer 
products and services. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. government and American companies have long complained  
that Japan shuts out foreign firms though a complex web of 
government regulations and informal barriers such as cozy ties 
among domestic enterprises. 
</P>
<P>
	At Friday's review meeting, the Japanese government showed that  
for fiscal 1997, which ended on March 31, 1998, the foreign share 
of Japanese government procurement of computers and computer 
systems was 16.5 percent, up from 15.9 percent a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	In comparison, foreign computer companies represent 35 percent  
of the private sector market, the U.S. Embassy said. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. representatives urged their Japanese counterparts to  
take steps to enhance fairness and transparency in government 
procurement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
