<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Votes To Beef Up Lab Security Wait </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The bipartisanship that accompanied this  
week's release of a House report on alleged nuclear espionage by 
China was short-lived. 
</P>
<P>
	Just days later, Democrats and Republicans are accusing each  
other of playing politics with the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	Votes on measures to increase security substantially at  
Department of Energy weapons laboratories and to tighten export 
controls prompted divisive debate and were then put off until after 
a 10-day Memorial Day recess in both the House and Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Democrats used delaying tactics late Thursday to stall a  
GOP-sponsored measure that would reorganize the Energy Department 
after the proposal drew a veto threat from the Clinton 
administration. The proposal would create a new assistant secretary 
for defense programs who would report directly to the president and 
Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., postponed action on that  
measure to prevent it from further delaying completion of a $288.8 
billion Defense Department spending bill for the fiscal year that 
begins Oct. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure, approved 92-3, would provide $8.3 billion more than  
President Clinton requested for a variety of Pentagon programs for 
next year, including a 4.8 percent across-the-board military pay 
raise next Jan. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	While the bill would provide some measures to beef up security  
at weapons labs and to intensify congressional oversight, Lott told 
reporters that Democrats had ``basically shut down'' the Senate 
over the more far-reaching reform proposals. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not going to get real security until we have a whole  
other arrangement at DOE,'' Lott said. ``It's not about fixing 
blame. It's about fixing the problem.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Sen. Harry Reid, D-Nev., who led the Democratic delaying  
tactics, said, ``This is the wrong time for this amendment. This is 
not the time for debate on reorganization the Department of 
Energy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, efforts to debate the China espionage issue in the  
House never got off the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	The House version of the defense bill was ``pulled'' Thursday by  
House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill. Hastert acted after Democrats 
complained they weren't getting a chance to offer their own 
amendments on the China issue, and GOP conservatives complained 
that the bill was too supportive of the administration's Kosovo 
policy. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an insult,'' said Rep. Norman Dicks, D-Wash., the senior  
Democrat on the special House committee that issued the report that 
claimed 20 years of Chinese nuclear espionage. He said procedures 
put in place by House GOP leaders barred him from offering 
amendments dealing with the China investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	One amendment would have supported current administration  
efforts to tighten security. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Christopher Cox, R-Calif., chairman of the espionage  
investigation, told reporters that Dicks should have been allowed 
to present his amendment and suggested there had been a 
misunderstanding. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite Senate Republicans' complaints about Democratic stalling  
tactics, the defense bill passed by the Senate does contain 
measures to address the China espionage issue. 
</P>
<P>
	The package includes $35 million to enhance computer security at  
Energy Department nuclear labs and another $17 million to upgrade 
security clearance investigations of employees. 
</P>
<P>
	It also includes a package offered by Lott and supported by  
Democratic leaders that would expand the role of intelligence 
agencies in reviewing export licenses. It also would boost Pentagon 
monitoring of satellite launches in China and require the 
administration to report to Congress on any security breaches. 
</P>
<P>
	The impasse on the Senate side came over an amendment by  
Republican Sens. Pete Domenici of New Mexico, Frank Murkowski of 
Alaska and Jon Kyl of Arizona to create a new assistant secretary 
for defense programs in the Energy Department. That official would 
have wide-ranging authority and could bypass the energy secretary 
in dealing directly with the president and Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Energy Secretary Bill Richardson opposed the proposal as too  
extensive and complained in a letter to Senate leaders: ``This 
proposal would effectively cancel my six-month effort to strengthen 
security.'' He said it might prompt an administration veto threat. 
</P>
<P>
	The three who voted against Senate passage of the defense bill  
were Democratic Sens. Russ Feingold and Herbert Kohl of Wisconsin 
and Paul Wellstone of Minnesota. Those not voting were Ernest 
Hollings, D-S.C.; Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J.; Richard Lugar, R-Ind.; 
Connie Mack, R-Fla., and Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	----	 
</P>
<P>
	The bills are H.R. 1401 and S 1059.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
