<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Harness Driver Returns To Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- George Brennan, the nation's  
leading harness driver until being suspended in a controversial 
ruling by the New Jersey Racing Commission, returned to racing 
Friday after getting a stay from the state Supreme Court. 
</P>
<P>
	Brennan picked up six drives on the 12-race card at the  
Meadowlands Racetrack, which had sought to bar him, and he 
eventually got back to the winner's circle with longshot Maxwells 
Champ ($32.80) in his fifth race back. 
</P>
<P>
	The state Supreme Court ruled Wednesday that the state-owned  
track could not do that while Brennan's case is being reviewed by a 
state appeals court. 
</P>
<P>
	Brennan was suspended by the racing commission on April 10 for  
an unsatisfactory effort in a race on March 10 at Freehold Raceway, 
a race in which an investigation found some questionable betting. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's great to be back racing,'' Brennan said after his third  
drive. ``I just really appreciate the trainers sticking by me, it 
means a lot to me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As he said that, the emotion was evident in Brennan's eyes and  
voice. 
</P>
<P>
	Brennan's win came in the 10th race when he had a perfect trip  
with Maxwells Champ, taking the lead in the stretch and barely 
holding off Palmer Seelster at the wire. 
</P>
<P>
	Brennan finished third in the first race with Our Commitment.  
Just prior to the race, a fan near the outside apron of the track 
held up a banner, welcoming the driver back and wishing him luck. 
</P>
<P>
	``It just felt good to be out there making a living again,''  
Brennan said. ``The fans treated me great. The one guy was out 
there with the sign and it was great knowing the fans and my fellow 
colleagues were behind me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The one difference Brennan noticed was that his hands felt a  
little weak after six weeks of not handling horses, which weigh 
about 1,000 pounds. 
</P>
<P>
	``I should be all right after about 15 or 20 races,'' said  
Brennan, who drove in a couple of qualifying races on Friday 
morning, winning one. 
</P>
<P>
	Brennan was 13th and last in the third race when Southwind  
Miranda broke stride shortly after the start. The 32-year-old was 
seventh in both the fifth and ninth races. He finished fifth in the 
11th race, his final drive. 
</P>
<P>
	Brennan was suspended based on his drive of My Dream Come True  
at Freehold Raceway on March 10. The racing commission ruled that 
``the drive was unsatisfactory due to a lack of effort'' and cited 
its rules against ``fraudulent or unsatisfactory driving'' and 
``conduct detrimental to the sport.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brennan had his finest season in 1998, finishing third with 172  
winners in 1,200 starts. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of Brennan's drives on Friday developed because Catello  
Manzi was unable to drive because of an injury sustained at 
Freehold on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The appeals court probably won't rule for at least two months on  
whether the Meadowlands has the right to bar Brennan, so it is 
likely he will be able to race through the end of the current meet, 
which ends in early August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990528.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 14:41:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> D.C. Shooting Case Decision Delayed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federal judge has postponed for three weeks  
a decision on whether the man accused of slaying two Capitol Hill 
police officers can be forced to take medication that doctors 
believe could make him mentally fit to stand trial. 
</P>
<P>
	At a hearing Friday, U.S. District Court Judge Emmet Sullivan  
deferred the decision on Russell Eugene Weston Jr. until June 18. 
</P>
<P>
	Weston is charged with murdering Capitol Police officers John M.  
Gibson and Jacob J. Chestnut in the Capitol on July 24, 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, a federal judge ruled that Weston, 42, was not  
competent to stand trial, after psychiatrist Sally C. Johnson, an 
associate warden at the Butner facility, said she believed Weston 
was a paranoid schizophrenic. But she did not rule out the 
possibility that Weston could stand trial after he receives 
treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	Confined at a federal prison hospital in Butner, N.C., Weston  
has refused medications prescribed by psychiatrists. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's been refusing to take his medication and not really  
cooperating with doctors down there,'' said Channing Phillips, 
spokesman for the U.S. attorney's office in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense attorneys have filed papers arguing that forcing Weston  
to take medication could violate his constitutional rights and 
could have harmful mental and physical effects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990528.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 06:01:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> TLC Beatrice To Liquidate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- TLC Beatrice International Holdings Inc., once  
the nation's largest black-owned company, is being liquidated as 
part of an evolving strategy begun following the death of its 
founder Reginald Lewis six years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The liquidation plan, announced Thursday along with the sale of  
its Spanish soft drink division, is expected to return a healthy 
profit for investors and the Lewis family, the company said. 
</P>
<P>
	That's in line with the long-term goal to generate shareholder  
wealth that Lewis set when he bought the company in 1987 in a $985 
million leveraged buyout, said his widow Loida Nicolas Lewis -- now 
the company's chairman. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mr. Lewis built the rocket ship,'' she said. ``He and I knew  
where he wanted to take it. That's basically what happened.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis died of brain cancer in 1993 at age 50. Mrs. Lewis said  
that, while she had not originally intended to liquidate the 
company, a detailed examination of its growth potential convinced 
management that was the best course. 
</P>
<P>
	Throughout its short life, TLC Beatrice has been hailed as a  
success story. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1987, when TLC Beatrice reported revenue of $1.8 billion, it  
became the first black-owned company to have more than $1 billion 
in annual sales. The company then began its reign at the top of 
Black Enterprise magazine's annual list of the country's 100 
biggest black-owned companies. 
</P>
<P>
	TLC Beatrice, which was closely held by the Lewis family and  
associates, hit its peak in 1996 when it had $2.23 billion in 
revenue. 
</P>
<P>
	Other companies weren't even close. In 1996, for example,  
Johnson Publishing Co. of Chicago ranked second on the BE 100 list 
with $325.7 million in sales. Philadelphia Coca-Cola Bottling Co. 
ranked third with $325 million in sales. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a model that we will continue to follow,'' said Earl  
Graves, the publisher of Black Enterprise magazine. Graves employed 
Lewis, an attorney, to represent him when he bought radio stations 
in the early 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis epitomized a break from traditional investment patterns  
among blacks in which entrepreneurs might own one or two companies 
for life. 
</P>
<P>
	``As black entrepreneurs acquire new businesses and develop  
strategic alliances, they will in many instances, as evidenced by 
Reginald Lewis, sell their companies, realize capital gains and use 
the process to capitalize on new business opportunities,'' Graves 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Following Lewis' death, his company went through a period of  
management and shareholder turmoil, with Mrs. Lewis finally taking 
over a year later. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I assumed office, I did not know what course to take,''  
Mrs. Lewis said in an interview. She considered several strategies, 
including an initial public offering and further acquisitions in 
order to enhance shareholder wealth. 
</P>
<P>
	``We knew the end goal, but going there is not always evident,''  
she said. ``Initially, there was no thought of selling all of the 
company.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The TLC Beatrice saga began in working class Baltimore where  
Lewis was a standout athlete whose bright future ended in a knee 
injury. He was invited to enter Harvard Law School without making 
an application after he impressed school officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis wound up on Wall Street engaged in mergers and  
acquisitions. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1984, he caught his first big wave. He bought the McCall  
Pattern Co., a supplier of sewing instructions, retooled it and 
sold it in 1987 at a 90-to-1 return on investment. 
</P>
<P>
	While the McCall sale impressed many on Wall Street, it was his  
move that December that took him over the top. 
</P>
<P>
	In a leveraged buyout partly funded by junk bond financier  
Michael Milken, Lewis used his TLC Group to take over a part of 
Beatrice International. Lewis sold off some of the food company's 
subsidiaries and grew what was left into TLC Beatrice, a food 
processing and distribution company based in the United States but 
whose operations were mainly in Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1992, Forbes magazine listed Lewis among the 400 richest  
Americans with a net worth estimated at $400 million and TLC 
Beatrice as the 74th largest privately-held company in the United 
States. 
</P>
<P>
	Before his death, Lewis set a plan in motion to install a  
brother, Jean Fugett Jr., as the new chairman. Fugett was ousted a 
year later and Mrs. Lewis took over. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time, the company was embroiled in a fight with Lewis'  
business partners at Milken's Drexel Burnham Lambert, who claimed 
Lewis was overcompensated and demanded tens of millions from his 
estate. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Lewis smoothed the waters, settling a lawsuit with the  
former Drexel employees. 
</P>
<P>
	She started selling subsidiaries. Following the largest sales  
over the past two years, the company dropped to the fourth greatest 
revenue generator on the Black Enterprise listings. In 1998, the 
company had revenues of $322 million. 
</P>
<P>
	A few parts of the company remain to be sold. Those sales are  
expected by summer. 
</P>
<P>
	After that?  
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Lewis won't talk about her plans although she said she  
wants to remain in business. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
