<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Casinos May Avoid New Taxes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Casinos apparently will avoid any  
recommendation of new taxes or federal supervision in next month's 
report from a national gambling commission. 
</P>
<P>
	The report, which the National Gambling Impact Study Commission  
will finish next week during a meeting in San Francisco, will be 
released June 18. It probably will propose restrictions on state 
lotteries, criticize American Indian casinos for being secretive 
and discourage racetracks from installing slot machines. 
</P>
<P>
	But, so far, the working draft of the nine-member commission's  
report steers clear of the most spectacular symbols of legalized 
gambling: the hulking, showy, laser-lit, buffet-fed, up-all-night 
casino resorts of Atlantic City, N.J., Las Vegas and the 
Mississippi Gulf Coast, along with smaller casinos on land and 
rivers in seven other states. 
</P>
<P>
	The casino industry feared the commission would urge the federal  
government to take over gambling supervision from the states and 
impose new federal taxes on gambling. Neither idea has yet come to 
pass, and probably won't. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission also rejected proposals that would have forced  
casinos to stop issuing credit, to send profit and loss summaries 
to patrons and to impose daily loss limits on bettors. 
</P>
<P>
	For now, the most objectionable part of the report is its call  
for an end to legalized betting on collegiate sports, said Frank 
Fahrenkopf Jr., a former Republican National Committee chairman who 
is head of the American Gaming Association, the industry lobby. 
</P>
<P>
	The commision, which also seems poised to recommend a national  
moratorium on new gambling ventures, includes three men who have 
been prominent in and around Las Vegas. But Fahrenkopf denies that 
the casino industry is getting kid-gloves treatment by the panel. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were looked at harder'' than the other forms of gambling,  
he said. Fahrenkopf credited the industry with ``being out front'' 
on issues like helping addictive gamblers. 
</P>
<P>
	But others see politics at work.  
</P>
<P>
	When Congress created the commission in 1996, casino  
heavyweights lobbied congressional leaders and the White House to 
appoint members friendly to their industry. 
</P>
<P>
	The result: Of the nine commissioners, three have worked in and  
around Las Vegas casinos -- William Bible, former chairman of the 
Nevada gaming control board; MGM Grand Chairman J. Terrence Lanni, 
a member of the AGA's board of directors; and John Wilhelm, 
national president of the Hotel Employees and Restaurant Employees 
Union. 
</P>
<P>
	All three say they approached their work with open minds. But  
Bernard Horn, who has followed the commission for the National 
Coalition Against Legalized Gambling, said he believes they ``made 
it their priority to protect the Vegas casino industry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	James Dobson, the commission's most unyielding critic of  
gambling, agreed that the casino industry got results by making 
sure some of its friends were appointed. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, Dobson said casinos also had a strong case on  
the merits. He believes casino resorts, to which people travel, are 
less worrisome than state lotteries, Internet betting and 
neighborhood slot machines that bring the temptation of gambling 
close to where people live. 
</P>
<P>
	The idea that people choose to travel to casinos was a point the  
casino lobby hammered home at every opportunity. 
</P>
<P>
	Casino operators formed the AGA in 1994 after President Clinton  
broached the notion of a federal gaming tax. It now has about 120 
member companies, including casino hotels, riverboat casinos and 
casino suppliers. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
