<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Official Shows Ambition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Nikolai Aksyonenko has been rattling a lot of  
nerves in Russia lately. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, the tall, graying 50-year-old was the relatively  
obscure chief of Russia's railroad network. Then he was named one 
of two first deputy prime ministers -- the top positions in the 
government after prime minister. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, the other first deputy has resigned and Aksyonenko's  
ambition has assumed stunning proportions. 
</P>
<P>
	He has brazenly assigned himself broad powers and said he would  
oversee all government policy -- baffling and outraging other 
Cabinet ministers. He even popped up unexpectedly at a key meeting 
at a Black Sea resort between President Boris Yeltsin and Prime 
Minister Sergei Stepashin. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the other first deputy prime minister, Mikhail  
Zadornov, was not among those complaining about Aksyonenko, he 
couldn't have been happy about his colleague's boasts. Zadornov 
resigned Friday, saying he had been frustrated in his quest to 
maintain his position as finance minister in addition to his new 
duties. 
</P>
<P>
	Aksyonenko is ``hogging the blanket'' and ``conducting himself  
like he's ... convinced of his hereditary right to rule the 
country,'' the daily Noviye Izvestia wrote Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Conductor, hit the brakes!'' the popular newspaper Moskovsky  
Komsomolets said in a headline Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Observers are wary of Aksyonenko's rapid rise and his boldness.  
But their concern stems largely from his alleged links to tycoons 
Boris Berezovsky and Roman Abramovich. Aksyonenko denies close 
connections to the men. 
</P>
<P>
	Both moguls are reported to wield immense influence over Yeltsin  
through his family, and to control some of Russia's most coveted 
businesses. For many Russians, they are also symbols of the ``crony 
capitalism'' that allowed several businessmen to use high-level 
contacts to buy government assets at giveaway prices and quickly 
amass fortunes. 
</P>
<P>
	Russian media have questioned Aksyonenko's recent incursions  
into the oil industry, one of Russia's most lucrative sectors. 
Abramovich heads Russian oil giant Sibneft, and Berezovsky is 
reputed to have oil holdings. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, Aksyonenko chaired a meeting on the condition of the  
oil industry. The day before, he overshadowed new Fuel and Energy 
Minister Viktor Kalyuzhny's first public appearance, laying out 
plans for the oil, gas and coal sectors while Kalyuzhny meekly 
nodded in agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	Aksyonenko's background lies in railroads, not oil. He graduated  
from the Novosibirsk Institute of Railways and worked his way up to 
head the Railways Ministry, which oversees the huge web of Russian 
railroads, one of the nation's giant state monopolies. 
</P>
<P>
	Aksyonenko has said little about his economic policies, though  
he has ordered the Cabinet to boost industrial output by 20 percent 
this year, Moskovsky Komsomolets reported. It was unclear how 
Russia's flailing industry was to achieve such an ambitious goal. 
</P>
<P>
	Some observers have said Yeltsin may be grooming Aksyonenko as a  
possible successor. 
</P>
<P>
	Others say the president is using Aksyonenko to check the powers  
of Stepashin, also touted as a potential presidential contender 
after his appointment as prime minister earlier this month. Yeltsin 
often plays his underlings off each other. 
</P>
<P>
	Resentment of Aksyonenko has been aggravated by confusion over  
who in the new government is in charge of what. 
</P>
<P>
	Aksyonenko dived into the vacuum Wednesday, announcing he would  
oversee the Cabinet's work in ``all fields.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``No one in the government, except Nikolai Aksyonenko, knows  
what his job is,'' the daily Segodnya wrote Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
