<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indicting Milosevic Was Easy Part </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Now comes the hard part.  
</P>
<P>
	After indicting President Slobodan Milosevic, the Yugoslav war  
crimes tribunal still needs someone to arrest him and escort him to 
The Hague, no small task. 
</P>
<P>
	The tribunal has no police powers, meaning it is entirely  
dependent on the international community to arrest indicted war 
criminals. Since its creation six years ago, 25 of 84 suspects, 
Bosnians of various ethnicities, have been taken into custody in 
The Hague, Netherlands. 
</P>
<P>
	And none had the kind of security apparatus that Milosevic has  
to fend off any bid to apprehend him. 
</P>
<P>
	Chief prosecutor Louise Arbour announced Thursday that the  
tribunal had indicted Milosevic and four other top officials on 
charges of crimes against humanity in the brutal expulsion of 
750,000 ethnic Albanians from Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and British Foreign  
Secretary Robin Cook were asked about the possibility of 
Milosevic's apprehension, but neither offered hope, at least 
publicly, that any move to arrest Milosevic was afoot. 
</P>
<P>
	``He has to be turned over and we want to see him in The  
Hague,'' said Albright, speaking to reporters at a joint news 
conference with Canadian Foreign Secretary Lloyd Axworthy. Cook 
offered a similar response during a news conference in London. 
</P>
<P>
	Arbour suggested that Yugoslav authorities themselves request  
that Milosevic and four indicted subordinates surrender to the 
tribunal. Alternatively, they should ``provide for their arrest and 
transfer to The Hague,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright welcomed the indictment of Milosevic, noting that it  
broadens the base of opposition to Milosevic to include a tribunal 
created by the U.N. Security Council. The indictment proves that 
the hostility to Milosevic is no mere ``figment of the imagination 
of NATO,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Zbigniew Brzezinski, a former White House national security  
adviser, said the capture of Milosevic would require nothing less 
than ``the occupation of Serbia and the seizure of Belgrade.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Appearing with a group of other Balkan experts, Brzezinski said  
the apprehension of Milosevic should not be a high priority. 
</P>
<P>
	``The real importance of the indictment is that it reinforces  
the international condemnation of an outlaw regime and thus gives 
... political as well as moral sanction to what is being pursued,'' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Top Russian officials suggested the indictment could complicate  
the Yugoslav peace process -- one in which Russian diplomats are 
deeply involved. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the legally elected president of Yugoslavia.  
Attempting to solve the situation in the Balkans, if you're dealing 
with Yugoslavia you have to deal with one person, the president of 
Yugoslavia,'' said presidential spokesman Dmitry Yakushkin. 
</P>
<P>
	Said Col. Terry Taylor of the London-based International  
Institute for Strategic Studies: ``The primary goal must be to get 
the people back in their homes. It's not that the law isn't 
important, but one must keep one's eyes on the primary goal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., saw the indictment of Milosevic as a  
mixed blessing. It may well complicate future negotiations, he 
said, but '' I believe it is important because it makes absolutely 
clear that the United Nations, NATO and the rest of the civilized 
world know what Milosevic has been doing and will not tolerate it 
longer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Said former Rep. Stephen Solarz, D-N.Y., who, like Brzezinski,  
is affiliated with the Balkan Action Council, ``It is neither 
possible nor appropriate to negotiate with an indicted war 
criminal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	State Department spokesman James P. Rubin disputed that notion,  
pointing out that Russian special envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin plans 
to meet with Milosevic in Belgrade on Friday to review peace 
efforts. 
</P>
<P>
	Irrespective of the indictment, Rubin said the administration  
believes ``it would not be a difficult proposition to have the 
acceptance of NATO's conditions implemented.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Foreign Relations Committee chairman Jesse Helms  
cautioned against any deal with Milosevic. 
</P>
<P>
	``Negotiate with Milosevic?'' he asked. ``Never. He must be  
removed from power now.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
