<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FBI Asked To Probe S.C. Dragging </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KINGSTREE, S.C. (AP) -- A black man who was dragged by two white  
men for a quarter-mile beside their pickup truck said he's not sure 
the attack had anything to do with his race. 
</P>
<P>
	``It could have been mistaken identity,'' Charone Green, who was  
not seriously injured in the dragging early Wednesday, told The 
(Columbia) State for today's editions. ``It could have been 
anything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Eric W. Jones, 38, of Gastonia, N.C., and Arthur Marshall, 34,  
of Georgetown were formally charged today with assault and battery 
with intent to kill. Marshall also was charged with possession of a 
stolen vehicle. Bond was set at $200,000 for Jones and $212,000 for 
Marshall. 
</P>
<P>
	Williamsburg County Sheriff Kelvin Washington has asked the FBI  
and State Law Enforcement Division to look into whether Green's 
civil rights were violated in the dragging. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the sheriff said authorities have no indication at this  
point that Green was attacked because he is black. ``There is a 
possibility that it may be drug-related,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities said Green was grabbed and dragged when he  
approached a pickup truck that had slowed in front of his cousin's 
house on a rural road in the Bloomingvale community, about 90 miles 
east of Columbia. 
</P>
<P>
	Green, 23, told investigators he was standing at the end of a  
driveway when two men pulled up in a red pickup truck and told him 
to come over. Green said he had a napkin in his hand that the men 
might have thought contained drugs. He said he did not have drugs 
on him. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the passenger grabbed his arm and the truck drove off,  
Chief Deputy Dwight Williams said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The first thing that came to my mind is, `If I don't hold on  
to this truck, I'm going to wind up getting killed,''' Green told 
the newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	Green said he did not remember much about what the men said as  
he clung to the side of the truck. 
</P>
<P>
	A cousin who witnessed it said Green broke free when the truck  
hit a culvert. 
</P>
<P>
	Green's right leg, ankle and arm were injured in the attack,  
according to a sheriff's report. He was treated at a hospital and 
released. 
</P>
<P>
	Green's grandmother, Mary Green, said last June's dragging death  
of a black man in Texas was the first thing that popped in her mind 
she heard what happened. One man has been convicted of murder and 
sentenced to death in that case, while trials are pending for two 
more. 
</P>
<P>
	But she said she wasn't sure the attack on her grandson was  
similarly motivated. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't say whether it's a racial thing or not,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	Investigators were unsure who was driving the truck that was  
reported stolen from Lexington County, near Columbia. It was found 
with flattened tires and a shattered windshield, its radio missing, 
Washington said. 
</P>
<P>
	The suspects were arrested at a home near Andrews, where  
Marshall has relatives. Washington wouldn't say what led 
investigators to them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990528.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 21:11:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Milosevic Stands Ground in Talks  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO jets are hitting Yugoslavia's  
power supply system early Saturday, just hours after Yugoslav 
President Slobodan Milosevic emerged from talks with a Russian 
envoy. Milosevic maintains his refusal to allow an armed, 
international security force in Kosovo. Despite that, Russian envoy 
Viktor Chernomyrdin said he was ``very satisfied'' with the 
meeting. Strobe Talbott, the deputy U.S. secretary of state, said 
Chernomyrdin was not negotiating on behalf of NATO nor was he 
acting as a mediator. 

</P>
<P>
	Albanian Army Stages War Games  
</P>
<P>
	KUKES, Albania (AP) -- The Albanian army Friday simulated a  
defense of its territory against a cross-border strike by Serbian 
forces, firing hundreds of artillery shells and rockets toward the 
embattled Kosovo frontier. The war games involved tanks, howitzers 
and 1,200 ground troops maneuvering several miles from the border, 
where Serbian forces have clashed with guerrillas of the Kosovo 
Liberation Army in recent days. NATO tried unsuccessfully to stop 
the exercise, fearing a Serbian military response in an area packed 
with more than 100,000 Kosovo refugees and international aid agency 
personnel. 

</P>
<P>
	Judge Won't Release Colo. Autopsies  
</P>
<P>
	GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) -- The autopsy reports of the Columbine High  
School shooting victims will not be released, a judge said Friday, 
as they would cause substantial harm to the community of Littleton. 
Families of the victims asked the judge to seal the records after 
19 news organizations requested the records. The Denver Post and 
Denver Rocky Mountain challenged the families' request, saying the 
autopsy reports might shed light on the attack and help prevent 
further tragedies. But Jefferson County District Court Judge Henry 
Nieto said the community was traumatized by the shootings, and 
release of the reports would reopen wounds that are just beginning 
to heal. 

</P>
<P>
	India Blames Pakistani Military  
</P>
<P>
	DRAS, India (AP) -- An Indian helicopter gunship was blasted from  
the skies above Kashmir's jagged Himalayan peaks Friday as the 
military pressed ahead with airstrikes to dislodge Islamic 
militants it says are backed by neighboring Pakistan. Despite the 
escalation in the military conflict, the political leadership in 
the two nuclear-armed nations appeared to be tempering their 
reactions, and India said it now believes Pakistan's military -- not 
its government -- is to blame for the latest fighting. 

</P>
<P>
	Kaczynski's Bid For New Trial Nixed  
</P>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- A federal judge has rejected Theodore  
Kaczynski's bid for a trial, turning aside the Unabomber's 
contention that he was forced into pleading guilty. U.S. District 
Judge Garland E. Burrell Jr. said Friday that Kaczynski's claims 
did not warrant a hearing and he dismissed the matter. Kaczynski 
pleaded guilty in January 1998 to bombings that killed three people 
and injured 23. He was sentenced to life in prison without the 
possibility of parole. The former math professor argued in recent 
filings that he was forced to either plead guilty or be portrayed 
at a trial as mentally ill by his attorneys, which he did not want. 

</P>
<P>
	JFK's Casket Was Dropped in Ocean  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A bronze casket used to transport President  
Kennedy's body from Dallas to Washington was dropped from a 
military plane into the ocean two years after he was killed, 
according to assassination documents. Kermit L. Hall, a member of 
the now-defunct Assassination Records Review Board, said Friday 
that documents to be released Tuesday by the National Archives show 
that the casket was flown several miles off the Maryland-Delaware 
coast in early 1965 and dumped in an area where the military 
discards unstable and outdated weapons and ammunition. The reasons 
for the disposal aren't clear, but it fuels speculation among 
assassination researchers that it was discarded to hide foul play. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks End Higher; Dow Up 92.81  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rebounded Friday from Thursday's steep  
selloff as new economic data showing slower-than-expected growth 
helped calm fears about rising inflation and higher interest rates. 
The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 92.81 at 10,559.74. 
Advancers on the NYSE outnumbered decliners 1,964-975. The Nasdaq 
closed up 51.26 to 2,470.41. 

</P>
<P>
	Avalanche Take Stars in OT  
</P>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Chris Drury scored with 31 seconds left in  
overtime to give the Colorado Avalanche a bruising 3-2 victory over 
the Dallas Stars in the Western Conference finals Friday night. 
Colorado tied the best-of-7 series at two games apiece and send it 
to Dallas for Game 5 on Sunday. 


</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
