<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                            *Alice Adams    	
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Novelist Alice Adams, widely admired for  
her artfully constructed stories, died Thursday. She was 72. 
</P>
<P>
	She had been treated for heart problems earlier in the week and  
appeared to have died in her sleep, said her editor, Victoria 
Wilson. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Adams' 10 novels and five collections of short stories about  
women's lives sometimes reflected or anticipated changes in 
society. 
</P>
<P>
	After publishing her first story for The New Yorker in 1969, Ms.  
Adams became one of the magazine's most distinctive voices. 
</P>
<P>
	Her 1975 novel ``Families and Survivors,'' about a woman who  
moves from the South to San Francisco, established her as an 
important literary presence. ``Superior Women,'' which traced the 
lives of five Radcliffe women, in 1984 became a best seller. 
</P>
<P>
	Known for her wry perspective on life, Ms. Adams once ruminated  
on the difficulty of writing as one ages: ``Some smart person once 
said that what happens is your critical standards rise, and your 
talent does not necessarily increase in a commensurate way.'' 

</P>
<P>
                         *Kelso Gillenwater    	
</P>
<P>
	TACOMA, Wash. (AP) -- Kelso Gillenwater, retired publisher of The  
News Tribune of Tacoma and former publisher of the Tri-City Herald, 
has died. He was 52. 
</P>
<P>
	Gillenwater, who had suffered a mild heart attack in 1997, was  
found dead Wednesday at his Gig Harbor home. He died of natural 
causes, apparently on Monday, the Pierce County Medical Examiner's 
Office said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gillenwater retired as publisher of The News Tribune in 1998.  
</P>
<P>
	In addition to The News Tribune, Gillenwater was responsible for  
three weekly newspapers in the region: The Peninsula Gateway, The 
Pierce County Herald and the Northwest Guardian, the Army newspaper 
serving Fort Lewis. 
</P>
<P>
	Before coming to Tacoma in 1991, he was publisher of the  
Tri-City Herald in Kennewick for 10 years. Both papers are owned by 
McClatchy Newspapers. 
</P>
<P>
	Gillenwater began his 32-year career in newspapers in the South,  
working as a reporter for dailies in Bristol, Va., Greensboro, 
N.C., and Memphis, Tenn. 
</P>
<P>
	After six years of reporting, Gillenwater and partners purchased  
one daily and several weekly newspapers in north and central 
Florida. In 1976, he joined Landmark Communications in Norfolk, 
Va., and became president of the company's small-newspaper 
division. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include a son, two daughters, a former wife and three  
sisters. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Ray Kimball    	
</P>
<P>
	DE QUEEN, Ark. (AP) -- Ray Kimball, who started his 79-year  
newspaper career as a boy at his father's paper and worked until 
two months ago as publisher of the weekly De Queen Bee and De Queen 
Daily Citizen, died Wednesday at age 91. 
</P>
<P>
	In the early 1940s, Kimball developed a Teletypesetter network  
that eventually linked nine Arkansas dailies. Later, the system was 
used by other newspaper groups and The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	His newspaper also was among the first in Arkansas to make its  
news available on the World Wide Web. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1992, he received the National Newspaper Association's  
highest award -- the Amos Award -- given for outstanding 
contributions to the newspaper business and his community, and his 
support of the nation's community newspapers. 
</P>
<P>
	The newspapers he owned or published included the Horatio Times  
weekly, the weekly Sevier County Citizen, and the Magnolia Banner. 
He also served a three-year stint as an aviation officer in the 
Navy. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include a daughter and three granddaughters.  

</P>
<P>
                        *William Schield Jr.    	
</P>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- William Schield Jr., a senior vice president at  
Robert W. Baird &AMP; Co., a stock brokerage firm, died Tuesday in a 
car accident. He was 72. 
</P>
<P>
	Schield and his wife, Charlotte, were killed when their car went  
off the road near the northern coast of Spain while on vacation. 
</P>
<P>
	Schield was known at Baird, which he joined in 1958, for his  
personal research into companies and for his insistence that 
clients keep stocks they had purchased. 
</P>
</TEXT>
