<DOCNO> APW19990528.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 17:51:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Won't Release Colo. Autopsies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) -- A judge on Friday refused to release  
autopsy reports on victims of the Columbine High School shootings, 
saying it would cause substantial harm to the community. 
</P>
<P>
	Families of the victims asked the judge to seal the records  
after 19 news organizations requested the records. The Denver Post 
and Denver Rocky Mountain challenged the families' request, saying 
the autopsy reports might shed light on the attack and help prevent 
further tragedies. 
</P>
<P>
	But Jefferson County District Court Judge Henry Nieto said the  
community was traumatized by the shootings, and release of the 
reports would reopen wounds that are just beginning to heal. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like every member of this community has lost a child,''  
Nieto said. 
</P>
<P>
	Two students, Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold, charged into  
Columbine High School at lunchtime April 20, killing 12 of their 
classmates and a teacher before killing themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	Family members wept as Nieto announced his decision. Attorneys  
for the two newspapers said they have not decided whether to 
appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, authorities pulled down the crime scene tape around  
the school on Friday, as school officials prepared to allow 
students into classrooms next week to pick up books and backpacks 
left behind as students fled the carnage. 
</P>
<P>
	Marilyn Saltzman, spokeswoman for Jefferson County schools, said  
the district plans to rebuild parts of the school damaged in the 
shooting and change the layout of some rooms like the library, 
where most of the killings happened. 
</P>
</TEXT>
