<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft Calls Caldera Claim Bogus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Neither consumers nor personal computer  
makers were hurt by Microsoft's licensing practices for the MS-DOS 
operating system in the early 1990s, a Microsoft attorney argued. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard Klapper said Thursday that the contention by Caldera  
Inc. of Orem, Utah, that Microsoft deliberately used licensing to 
quash the competing DR-DOS system is bogus. 
</P>
<P>
	``Where was competition hurt here?'' he asked U.S. District  
Court Judge Dee Benson, who is hearing Caldera's antitrust case 
against the much bigger software company. 
</P>
<P>
	Caldera now owns DR-DOS, an operating system that in the late  
1980s and early 1990s was gaining a toehold against MS-DOS in the 
personal computer market. An operating system controls the basic 
functions of a computer. 
</P>
<P>
	Retail customers could have bought DR-DOS in stores, Klapper  
said. ``It was pretty clear they didn't want DR-DOS.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And manufacturers chose one of three kinds of MS-DOS licenses  
from Microsoft rather than DR-DOS, a product of DRI and later 
Novell, he said. ``They had choices and they made them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft is asking the judge to dismiss Caldera's claim that it  
kept a stranglehold on the personal computer operating system 
market with its licenses. 
</P>
<P>
	The licensing claim is one of nine aspects of Caldera's case  
that Microsoft has asked the judge to throw out. Benson is hearing 
arguments on the nine motions this week and during June. 
</P>
<P>
	Caldera, financed by former Novell chairman Ray Noorda, bought  
DR-DOS from Novell in 1996 and promptly filed the antitrust 
lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	Novell had stopped selling DR-DOS for personal computers in  
1994, but Caldera chief executive Bryan Sparks says he and Noorda 
wanted Microsoft held accountable for what they claim was 
anticompetitive behavior by a monopolist. 
</P>
<P>
	Caldera claims that personal computer manufacturers -- the  
biggest customers for operating systems -- were coerced to buy only 
Microsoft's MS-DOS. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the most economical licensing arrangement, manufacturers  
had to pay Microsoft a royalty whether they loaded MS-DOS or not, 
which made purchases of DR-DOS unlikely, Caldera says. 
</P>
<P>
	And the Redmond, Wash., company also used tactics that resulted  
in manufacturers ending their MS-DOS licensing periods with large 
account balances that could only be erased by renewing the 
licenses, Caldera alleges. 
</P>
<P>
	``A customer who had any crazy ideas about going with a  
competitor knew that his account was in jeopardy,'' Caldera 
attorney Stephen Susman argued on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Few manufacturers that signed Microsoft's restrictive licenses  
ever did business with DR-DOS, Caldera says. 
</P>
<P>
	Susman told the judge that it's silly for Microsoft to claim  
consumers could have bought DR-DOS if they preferred it over MS-DOS 
since retail sales are almost all software upgrades. Since the 
computers originally came with MS-DOS, consumers were unlikely to 
upgrade with DR-DOS. 
</P>
<P>
	Klapper said the fact Microsoft offered three kinds of licenses  
indicates it was not trying to crush DR-DOS. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, more than half of the licenses required manufacturers  
to pay only for each copy of Microsoft's operating system that they 
put in PCs or a line of PCs, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	DRI and Novell had frequent chances to go after manufacturing  
customers as their Microsoft licenses expired, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Klapper said Microsoft was using its licensing practices before  
and after DR-DOS was a competitive threat, but the judge was 
dubious. 
</P>
<P>
	He noted that the per-processor licenses -- the ones Caldera  
claims were anticompetitive -- made up the vast majority of 
Microsoft's MS-DOS licenses in precisely the years DR-DOS was 
competing against it. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge suggested that evidence alone may be sufficient for  
him to reject Microsoft's motion to dismiss and instead allow a 
jury to hear the evidence. 
</P>
<P>
	A jury trial is scheduled for January.  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
