<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Personal Income Rises 0.5 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Money is burning a hole in Americans' pockets  
as consumers in April spent nearly as much as they earned, helping 
to push the nation's savings rate to an all-time low. Spending 
climbed 0.4 percent last month, a tad lower than the 0.5 percent 
increase in Americans' personal income, the Commerce Department 
reported today. ``You can't underestimate the hedonism of the 
American consumer,'' said economist Mark Zandi of Regional 
Financial Associates in West Chester, Pa. ``But consumers have good 
reason to be out there spending. '' 

</P>
<P>
	Kosovo Refugees Pour Into Albania  
</P>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- Refugees from Kosovo continue to pour into Albania  
despite a flare-up in border fighting that has made their traumatic 
trek even more perilous, a U.N. official said today. Kris Janowski, 
a spokesman for the U.N. refugee agency, said 400 ethnic Albanians 
arrived in northern Albania yesterday amid artillery fire between 
Serb forces and separatist rebels on the Kosovo side. In Belgrade, 
Russia's top envoy for Kosovo presented a peace plan to Slobodan 
Milosevic today, as NATO took advantage of good weather to hammer 
ammunition sites and Serb forces. 

</P>
<P>
	Charity Director Resigns Amid Probe  
</P>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- The director of a distribution warehouse  
for a worldwide charity organization resigned today after he and 
six of his workers were videotaped taking what authorities believe 
were boxes of donated goods intended for the poor. Steve Highfill, 
director of the Nashville center, was the only employee to resign, 
said a Feed The Children spokeswoman in Oklahoma City. The 
Tennessee Bureau of Investigation has begun a probe into the center 
following a television report aired this week. Highfill said he saw 
nothing wrong with allowing staff to take donated items. 

</P>
<P>
	FBI Asked To Probe S.C. Dragging  
</P>
<P>
	KINGSTREE, S.C. (AP) -- A black man who was dragged by two white  
men for a quarter-mile beside their pickup truck said he's not sure 
the attack had anything to do with race. ``It could have been 
mistaken identity,'' Charone Green, who was not seriously injured 
Wednesday, told The (Columbia) State for today's editions. ``It 
could have been anything.'' Eric Jones, of Gastonia, N.C., and 
Arthur Marshall of Georgetown are to be formally charged today with 
assault and battery with intent to kill. 

</P>
<P>
	Cuban Foreign Minister Replaced  
</P>
<P>
	HAVANA (AP) -- Cuban Foreign Minister Roberto Robaina, long  
considered a leading candidate to succeed President Fidel Castro 
one day, has been replaced by Castro's 34-year-old chief of staff, 
Felipe Perez Roque, the government announced today. Robaina's plans 
were not announced and the reasons for his removal were not 
immediately clear. The reshuffling does not necessarily mean 
Robaina has lost favor. His predecessor, Ricardo Alarcon, became 
president of the National Assembly. 

</P>
<P>
	IRA Hands Over Remains of Victim  
</P>
<P>
	BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- The Irish Republican Army  
handed over the suspected remains of one of its long-missing 
victims today, starting a process that politicians hope will 
breathe fresh life into Northern Ireland's ailing peace accord. 
Eamon Molloy, a former IRA member who was killed by his comrades in 
1975 for allegedly informing on them to police, was one of nine 
people killed and secretly buried by the IRA that the outlawed 
group has pledged to locate. A group called Families of the 
Disappeared has campaigned for recovery of the bodies for five 
years. 

</P>
<P>
	Lion Kills Warden in Namibia  
</P>
<P>
	WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) -- A lion killed a game warden at a  
private lodge outside Namibia's capital while nine horrified 
tourists looked on helplessly, local media reported today. Steyn 
Lusse was attacked yesterday inside the lions' enclosure on the 
popular Okapuka game farm outside Windhoek as he tried to free up a 
mechanism used to feed the lions. Witnesses say Lusse ignored 
warnings from the group of tourists from the United Kingdom, the 
United States and South Africa that one of the lions was stalking 
him. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Gains 89, Nasdaq Up 33  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 2 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
up 89.68 points at 10,556.61. Advancers on the New York Stock 
Exchange outnumbered decliners 1,888-940. The Nasdaq Composite 
Index was up 33.92 at 2,453.07. 

</P>
