<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NY Braces for Clinton-Guiliani Bout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Clash of the Titans! Better than the Coney  
Island roller coaster! A spectacle to rival Niagara Falls? 
</P>
<P>
	If Hillary Rodham Clinton enters New York's Senate race, it  
could be the state's wildest ever -- a sitting first lady pitted 
against the Big Apple's mayor in a campaign one political veteran 
thinks could be ``the all-time meanest, nastiest race ever in New 
York.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What started as cocktail party chatter a few months ago  
apparently is about to break on Broadway with Mrs. Clinton in the 
starring role for the Senate seat being vacated next year by 
Democrat Daniel Patrick Moynihan. 
</P>
<P>
	She has called 200 New York politicians for advice, is learning  
exactly where Penn Yan is and apparently wants to drag her husband, 
the president, off to the wilds of the Adirondack Mountains or the 
windswept expanse of eastern Long Island for summer vacation. 
</P>
<P>
	She has gone so far as to ask state Democratic chairwoman Judith  
Hope to scout out living rooms in rural upstate New York where the 
folks might want to share coffee and cookies with a first lady. 
</P>
<P>
	The first couple is vacationing in Florida this Memorial Day  
weekend. When they return, top advisers say, Mrs. Clinton will 
either announce she is not running or will press ahead. If advisers 
get the green light, there would be an exploratory committee formed 
in late June or early July with a full-fledged candidacy sometime 
in the fall or later. 
</P>
<P>
	Hope and other advisers expect Mrs. Clinton -- who has never  
worked, lived or studied in the Empire State -- to enter the race, 
which could pit her against New York City's hard-nosed Republican 
mayor, Rudolph Giuliani. 
</P>
<P>
	``Giuliani, because of his nature, will throw every vile charge  
he can dream up at her,'' said former New York Mayor Edward Koch, a 
Democrat. ``I think she can beat him, but it will be a very tough 
race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other prominent New York Democrats agree.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think Rudy and company will fight a pretty nasty battle,''  
said former Mayor David Dinkins, who beat Giuliani in 1989, only to 
lose to him in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	``It could be the all-time meanest, nastiest race ever in New  
York,'' state Comptroller H. Carl McCall said. 
</P>
<P>
	Should Mrs. Clinton run, New York's political pros say she will  
not only face a brutal campaign, but could wind up hurting 
Democrats elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	And, on the Republican side, one veteran operative thinks the  
price of beating her may be so high as to leave any GOP winner with 
a ``Pyrrhic victory.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``She's going to take advantage of how she's perceived right  
now, which is as first lady, mother, wronged wife, feminist 
champion, humanitarian, martyr. She's going to run as St. Joan of 
Arc ... Eleanor Roosevelt reincarnated,'' GOP consultant Jay 
Severin said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The sobering news for Republicans is that anybody who plans to  
beat her is going to have to knock her off every one of those 
pedestals ... and the cost of doing that is very high,'' he added. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to being attacked as a carpetbagger, Mrs. Clinton  
will face questions again over Whitewater, Travelgate, her good 
fortune investing in cattle futures and her husband's infidelity. 
</P>
<P>
	She got a taste of that Wednesday when CBS' Dan Rather asked her  
what she would answer when asked, ``Why are you still with this 
man?'' 
</P>
<P>
	She noted they had been married for nearly 24 years.  
</P>
<P>
	There is also talk among some party stalwarts that by running a  
high-profile and expensive race in heavily Democratic New York, 
Mrs. Clinton could damage Vice President Al Gore's chances of 
moving up to the White House and even the party's chances of taking 
back Congress. She is considered one of the party's most effective 
campaigners. 
</P>
<P>
	``New York is one place where (Gore) needs her less,'' McCall  
said. ``He'd rather have her in Nebraska.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the carpetbagger charges will force her to stay in New York,  
said William Cunningham, a former Moynihan campaign manager. 
</P>
<P>
	``If she runs in New York, she will not be available to campaign  
in other critical states and districts. That affects not only Gore 
but the whole effort to take back the House,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
