<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grains, Livestock Up; Oil Down  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The prospect of hot, dry weather sent corn and soybean future  
prices surging Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Livestock futures prices also advanced, while oils and metals  
declined in sessions shortened to get a jump on the three-day 
Memorial Day weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn and soybean prices on the Chicago Board of Trade were  
boosted by reports of a possible high-pressure ridge forming next 
week in the U.S. Midwest, which could result in hot, dry conditions 
for newly planted crops. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're getting to June, and in June, July and August, there's  
always talk about the weather,'' said Dick Loewy, president of 
AgResource Co. in Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	But Loewy said there was little evidence of a drought pattern  
and believes the rally was mainly due to an oversold market as 
traders tried to even up their holdings to reduce risk before the 
long weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat continued to recover from new contract lows set on Monday  
as prices were supported by the prospects of more rain-induced crop 
disease. Reports from Oklahoma told of severe crop damage from hail 
earlier his week. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for July delivery settled 2 1/4 cents higher at $2.52 1/4 a  
bushel; July corn rose 3 cents to $2.19 1/2 a bushel; July oats rose 2 
cents to $1.23 a bushel; July soybeans rose 4 1/2 cents to $4.61 3/4 a 
bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Livestock prices were higher on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.  
</P>
<P>
	June live cattle reached a new six-week peak as traders  
anticipated a holiday weekend that would have consumers grilling 
hamburgers and driving up the demand for boxed beef. 
</P>
<P>
	Following cattle's strength, live hogs rebounded after hitting  
an eight-week low on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	June live cattle was .75 cent higher to 64.25 cents a pound;  
August feeder cattle rose .82 cent to 75.52 cents a pound; June 
lean hogs climbed .78 cent to 52.95 cents a pound; July pork 
bellies was up .65 cent to 53.37 cents a pound. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude oil and gasoline future prices tumbled on the New York  
Mercantile Exchange as some refineries reported production cutbacks 
due to a lack of demand. 
</P>
<P>
	Natural gas prices extended gains from Thursday, when traders  
received news that storage statistics were below market 
expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	Light sweet crude for delivery in July fell 33 cents to $16.84 a  
barrel, June unleaded gasoline dropped 1.32 cents to 48.58 cents a 
gallon, June heating oil fell .82 cent to 39.43 cents a gallon, but 
July natural gas was up 7.8 cents at $2.36 per 1,000 cubic feet. 
</P>
<P>
	Precious metal future prices were lower on the New York  
Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	July silver hit a six-week low of $4.88 late in the session,  
continuing a decline that started Thursday with the news of a large 
Australian sale of the metal and a reaction to cooper futures 
plunging to 12-year lows. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold for August delivery settled at $272 a troy ounce, down 20  
cents; while June silver was $4.89.5 a troy ounce, down 4.5 cents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
