<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bowman To Return As Red Wings Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Retirement simply doesn't appeal to Scotty  
Bowman. 
</P>
<P>
	Stopping just short of labeling himself a lifer, the most  
successful coach in NHL history said he'll return to the Detroit 
Red Wings next season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it would have been difficult not to come back,'' the  
65-year-old Bowman said during a conference call Friday with 
general manager Ken Holland. ``I looked at the alternatives and 
they didn't look very good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bowman, who got his first coaching job with a Montreal junior  
team in 1955, wouldn't discuss terms of his contract, but it is 
believed to be for one year with options that will allow him to 
continue for as long as he wants. 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Wings made it clear long ago that he will always have a  
place in the organization. 
</P>
<P>
	``We met a couple of days ago and discussed the opportunity to  
come back,'' Bowman said. ``I had pretty much decided by the end of 
the season to make the decision pretty quickly. 
</P>
<P>
	``We didn't get the job done this year ... and we have the right  
mix and with a few minor changes we should be able to contend again 
next year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The decision came 10 days after the Red Wings were ousted from  
the playoffs in their bid for a third straight Stanley Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would have been a huge loss if Scotty had decided not to  
coach,'' Holland said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bowman, who has won eight Stanley Cups, had angioplasty last  
July and knee replacement surgery in August. He missed all of 
training camp and the first five games this past season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I missed it when I was out,'' he said. ``Not being with the  
team is tough.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bowman, whose brother died during heart surgery last June, had  
said he would not return unless cleared by his doctor. 
</P>
<P>
	He appeared to be leaning toward remaining behind the bench  
shortly after Detroit was eliminated in six games by Colorado in 
the second round of the playoffs. He said he was intrigued by the 
prospect of coaching in the year 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	``Coaching in another decade is something that's there,'' Bowman  
said. ``It won't go away. But I'm actually more excited about 
coaching in 2000. If you get there, it means you had to play pretty 
well before Christmas.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bowman has a 1,100-516-284 regular-season record and a 204-116  
playoff record, the most victories of any NHL coach. His eight 
Stanley Cup titles match the number won by Toe Blake with Montreal. 
</P>
<P>
	Bowman came to Detroit in 1993 and quickly turned the Red Wings  
into an NHL power. The team won the Cup in 1997 and 1998, lost in 
the Cup finals to New Jersey in 1995 and played in the Western 
Conference finals in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Since having his arteries unblocked in July, Bowman has lowered  
his blood pressure and cholesterol through diet. 
</P>
<P>
	He remains devoted to daily workouts meant to improve mobility  
of his titanium knee. When his natural knee became so arthritic he 
hardly could walk to his car and needed a cane, Bowman decided to 
have the operation. Since then, he has regained 80 percent 
mobility. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he no longer has pain and did not doubt his decision to  
return for this past season. 
</P>
<P>
	So, is he a lifer?  
</P>
<P>
	``Bob Johnson used to put it pretty well when we were at  
Pittsburgh,'' Bowman said. ``He related it to golf. I know I'm on 
the back nine. I don't know what hole I'm on, but I'm out there 
somewhere.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990528.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 06:51:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chickenpox Vaccine Urged for Kids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- All states should require chickenpox vaccinations  
for children entering day care or elementary school, federal health 
officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The requirements are recommended because the highly contagious  
disease is most prevalent among children ages 1 to 6, the Centers 
for Disease Control and Prevention said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 4 million Americans, mostly children, get chickenpox every  
year. Caused by the varicella virus, it typically just causes 
severe itching and rash in children. 
</P>
<P>
	The CDC estimates that in 1990-94, before the vaccination became  
available, about 100 people in the United States died each year 
from chickenpox complications such as pneumonia, hemorrhaging and 
blood infections. As many as 11,000 were hospitalized each year. 
</P>
<P>
	Researchers don't have precise numbers on how many people are  
dying now that the vaccine is available. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is data out there to suggest that deaths are continuing  
to occur,'' said Dr. Jane Seward of the CDC's National Immunization 
Program. ``It's not a lot compared to other vaccine-preventable 
diseases, but it's too many when you've got a way to prevent 
them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The vaccine is 80 to 90 percent effective, and protects against  
the most severe symptoms of chickenpox in all cases, according to 
the CDC. 
</P>
<P>
	The Food and Drug Administration approved the nation's first  
chickenpox vaccine, Varivax, in 1995 and the CDC and the American 
Academy of Pediatrics had recommended vaccinating children for 
chickenpox at 12 to 18 months. 
</P>
<P>
	Colorado, Maryland, Massachusetts, Michigan, Oklahoma, Oregon,  
Rhode Island, Tennessee, Texas, Virginia and Washington, D.C., have 
already passed laws requiring vaccinations for children. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990528.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 16:31:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Broad, Ovitz Might Join NFL Forces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Just two weeks after billionaire Eli Broad  
said he had no plans to join forces with Hollywood super agent 
Michael Ovitz to get an NFL team back in Los Angeles, the 
invitation was in the mail. 
</P>
<P>
	Broad wrote a letter to Ovitz and food magnate Ron Burkle on  
Thursday suggesting the chief rival to his group ``join our effort 
to obtain the expansion franchise.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this month, Broad implied he was confident his group  
would be successful in its quest to own the NFL's 32nd franchise, 
tentatively scheduled to begin play in 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	The letter did not say who would lead the combined effort, but  
the implication was it would be the Broad team. 
</P>
<P>
	``We still have those last few yards to go before reaching the  
end zone,'' Broad wrote. ``To help us all get there, Ed Roski and I 
would like to extend an invitation for you to join our effort to 
obtain the expansion franchise. 
</P>
<P>
	``Gentlemen, your joining us will send a clear message to the  
National Football League that we are committed to the success of 
professional football in Los Angeles.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Broad alluded to the rival group's star power, telling Ovitz his  
``talent for marketing and promotions is world-renowned and will 
advance our mutual efforts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	James Ellis, an attorney for Ovitz, said Friday his client and  
Burkle remain committed to bringing football to Los Angeles, and 
``doing whatever it takes to ensure a successful franchise is 
established here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Whether that's uniting with Broad remains to be seen.  
</P>
<P>
	David Carter, a sports business analyst, believes each side  
needs the other. 
</P>
<P>
	``Clearly, both have suffered setbacks in the last week to 10  
days,'' Carter said. ``Obviously, if Broad was in a real position 
of strength, you would not have expected him to extend the olive 
branch to Ovitz.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Carter believes the plan needs Broad for his money and Ovitz for  
his creativity. 
</P>
<P>
	Ovitz was in the Bahamas on Friday and unavailable for comment.  
</P>
<P>
	At its March meetings in Phoenix, the NFL tentatively awarded  
Los Angeles the franchise over Houston. But the league told Los 
Angeles it needed to come up with a viable plan by Sept. 15. 
</P>
<P>
	The NFL has said it intends to put a team in a 76-year-old,  
reconstructed Coliseum. But it has yet to name a price or choose an 
owner. 
</P>
<P>
	Broad and Roski head one faction, while Ovitz has gathered a  
star-powered group that includes Burkle, actor Tom Cruise and 
former Los Angeles Lakers star Magic Johnson. 
</P>
<P>
	A potential challenger to those groups surfaced recently when  
billionaire Marvin Davis obtained a signed option agreement from 
the Hollywood Park racetrack for 100 acres of land to develop a 
football stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	In Atlanta this week, Ovitz presented NFL owners with a plan  
intended to meet the league's specifications. Chief among those was 
that Exposition Park be altered to accommodate 25,000 parking 
spaces -- more than double the park's existing space. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ovitz plan would meet the NFL goal, but at a possible cost  
of more than $200 million in public financing. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Broad was on hand to tell league officials why  
Ovitz's plan could not win the necessary approvals, much less the 
public financing. 
</P>
<P>
	The NFL tentatively endorsed Ovitz's proposal but said it needed  
more review time. 
</P>
<P>
	``Southern California taxpayers and politicians will not allow  
for the magnitude of that subsidy,'' Carter said. ``Ovitz's plan 
has some financial holes in it, Broad's plan doesn't have the 
sizzle that Ovitz's plans have. 
</P>
<P>
	``(NFL commissioner) Paul Tagliabue has talked about plan A and  
plan B, what he is hoping to do is have those two parties work 
together to have a plan C -- pull the marketing elements out of 
Ovitz's plan, and the financial elements out of Broad's plan. 
</P>
<P>
	``The NFL is clearly trying to make these guys work together in  
order to maximize the amount of money to the NFL.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tagliabue and some owners have suggested the groups might want  
to work together. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
