<DOCNO> APW19990528.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 07:11:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> L.A. Football Rivals May Join Forces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Billionaire Eli Broad sent a letter to  
Hollywood magnet Michael Ovitz in an apparent effort to end the 
conflict over who will own the NFL franchise in Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	Broad wrote a letter Thursday to chief rival Ovitz and food  
magnate Ron Burkle stating the two groups should end their 
differences and present a united plan to the NFL. It did not 
specify who would lead the combined effort. 
</P>
<P>
	``We still have those last few yards to go before reaching the  
end zone,'' Broad wrote. ``To help us all get there, Ed Roski and I 
would like to extend an invitation for you to join our effort to 
obtain the expansion franchise.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The league has said it intends to put a team in the 76-year-old  
Coliseum by 2002, but it still has not named a price or picked an 
owner. 
</P>
<P>
	``Gentlemen, your joining us will send a clear message to the  
National Football League that we are committed to the success of 
professional football in Los Angeles,'' Broad wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	In his letter, Broad alluded to the rival group's star power,  
telling Ovitz his ``talent for marketing and promotions is 
world-renowned and will advance our mutual efforts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Ovitz group includes such heavy hitters as former Los  
Angeles Lakers star Magic Johnson and actor Tom Cruise. 
</P>
<P>
	Ovitz told the Los Angeles Times in a story published today he  
intended to stick with his own plan. He declined to comment on 
joining forces with Broad's group. 
</P>
<P>
	``If Eli has something that makes good sense, then I'm willing  
to listen,'' Ovitz told the Times, after being contacted on his way 
to the Bahamas. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this week, the two competing groups presented their  
plans during NFL meetings in Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ovitz group plan included a lavish parking garage with a  
park on top. The NFL tentatively endorsed the proposal, but said it 
wanted more time to review it. 
</P>
<P>
	NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue and some owners this week had  
suggested that the two groups work together. 
</P>
</TEXT>
