<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Rise on Heat Worry / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean future prices rose  
significantly early today on the Chicago Board of Trade as weather 
forecasts had investors worried. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders, preparing for the three-day Memorial Day weekend,  
talked of a possible high-pressure ridge forming next week in the 
U.S. Midwest, which could result in hot, dry conditions in corn and 
soybeans growing areas. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat was boosted by concerns about disease outbreaks and hail  
damage, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for July delivery rose 2 1/2 cents to $2.52 1/2 a bushel; July  
corn rose 3 1/2 cents to $2.20 a bushel; July oats rose 1 3/4 cent to 
$1.21 3/4 a bushel; July soybeans rose 5 3/4 cents to $4.63 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Livestock prices were mostly higher on the Chicago Mercantile  
Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	June live cattle rose .12 cent to 63.62 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle climbed .05 cent to 74.75 cents a pound; June lean 
hogs fell .25 cent to 51.92 cents a pound; July pork bellies went 
up .53 cent to 53.25 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
