<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Rebound; Dow Up 88.11 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were rebounding today from Thursday's  
steep selloff as new economic data showing slower-than-expected 
growth helped calm fears about rising inflation and higher interest 
rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors also jumped at the chance to pick up shares at cheaper  
prices as a result of this week's turbulent slump on Wall Street. 
</P>
<P>
	At 2 p.m., the Dow Jones industrial average was up 88.11 at  
10,555.04. The blue-chip index rose as much as 120 points in 
morning trading. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, the Dow plunged more than 235 points, or by 2.2  
percent, in its steepest one-day point drop since Sept. 30, 1998, 
when the Dow tumbled 237.20. 
</P>
<P>
	Broad-market indexes also rose today. After some weakness in  
early trading, the Nasdaq composite index, which has been battered 
recently by a steep decline in Internet stocks, was up 24.99 at 
2,444.14. 
</P>
<P>
	Trading was light ahead of the three-day holiday weekend. U.S.  
financial markets will be closed Monday in observance of Memorial 
Day. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow has been seesawing all week with declines of more than 1  
percent on both Monday and Tuesday, then a rebound of more than 1 
percent on Wednesday before Thursday's slide. Heading into today's 
session, the average was down 362.35 points, or by 3.3 percent, for 
the week. 
</P>
<P>
	The volatile ride on Wall Street has been fueled by fears that  
any signs of rising inflation will prompt the Federal Reserve to 
raise interest rates to prevent the economy from overheating. 
Higher rates typically cut into profits as it becomes more 
expensive for companies to borrow money. 
</P>
<P>
	``We still are in a tug-of-war between those people who thing  
interest rates will go higher and those that don't,'' said Alan 
Ackerman, senior vice president at Fahnestock &AMP; Co. 
</P>
<P>
	But some of the fears about rising inflation and interest rates  
were tempered today after the Purchasing Management Association of 
Chicago reported a greater-than-expected drop in its business 
activity index. 
</P>
<P>
	That helped boost stocks, especially banks and financial  
services shares, which have been hurt by concerns over an 
interest-rate hike. Citigroup was up 2 1/4 at 65 11/16 and Merrill 
Lynch was up 1 3/4 at 84 3/4. 
</P>
<P>
	A flood of bargain-hunters entering the market today also helped  
lift stocks. Investors were looking to pick up stocks at much 
cheaper prices than they were just a week ago. Microsoft rose 2 to 
80 3/8, and Amazon.com gained 3 13/16 to 118 3/8. 
</P>
<P>
	General Motors was among the strongest Dow components, rising 2  
5/16 to 70 13/16 after completing the spinoff of its Delphi 
Automotive unit. Delphi shares were down 3/4 at 19 3/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 2-to-1 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 451.81 million 
shares, down from 534.22 million shares on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 19.24 at 1,300.65, the  
NYSE composite index was up 8.44 at 622.46, and the American Stock 
Exchange composite index was up 3.75 at 778.14. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
