<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vintage Chinese Movies Saved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- A hundred Chinese films from the 1950s and  
'60s were saved from a garbage bin and will be shipped to a Hong 
Kong archive. 
</P>
<P>
	The black-and-white Cantonese movies, which include features on  
Hong Kong folk hero and martial-arts master Wong Fei-Hung, were 
thrown away Tuesday from a leaky restaurant basement where they had 
been stored for years. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe this is a historical record that needs to be  
preserved, and the film industry of that time deserves to be 
recognized,'' said Brian Lau, director of the San Francisco Asian 
American Film Festival. Film experts rescued the movies. 
</P>
<P>
	Ruby Yang and her husband, San Francisco film producer Lambert  
Yam, spent two days rummaging through the cinematic treasure, 
salvaging about half of the 200 film canisters. 
</P>
<P>
	Betty Gee, who sold the Golden Bull restaurant two years ago,  
left the canisters because she had no place for them. The films 
belonged to her late father-in-law, a onetime Hong Kong film 
director who ran a San Francisco Chinese theater until about 10 
years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The films eventually will be sent to the Hong Kong Film Archive.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
