<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Albanian Army Stages War Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KUKES, Albania (AP) -- Firing hundreds of artillery shells and  
rockets toward the embattled Kosovo frontier on Friday, the 
Albanian army simulated a defense of its territory against a 
cross-border strike by Serbian forces. 
</P>
<P>
	The war games involved tanks, howitzers and 1,200 ground troops  
maneuvering several miles from the border, where Serbian forces 
have clashed with guerrillas of the Kosovo Liberation Army in 
recent days. 
</P>
<P>
	Western military sources said NATO tried unsuccessfully to stop  
the exercise, fearing a Serbian military response in an area packed 
with more than 100,000 Kosovo refugees and international aid agency 
personnel. 
</P>
<P>
	But NATO spokesman Jamie Shea played down any objections within  
the alliance. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not that we are unhappy about it,'' Shea said, noting  
that Albania has been fired upon by the Serbs and ``has the right 
to take any steps which it deems necessary to defend itself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He added, however, that helicopter flights of refugees had been  
suspended during the exercise. 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter sent Thursday to the U.N. refugee agency in Tirana  
and Kukes, the NATO-led force in Albania said that in its 
assessment ``the conduct of a military exercise so close to the 
border with Kosovo could elicit a Serbian artillery response.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It said ``prudent protective measures should be followed during  
and immediately after any live firing of artillery or other major 
weapons by the Albanian army.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There was no report of a response from the Serbs, dug in just  
behind the key border crossing point at Morini. 
</P>
<P>
	``Perhaps the Serbs will shoot back, but we are not afraid of  
them. We are going to defend our borders, our area,'' said Kukes 
military commander Gen. Kujdesi Lamaj. 
</P>
<P>
	The 20,000-strong Albanian army is widely regarded as inferior  
to the Serb military machine. It nearly collapsed two years ago 
when a failed pyramid investment scheme sparked enraged citizens to 
storm barracks and loot armories. 
</P>
<P>
	Observed by Albanian President Rexhep Meidani and the country's  
top government leaders and military officers, Albanian troops fired 
off artillery and tank shells as well as rockets. 
</P>
<P>
	Several foreign military observers, including U.S. and British  
personnel, were also present. The scenario for the exercise was a 
defense of the Kukes area from a hypothetical Serbian attack. 
</P>
<P>
	Target areas for the Albanian fire were hillsides located  
several miles from the Morini checkpoint. 
</P>
<P>
	An Albanian man was evacuated during the war games by a U.S.  
military helicopter. One report said he was a soldier, but other 
sources said a civilian was shot and severely wounded when he 
attempted to steal a tractor from refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees, which processes  
refugees at Morini, pulled out during the exercise and warned 
journalists to exercise caution. 
</P>
<P>
	``UNHCR is very concerned that this could draw incoming  
artillery fire from the Serb side with disastrous effects for the 
refugees,'' spokesman Kris Janowski said in Geneva, referring to 
tens of thousands of Kosovo Albanian refugees concentrated in the 
Kukes area. 
</P>
<P>
	UNHCR personnel also withdrew from Morini, less than 30 miles  
from Kukes, on Thursday when the Serbs and KLA guerrillas traded 
gunfire for a second day. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the clashes, UNHCR spokesman Rupert Colville said 436  
refugees crossed the border at Morini from Kosovo. Another 542 
refugees left Kukes refugees camps on Friday as part of an 
organized relocation to safer camps in central and southern 
Albania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990528.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 15:51:03 </DATE_TIME>
