<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Overturns US Air Union Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federal court panel ruled Friday that a 1997  
union election in which US Airways passenger service employees 
decided to join the Communications Workers of America should be set 
aside. 
</P>
<P>
	The Circuit Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia ruled  
that a lower court judge was wrong to throw out a prior election in 
which the employees voted against joining the CWA. 
</P>
<P>
	Following the earlier election, the National Mediation Board  
ruled that the airline had tainted the vote by holding 
employer-employee roundtable discussions. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, Appeals Court judge Laurence Silberman wrote for the  
three-judge panel that ``the board's order unconstitutionally 
restrained US Airways' speech leading up to the rerun election.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the first vote, held Jan. 30, 1997, some 9,272 workers were  
eligible to vote, but the Communications Workers fell short of a 
majority with only 3,973 voting to join. The CWA appealed to the 
mediation board and won. 
</P>
<P>
	In the second vote, held Sept. 29, 1997, 4,773 people, or 54  
percent of the 8,772 employees eligible, voted in favor. The 
airline appealed that vote to the U.S. District Court and lost. 
</P>
<P>
	Either the mediation board or the Communications Workers of  
America could appeal Friday's ruling to the full Circuit Court or 
to the Supreme Court. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990528.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 15:36:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda Declares Cease-Fire in Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KIGALI, Rwanda (AP) -- Rwanda declared a unilateral cease-fire  
Friday in Congo, where it has been backing the rebels fighting to 
oust Congolese President Laurent Kabila. The declaration appeared 
to challenge Kabila to comply. 
</P>
<P>
	Foreign Minister Amri Sued Ismael said in a news conference that  
the cease-fire will take effect at midnight local time (6 p.m. EDT) 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is to enhance chances for a negotiated settlement in  
Congo,'' Sued told reporters. ``We shall see tomorrow how the other 
parties will react. If they don't respect our unilateral 
declaration, then we shall evaluate our position.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni and Kabila signed a cease-fire  
agreement on April 18 that was mediated by Libyan leader Moammar 
Gadhafi. But Rwanda and the Congolese rebels rejected the deal as 
premature and said it was reached without their consultation. 
</P>
<P>
	Relations between Rwanda and Uganda have since been strained  
over how to end the Congolese war, and the tension has helped to 
widen rifts between rebel factions. 
</P>
<P>
	Sued denied the declaration had anything to do with Libyan  
troops arriving in Uganda earlier this week in what Libya said was 
the ``vanguard'' of an African force to monitor the peace deal 
signed in April. Under the deal, foreign peacekeepers would be 
deployed only after a cease-fire, but none had been declared until 
now. 
</P>
<P>
	With the help of troops and equipment from Rwanda and Uganda,  
Congolese rebels have captured the eastern third of the country 
since they took up arms in August. They accuse Kabila of nepotism, 
corruption and ethnic warmongering. 
</P>
<P>
	Congolese rebels could not be reached for comment, but Rwandan  
officials said the main rebel group had agreed to participate in 
the cease-fire. 
</P>
<P>
	Congo's information minister, Didier Mumengi, reached in the  
Congolese capital, Kinshasa, said Rwandan defense minister and top 
strategist, Paul Kagame, ``has been trapped'' by Uganda's signing 
of a peace deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Congolese Justice Minister Mwenze Kongolo was reportedly heading  
to Kampala, Uganda, Friday to hold talks with Libyan and Ugandan 
officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Rwanda is operating with rebels in the central and southern  
portion of eastern Congo, while Uganda is backing rebel forces 
further north. 
</P>
<P>
	In Kampala, the independent Monitor newspaper reported Friday  
that troops and anti-aircraft equipment had been withdrawn from 
several towns in eastern Congo that are held by the rebels and 
their Rwandan allies. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Rwanda and Uganda have said they are fighting in Congo to  
secure their borders from armed groups operating in the east, and 
they have blamed Kabila for neglecting to secure the areas. 
</P>
<P>
	Rwanda has said it will not stop fighting or withdraw troops  
until at least 5,000 Hutu militiamen responsible for the 1994 
genocide in Rwanda and fighting alongside Kabila's army are 
defeated or disarmed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990528.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 06:11:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Asian Stock Markets Close Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian stock markets ended the week sharply  
lower Friday on the back of a tumble overnight on Wall Street. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo's benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average lost 204.51  
points, or 1.26 percent, to finish the day at 15,972.68. On 
Thursday, the Nikkei index shed 53.33 points, or 0.33 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices fell because investors were worried about a possible  
slowdown in the U.S. economy following Thursday's plunge in New 
York stock prices. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wall Street overnight, the Dow Jones industrial average sank  
235.23 points to 10,466.93, its worst single-session decline of the 
year and its lowest level since April 20. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo stock prices fell sharply in the morning as investors  
dumped export-oriented shares such as telecommunications and 
electronics issues after their U.S. counterparts fell. 
</P>
<P>
	But in the afternoon domestic institutional investors began  
buying shares seen as having strong earnings potential, pulling the 
market off its lows. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the U.S. dollar was quoted at 120.52 yen, down 1.91  
yen from late Thursday in Tokyo but above its late New York level 
of 120.38 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesian shares tumbled as jittery investors took profits in  
view of possible clashes during a large election campaign rally, 
weak regional sentiment and Thursday's fall on Wall Street. 
</P>
<P>
	Security was tight when hundreds of thousands of people jammed  
Jakarta's main streets in a show of support for Indonesian 
presidential frontrunner Megawati Sukarnoputri. 
</P>
<P>
	Tensions were rising elsewhere in Indonesia with clashes between  
rival parties leaving at least 20 injured. Indonesia holds a 
parliamentary election early next month. 
</P>
<P>
	The Jakarta Stock Exchange's Composite Index fell 19.467 points,  
or 3.2 percent, to 583.649. 
</P>
<P>
	In Hong Kong, the blue-chip Hang Seng Index fell 2 percent, or  
249.28 points, closing at 12,059.25. On Thursday, the index had 
slumped 100.63 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Brokers said investors dumped shares in reaction to Thursday's  
slide on Wall Street. 
</P>
<P>
	Worries over U.S.-China relations strained by U.S. allegations  
that China has stolen American nuclear secrets also dampen market 
sentiment, they said. 
</P>
<P>
	Going against the trend was the Seoul Stock Exchange, where the  
key index rose for a fourth consecutive session in reaction to the 
rise of the Japanese yen against the U.S. dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	A stronger yen helps South Korean companies gain a competitive  
edge against their Japanese rivals since they compete directly in 
such industries as semiconductors, steel and automobiles. 
</P>
<P>
	The Korea Composite Stock Price Index rose 5.58 points, or 0.7  
percent, to 732.24. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Thai share prices closed sharply lower. The Stock  
Exchange of Thailand Index fell 10.68 points, or 2.3 percent, to 
453.60. 
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Share price closed sharply lower as investor sentiment  
was damped by falls in U.S. as well as regional stock markets. The 
market's key Weighted Stock Price Index fell 81.64 points, or 1.1 
percent, to 7,387.37. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices closed lower. The benchmark  
NZSE-40 Capital Index fell 12.51 points, or 0.5 percent, to 
2,114.21. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippines shares closed lower, pulled by the slump on  
Wall Street. The Philippine Stock Exchange index of 30 selected 
companies lost 10.6 points, or 0.4 percent, to 2,392.28. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: The Australian share market closed lower. The All  
Ordinaries Index fell 16.1 points, or 0.55 percent, to 2,888.6. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Malaysian share prices closed lower in line with  
regional markets. The benchmark Composite Index, which tracks 100 
blue-chip stocks, fell 11.31 points, or 1.4 percent, to 749.03. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Share prices closed mostly lower. The Straits Times  
Index fell 12.09 points, or 0.63 percent, to 1,903.68. 
</P>
</TEXT>
