<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan Cigarettes May Get New Names </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- A Taiwan health official said Friday that  
the country's most popular brands of cigarettes -- Longevity, 
President and Paradise -- may have to be renamed because they 
suggest that smoking is good. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Health Administration plans to propose a law that  
bans cigarette names suggesting ``positive values,'' said Chen 
Tsai-chin, an NHA department head. 
</P>
<P>
	Taiwan needs to tighten its smoking law further because surveys  
show that an alarming 47 percent of males and 5 percent of females 
smoke cigarettes regularly, Chen said. 
</P>
<P>
	But an official at the government-run Bureau of Wine and Tobacco  
Monopoly, maker of Taiwan's leading cigarette brands, wondered if 
such a law would require the banning of foreign brands such as 
Lucky Strike and Virginia Slims. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
