<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Father Pleads Guilty in Kidnap Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) -- Florida socialite Stephen Fagan pleaded  
guilty to kidnapping Friday, admitting he took his two girls 20 
years ago and told them their mother was dead. 
</P>
<P>
	Under terms of the deal, Fagan, who invented a life for himself  
and his girls in Florida, must pay a $100,000 fine, to be given to 
the New England Home for Little Wanderers. The charity was chosen 
by his ex-wife, Barbara Kurth. 
</P>
<P>
	Kurth was in court, but chose not to speak. It was the first  
time she, her daughters and her ex-husband had been in the same 
room together since he took the girls from her home. 
</P>
<P>
	Fagan received a suspended three- to five-year state prison  
sentence and must serve probation for five years. He was also 
ordered to perform 2,000 hours of community service at the 
Department of Veterans Affairs Medical Center in West Palm Beach, 
Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	Fagan would have faced up to 20 years in prison if convicted of  
two counts of kidnapping. 
</P>
<P>
	In October 1979, Fagan allegedly kidnapped the two girls, then 2  
and 5, from Massachusetts and moved them to Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	Fagan, 57, who has been free on $250,000 bail, claims he rescued  
the girls from an unfit and alcoholic mother. The courts at the 
time, he said after his arrest, didn't look kindly on a father 
seeking custody. 
</P>
<P>
	Kurth, who was divorced from Fagan in 1978, denies the charge  
and said she was suffering from narcolepsy, an illness that causes 
sudden, deep sleep. 
</P>
<P>
	Fagan was living under the assumed name Dr. William Martin when  
he was arrested in his Palm Beach, Fla., mansion last April after 
eluding authorities for 19 years. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time of his arrest, he was driving expensive cars and was  
a member in some of the most exclusive clubs in Palm Beach. 
</P>
<P>
	His daughters, Rachael and Lisa Martin, who are now in their  
20s, have stood by him. They have described him as supportive, 
loving, warm and kind -- a provider who did what he had to do to 
keep them safe. 
</P>
<P>
	Kurth, now a biologist at the University of Virginia, has been  
unsuccessful thus far in reuniting with her daughters, her lawyer 
has said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some legal observers questioned whether prosecutors would be  
sending the wrong message with such a lenient deal. 
</P>
<P>
	``Kidnapping is a very serious offense and it's not less serious  
because a parent commits the act,'' said Wendy Murphy, a former 
prosecutor and legal analyst. 
</P>
<P>
	Just because the daughters don't want to see their father  
imprisoned doesn't mean Fagan automatically deserves to remain 
free, Murphy said. 
</P>
<P>
	The fact that the kidnaping happened two decades ago doesn't  
lessen the seriousness of what he allegedly did, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``He would have been in a huge pile of trouble had we caught him  
sooner,'' said Murphy, who heads the Victim Advocacy and Research 
Group. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
