<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GTE Selling Local Phone Systems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- GTE Corp. is selling local telephone systems  
serving a total of 200,000 customer lines in four states. 
</P>
<P>
	Still awaiting government approval of its deal to be acquired by  
Bell Atlantic, GTE is selling 154 local exchanges with 186,839 
access lines in Arizona, California, and Minnesota to Citizens 
Utilities Co. for $664 million in cash. 
</P>
<P>
	GTE also agreed to sell 12 local exchanges with 20,564 access  
lines in Alaska to the Alaska Telephone Exchange Acquisition Corp. 
for an undisclosed amount. 
</P>
<P>
	The two deals are part of GTE's previously announced plan to  
sell about 1.6 million lines in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Citizens, based in Stamford, Conn., already has local exchange  
properties serving 1 million access lines in 13 states. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal announced Thursday represents all of GTE's local phone  
properties in Arizona, which cover about 8,000 lines, and in 
Minnesota, which cover about 128,000 lines. The California 
properties being sold serve nearly 51,000 lines. 
</P>
<P>
	Alaska Telephone Exchange is an alliance of four local phone  
companies: Alaska Power &AMP; Telephone, Arctic Slope Telephone 
Association Cooperative, TelAlaska Inc., and United Utilities. 
</P>
<P>
	The consortium was formed to meet a GTE condition that the  
Alaskan properties be sold to a single purchaser. The partners 
currently provide service to 104 Alaskan communities in regions 
surrounding the GTE Alaska properties being acquired. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990528.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 00:31:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pole vaulter Hartwig Raises Snakes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EUGENE, Ore. (AP) -- Pole vaulters have a reputation for being a  
little off-beat, and Jeff Hartwig is no exception. 
</P>
<P>
	Hartwig, though, is perhaps more off the beaten track than most,  
at least in his choice of hobbies. 
</P>
<P>
	He raises and sells snakes.  
</P>
<P>
	``They're a good escape from the pressures of training and  
traveling,'' said Hartwig, the American indoor and outdoor 
record-holder in the pole vault and the favorite in Sunday's 
Prefontaine Classic, an IAAF Grand Prix meet. 
</P>
<P>
	As usual, Hartwig left his pets at home in Jonesboro, Ark. They  
include boas and pythons, some as long as 14 feet, plus a bunch of 
lizards. 
</P>
<P>
	There's always the fear that when he's gone, something unusual  
might occur. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had a neighbor who said that if Jeff's house blows away,  
there will be snakes all over the place,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	When he's home, Hartwig is mesmerized by his collection.  
</P>
<P>
	``Sometimes, I'll just look at one snake for 35 or 40 minutes,''  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In turn, Hartwig's pets are mesmerized by him.  
</P>
<P>
	``I have a 6-foot lizard,'' he said. ``He pays attention to what  
I say.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the pets are well-behaved.  
</P>
<P>
	``I can play with quite a few of them,'' Hartwig said. ``But I  
also have some meaner snakes. I can't pick them up because they'll 
bite.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One of the tamer ones is a Burmese python named Niki. He took  
her to practice, where she lolled in the steeplechase water-jump 
pit. Another, a 10 1/2-2-foot python named John, slept in Hartwig's 
water bed. Hartwig slept on top of him without a problem. 
</P>
<P>
	Hartwig is so fond of his pets that he recently built a  
600-square-foot snake room in his basement with running water in 
the cages. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a good healthy environment for them,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Hartwig has so many snakes that he's thinking about putting a  
sign outside his house that says, ``Beware of snakes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier in the year, he had 42 snakes. Then, when he was in  
Maebashi, Japan, for the World Indoor Championships in March, his 
collection nearly doubled when 39 babies were hatched. 
</P>
<P>
	``We expect 110 more babies,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	A lot of the babies are sold to pet stores.  
</P>
<P>
	Hartwig's fondness for snakes began when he was growing up in  
St. Charles, Mo., a suburb of St. Louis 
</P>
<P>
	``I was always in the woods catching snakes or whatever I could  
get,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The turning point came when a friend with a 10 1/2-foot snake moved  
and couldn't take the reptile with him. 
</P>
<P>
	``I took it off his hands,'' Hartwig said.  
</P>
<P>
	Hartwig not only is serious about caring for his pets, but also  
about pole vaulting. 
</P>
<P>
	He broke the American indoor record twice this year, raising the  
mark to 19 feet, 5 inches. Last year, he set the U.S. outdoor mark 
of 19-8 1/2 at the Goodwill Games in Uniondale, N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	He will compete in Uniondale again June 6 in the inaugural TFA  
Pro Championships, against a field including 1996 Olympic champion 
Jean Galfione of France. 
</P>
<P>
	First, Hartwig will defend his title in the Prefontaine Classic  
against an all-American field, including former U.S. record-holder 
Lawrence Johnson. Last year, Hartwig won at 19-5. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, he has even greater ambitions, such as breaking Sergei  
Bubka's world outdoor record of 20-1 3/4. Bubka's indoor mark is 20-2. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bubka's records are becoming approachable,'' Hartwig said.  
``Once, other athletes regarded him as in another class.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bubka had a foot operation and was on crutches in February, but  
he's back training and Hartwig expects the imperturbable Ukrainian 
to try for his seventh consecutive world title in Seville, Spain, 
in August. He's not sure Bubka can win again. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are too many guys jumping well and it will take an  
incredible performance by him,'' Hartwig said. 
</P>
<P>
	Considered to have the best chances to stop Bubka's remarkable  
streak are Galfione, Maksim Tarasov of Russia, Tim Lobinger and 
Danny Ecker of Germany -- and Hartwig. 
</P>
<P>
	That's if he can slither over the bar with the same charm he  
uses on his snakes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
