<HEADLINE> Bowman To Return As Red Wings Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Scotty Bowman will return to coach the Detroit  
Red Wings, a source said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Bowman, 65, and Red Wings general manager Ken Holland were  
expected to make the announcement Friday in a joint teleconference 
with reporters, but a league source confirmed that Bowman intends 
to stay on. 
</P>
<P>
	Bowman appeared to be leaning toward remaining behind the bench  
shortly after Detroit was eliminated in six games by Colorado in 
the second round of this season's playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are a lot of pluses to coming back and a few minuses,''  
Bowman said then. ``You want to make sure. It would be nice to 
coach in the year 2000. I'm just intrigued. 
</P>
<P>
	``As far as coaching in five decades, it's more of a thrill the  
first time to do it. It's the satisfaction of staying in the 
game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bowman, the most successful coach in NHL history, has a  
1,100-516-284 regular season mark and a 204-116 playoff record, 
winning five Stanley Cups with Montreal, two with Detroit and one 
with Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
	His eight Cup championships equals former Montreal Canadiens  
coach Toe Blake for the most in NHL history. 
</P>
</TEXT>
