<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NBA Upholds Agent Decertification </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- An agent who harshly criticized the players'  
union during the NBA lockout will remain decertified, an arbitrator 
ruled Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling will keep Stephen Woods, who represented Kevin Willis  
of the Toronto Raptors, barred from negotiating player contracts. 
He said he plans to appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	``If Latrell Sprewell can get reinstated for choking his coach,  
why should I be barred from making a living?'' Woods said. 
</P>
<P>
	Woods was a vocal anti-union voice during the nearly  
seven-month-long lockout, taking numerous shots at union president 
Patrick Ewing and union director Billy Hunter over their 
negotiating strategies. 
</P>
<P>
	The union revoked his certification for not acting in its best  
interest, and Woods appealed the action before arbitrator George 
Nicolau. 
</P>
<P>
	``The discipline of decertification imposed by the disciplinary  
committee is reasonable,'' Nicolau wrote in a 47-page decision. 
</P>
<P>
	Woods also filed two complaints with the National Labor  
Relations Board, charging the union with unfair labor practices. 
Both filings were later withdrawn. 
</P>
</TEXT>
