<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Furman Women's Coach Requests Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREENVILLE, S.C. (AP) -- Furman women's basketball coach Sherry  
Carter has filed a federal complaint, saying she should be paid as 
much as men's basketball coach Larry Davis. 
</P>
<P>
	Carter said she tried in vain for 10 years to get the university  
to address her salary concerns. She also wants a multiyear 
contract. 
</P>
<P>
	If the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission decides to pursue  
the complaint, it will attempt mediation, said Rosemary Fox, an 
attorney with the agency. If that fails, the case could go to 
court. 
</P>
<P>
	Carter filed the complaint last November, but did not publicly  
discuss it until this week, The (Greenville) News reported Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither Carter nor Furman officials would discuss specifics of  
coaches' salaries or contract lengths -- the school is private so 
such information need not be disclosed -- but Carter referred to ``a 
big pay discrepancy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I have two children, both in college, and my husband was  
killed in a car accident. So I'm a single mother,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	University spokesman Vince Moore would not comment on the  
complaint, ying it was a personnel matter. 
</P>
<P>
	``The university will continue to support coach Carter and the  
Lady Paladin basketball program as it has throughout the years,'' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress passed Title IX legislation 27 years ago to address  
inequities in sports programs for females. Furman underwent a Title 
IX investigation in 1991, and an NCAA review of its 1996 self-study 
concluded that no major issues needed to be addressed, Moore said. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this month, a Chronicle of Higher Education study of  
women in college athletics said Furman spent $746,501 on salaries 
for coaches and staff working with men's teams, compared with 
$332,465 for women's teams. 
</P>
<P>
	Coaches who head women's teams in NCAA Division I-A make 63  
cents for every dollar earned by coaches who head men's teams, 
according to a Women's Sports Foundation report using 1995-96 data. 
</P>
<P>
	``The salary gap between coaches of women's and men's teams  
remains somewhat consistent across all the NCAA divisions,'' the 
report said. 
</P>
<P>
	Carter said that although Davis probably has more speaking  
engagements, the two follow identical NCAA rules that limit 
practice hours per week, recruiting days and days spent observing 
teams. ``The job is definitely the same,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Carter has compiled a 244-219 record during her 17 years at  
Furman, compared with Davis' two-season record of 21-36. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
