<HEADLINE> Mom Charged in Girl's Attempted Sale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) -- A woman was charged Friday with trying  
to sell her 8-year-old adopted Russian daughter for $4,000 through 
an e-mail. 
</P>
<P>
	Denise Kay Thomas, 42, was charged with attempted trafficking in  
children and criminal solicitation to commit trafficking in 
children. 
</P>
<P>
	In a telephone interview Friday, Mrs. Thomas said she did not  
intend to sell Elena, the girl she and her husband adopted in 
January. 
</P>
<P>
	She said she was trying to find a suitable home for Elena  
because the girl had emotional problems that were too much for her 
and her husband to overcome. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel I am innocent and will plead innocent. I don't feel  
guilty at all,'' she said. ``We want to find a good home for her, 
obviously that's our main goal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Elena has been placed in a foster home.  
</P>
<P>
	The proposed sale was uncovered May 21 when sheriff's deputies  
were contacted by a Texas couple who said they had received an 
e-mail from a woman offering to sell the girl. 
</P>
<P>
	It is illegal to sell a child and a private adoption must go  
through a licensed agency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
