<DOCNO> APW19990528.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 15:48:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Castro Replaces Foreign Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HAVANA (AP) -- The former Communist Party youth leader once seen  
as a protege and surrogate son to Cuban President Fidel Castro was 
replaced as foreign minister Friday by an even younger man -- the 
34-year-old chief of staff who handles Castro's daily schedule. 
</P>
<P>
	Castro's replacement of Roberto Robaina with Felipe Perez Roque,  
a key adviser to the president for seven years, appeared aimed at 
giving Castro tighter control over Cuba's foreign policy, which has 
become increasingly important with the Soviet Union's collapse. 
</P>
<P>
	Perez Roque ``is familiar as few are with the ideas and thoughts  
of Fidel,'' the Communist Party daily Granma said in a front-page 
story announcing the replacement. Robaina was not openly 
criticized, but the article made clear that Castro wanted a change. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am very happy with my new duties,'' Perez Roque told  
reporters Friday as he left the ministry after a full day inside. 
``I intend to maintain the policies of my predecessor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although rumors had circulated in recent weeks that Robaina was  
going to be moved from the foreign ministry, the news surprised 
much of the political establishment. 
</P>
<P>
	As recently as Thursday afternoon, a foreign ministry spokesman  
announced that Robaina was to leave Monday for a tour of Venezuela, 
Panama and Haiti -- a trip that he will now no longer make. 
</P>
<P>
	Robaina was not seen in public Friday and issued no statements.  
</P>
<P>
	Castro's decision was seconded by the Council of State,  
controlled by Castro and comprised of the country's most powerful 
and trusted government officials, including both Robaina and Perez 
Roque. The decision was also approved by the Communist Party's top 
leadership. 
</P>
<P>
	It does not necessarily mean that Robaina is being moved aside.  
Robaina's predecessor, Ricardo Alarcon, went on to become president 
of the National Assembly and continues to play an important role in 
both domestic and foreign policy, especially with the United 
States. 
</P>
<P>
	But when Robaina was named foreign minister six years ago,  
Alarcon's new post was announced at the same time. The government 
has not said what role Robaina will now have. 
</P>
<P>
	Granma said simply that Robaina was ``freed from his position  
until a new function is assigned to him.'' It said he had ``made 
the greatest efforts to complete his job during his time in 
charge.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In what could be seen as a criticism of Robaina, the newspaper  
said Castro's choice of Perez Roque took into account ``the current 
complexity of the tense international situation, its growing 
importance for the future of our country and the world, and the 
need for more profound, rigorous, systematic and demanding work'' 
in foreign relations. 
</P>
<P>
	Cuba has suffered several diplomatic setbacks recently following  
the conviction of four of the country's best-known dissidents on 
sedition charges in March. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.N. Human Rights Commission voted narrowly last month to  
criticize Cuba's human rights record. 
</P>
<P>
	King Juan Carlos of Spain, scheduled to visit Cuba this spring,  
still has not announced a date for the visit. Diplomatic sources 
say the trip has been postponed because of human rights concerns, 
adding that the monarch may not come to Cuba until the 
Ibero-American summit in November. 
</P>
<P>
	Foreign minister since 1993, Robaina has overseen the communist  
country's foreign policy during years of extreme economic hardship 
following the collapse of the former Soviet Union. 
</P>
<P>
	Through his almost constant travels around the world, Robaina  
has been credited with helping Cuba expand and strengthen its ties 
with many nations following the loss of its communist allies. 
</P>
<P>
	When he was appointed at age 37, Robaina was the embodiment of  
Cuba's young leadership and was said to have a father-son 
relationship with Castro. 
</P>
<P>
	A mathematics teacher by training, he was at the time the head  
of the Communist Party's youth union, a deputy to the National 
Assembly, and a member of the party's Political Bureau and the 
government's Council of State, indicating he was one of Castro's 
inner circle. 
</P>
<P>
	A casual dresser who rarely wears socks and shoves up his jacket  
sleeves, the bouncy, compact man in eyeglasses was also a bit of a 
populist, riding his bicycle to work during the most difficult 
years of Cuba's economic crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	During his brief stays in Cuba, an animated Robaina greeted  
visitors in a garden decorated with cages of tropical birds inside 
the Foreign Ministry building, one block from Havana's famous 
Malecon seawall. 
</P>
<P>
	Government sources say Perez Roque is considered serious, down  
to earth, and extremely loyal to the president. 
</P>
<P>
	Perez Roque has played numerous leadership roles over the years,  
serving as president of the Federation of University Students, a 
national director of the Communist Youth Union and a member of the 
Communist Party's Central Committee since 1991, when he was 26. 
</P>
<P>
	Since he was 21, Felipe Perez Roque has been a deputy with the  
National Assembly, Cuba's unicameral legislature. He has been a 
member of the Council of State since 1993, when he was 28. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
