<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Feds Depose Microsoft Witness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Federal prosecutors on Friday tried to  
discredit a Silicon Valley CEO who was asked by Microsoft chairman 
Bill Gates to testify on behalf of the company as part of its 
antitrust trial. 
</P>
<P>
	During six hours of testimony in a San Jose hotel, Oblix  
president Gordon Eubanks described a telephone conversation with 
Gates three to four weeks ago in which the multibillionaire 
congratulated him on his move from Symantec to Oblix. 
</P>
<P>
	``He said they would like to have someone who has been in the  
industry a long time to testify about trends and technology,'' 
Eubanks said. 
</P>
<P>
	Eubanks could not recall, when asked by prosecutor David Boies,  
whether Gates had said this purpose was to help ``control damage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Eubanks also said he hadn't discussed the testimony of others or  
specific topics to testify that would be favorable to Microsoft. 
</P>
<P>
	During the sometimes tense questioning from Boies, Eubanks said  
that over the past several years, Microsoft executives had asked 
him to speak to reporters about industry issues on behalf of 
Microsoft. 
</P>
<P>
	Eubanks admitted that an op-ed article about Microsoft with his  
name on it was actually written by a spokesperson for Symantec and 
reviewed by his company's lawyers. 
</P>
<P>
	But he defended the article, saying, ``I have a dear belief that  
if it had my name on it, they were words that I wanted to say about 
the subject.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Department of Justice and 19 states accuse Microsoft of  
crushing competitors by illegally wielding the power of its 
dominant Windows computer operating system to expand into new 
markets, such as Internet software. 
</P>
<P>
	Eubanks was the final of three witnesses deposed before the  
rebuttal phase of the trial resumes Tuesday in Washington after a 
13-week recess. 
</P>
<P>
	Department of Justice witness Edward Felten, a computer expert,  
was deposed Wednesday in Washington and IBM executive Garry Norris, 
who will testify against Microsoft, was deposed Thursday in North 
Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	Eubanks stepped down in January as president and chief executive  
of Symantec Corp., which makes a popular anti-virus program and 
other software utilities that run using Microsoft's Windows 
operating system. 
</P>
<P>
	A longtime Microsoft ally, Eubanks left to become president of  
Oblix Inc., a small computer automation company whose investors 
include Netscape and Novell Inc. -- some of Microsoft's biggest 
rivals. 
</P>
<P>
	``Microsoft has done some bad things,'' Eubanks told The New  
York Times last year. But he added that Microsoft's chairman, Bill 
Gates, is a victim of American culture's trend of attacking and 
tearing down successful people. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft will use Eubanks' success at Symantec to try to  
explain to the trial judge that Microsoft routinely adds new 
functions to its Windows operating system and that those actions 
are not necessarily anticompetitive. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think his testimony will show the incredible competition  
that exists throughout the software industry, and the benefits of 
Microsoft's continued evolution of the operating system for 
consumers,'' Microsoft spokesman Mark Murray said. 
</P>
<P>
	Antitrust attorney Richard Gray, who is closely following the  
Microsoft case, said it would be difficult for Eubank's testimony 
about the industry to undercut the government's case, if indeed the 
proof is there that the computer giant did indeed have an illegal 
monopoly. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
