<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Car Haulers Might Go On Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- A threatened Teamsters strike against the  
nation's car haulers next week could put the brakes on the auto 
industry's record sales pace, hurting automakers who depend on the 
big-rig drivers to get cars and hot-selling sport utility vehicles 
to dealers' showrooms. 
</P>
<P>
	So far this year, U.S. sales of new cars and light trucks are up  
9 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The showdown is the first test for James P. Hoffa since he  
became president of the union in March, assuming a post once held 
by his late father, Jimmy. 
</P>
<P>
	``The industry is making big money. It's time the owners shared  
the profits with the people doing the hard work,'' Hoffa has said. 
</P>
<P>
	Negotiators are working against a deadline of 12:01 a.m.  
Tuesday, when the contract expires. Earlier this month, the 
truckers voted 5,705 to 251 to give their negotiating committee the 
power to call a strike if talks fail. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the moment of negotiations when one never knows,''  
said Ian Hunter, of the National Automobile Transporters Labor 
Division, among the management organizations involved in the 
negotiations. ``But we're still talking, we're still seeking a 
mutual solution.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Though Hunter said he is optimistic, he said negotiations are  
intense. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is fair to say there are a number of major issues  
unresolved,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Teamsters are seeking improved pensions, higher wages, a  
reduction in ``excessive work hours'' and improved health care. 
They also say they oppose proposals for a wage scale that provides 
lower salaries to entry-level drivers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our drivers are the highest paid in the trucking industry,''  
Hunter said. ``The average driver wage last year was $68,000.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, he said, automakers are pressuring for lower prices  
and labor costs have gone up 33 percent in the past four years. 
</P>
<P>
	``We recognize our work force is a very diverse and capable  
group. They earn their keep. But at the same time they have to 
realize we're facing this competition,'' Hunter said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Teamsters contract covers about 12,000 drivers, mechanics,  
yard and office workers nationwide. If a strike were called, 
industry officials expect the Teamsters initially would target just 
one of the major trucking companies that contract with automakers 
to move new cars and trucks to dealers from assembly plants, ports 
and rail yards. 
</P>
<P>
	``The auto industry will certainly feel it. It depends on how  
long it lasts,'' said Howard Foster, professor of industrial 
relations at State University of New York. ``It's distressing to 
the car companies now because ... they're in the middle of a banner 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	``(But) I don't see it as an event that will bring the republic  
to its knees.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Automakers likely would use their own drivers and hire  
independents to help get some vehicles to dealers in the event of a 
strike. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're monitoring the situation closely,'' said Ford Motor Co.  
spokesman Ron Iori. ``We're hoping both the Teamsters and the 
haulers can reach a mutually agreeable situation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the automaker has a contingency plan, but how it would  
be carried out would depend on the nature of a possible strike. 
</P>
<P>
	Teamsters spokesman Chip Roth said Friday that the union would  
have the option to strike on some or all of the 17 trucking 
companies that are at the negotiating table. He said he couldn't 
say which option the union would choose. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to assess that continuously as we go through the  
negotiations,'' Roth said. 
</P>
<P>
	A likely target is Allied Holdings Inc., the largest of the  
trucking companies. Based in Decatur, Ga., Allied operates about 
5,200 car- and truck-hauling rigs from 120 terminals in the United 
States and Canada, and serves all the domestic and foreign 
automakers with North American plants. It handles about two-thirds 
of the U.S. car-hauling market. 

</P>
</TEXT>
