<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dancing Graduates' Diplomas Held </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- One boy did a version of Michael  
Jackson's famous ``moonwalk'' dance, gliding backward across the 
stage. Another shimmied and shook his rump. 
</P>
<P>
	Sound like a hip party? Try a high school graduation ceremony.  
</P>
<P>
	And now, the six graduates of Ruskin High School are in hot  
water for apparently expressing a little too much joy at receiving 
their diplomas at graduation. 
</P>
<P>
	District officials are holding the students' diplomas until they  
perform 10 hours of community service. 
</P>
<P>
	The acts qualified as ``disorderly conduct'' that violated the  
graduation plan signed by each of the school's 162 graduates before 
the ceremony Tuesday, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The ceremony was going fine,'' said Hickman Hills School  
District spokesman Gary Martasin. ``As soon as the first student 
acted different, then it started. It's a snowball effect that we 
have to guard against. The next thing you know, you've lost 
control.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But not everyone agrees with the district's reaction. One parent  
has contacted the American Civil Liberties Union of Kansas and 
Western Missouri. 
</P>
<P>
	Dick Kurtenbach, ACLU executive director, said it was an  
interesting case. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a civil liberties issue involved in the freedom of  
expression,'' Kurtenbach said. ``I think the school would be 
hard-pressed to say that the act disrupted the ceremony.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
