<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Prepares for New Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ABUJA, Nigeria (AP) -- Bouncing to the blare of 1950's doo-wop  
hits, cleaners and construction crews made final preparations 
Friday on the parade grounds where Nigeria's military rulers will 
hand over power to the first civilian government in 15 years. 
</P>
<P>
	While technicians testing the sound system played ``Bye Bye  
Love'' and ``At the Hop,'' twin 20-foot-high television screens 
played silent Spice Girls videos. 
</P>
<P>
	Teen-agers scrubbing the bright red carpet where the  
inauguration ceremony of President-elect Olusegun Obasanjo will 
take place wiggled to the music. Others hung decorative ribbons, 
tied balloons and mopped the floor of the glassed-encased area 
where top officials will watch the handover. 
</P>
<P>
	Politicians and celebrities from South African President Nelson  
Mandela to Britain's Prince Charles will watch as Gen. Abdulsalami 
Abubakar relinquishes power -- bringing to an end a peaceful 
yearlong transition that began with the sudden death last June of 
Gen. Sani Abacha, whose wanton corruption and brutality crippled 
Nigeria and left it an international pariah. 
</P>
<P>
	For the dozens of Nigerians watching the show through a  
chain-link fence, it was all just in time. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nigeria will try to restore tomorrow our economic life, our  
political life, our social life,'' said Owolaei Lawal, a civil 
servant taking a break to watch. ``Nigeria has become a dead 
nation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Abubakar welcomed the ``profound achievement'' of the democratic  
transition, and on Friday urged the incoming politicians to govern 
well. Nigeria has been ruled by the military for all but 10 years 
since it gained independence in 1960. 
</P>
<P>
	As a parting gesture, Abubakar also announced that the junta had  
repealed the hated decree 2, which allowed imprisonment without 
trial. 
</P>
<P>
	``To us all beckons the historic opportunity to break, once and  
for all, the cycle of instability and mistrust that have wracked 
our political life since independence,'' he said in a nationally 
broadcast speech. 
</P>
<P>
	Obasanjo, who won February's presidential elections, faces a  
wealth of problems in Africa's most populous nation, which is rich 
in oil but has been dragged down by years of neglect, corruption 
and mismanagement. 
</P>
<P>
	Local phone calls are often impossible to place and lights can  
stay out in many Nigerian neighborhoods for weeks at a time. 
Unemployment is at staggering levels, and the people of the Niger 
Delta -- the swampy region that provides Nigeria with its oil wealth 
-- live in isolated towns with no electricity, roads or schools. 
They have seen few benefits from the oil they live above, and 
violence has rocked the Delta repeatedly in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	Nigeria, which should have been able to use its billions in oil  
revenues to grow, instead has withered. 
</P>
<P>
	Abuja, Nigeria's always-under-construction capital city, is a  
grid of skyscrapers and boxy, modern office blocks, while much of 
Nigeria still lives in mud homes. Lagos, the country's main city, 
is a jumble of walled-in compounds for the wealthy and sprawling 
slums of staggering poverty. 
</P>
<P>
	But Obasanjo, who 20 years ago became the first -- and until  
Saturday, the only -- Nigerian military leader to voluntarily give 
up power, insists he will bring Nigeria back from economic 
collapse. 
</P>
<P>
	He has promised repeatedly to stop the corruption that has  
hobbled this nation of 120 million and to end the stifling poverty 
that most Nigerians endure. He says he will attract investors to 
Nigeria, most of whom have been frightened away by the crumbling 
infrastructure and rampant corruption. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
