<HEADLINE> Woman Sentenced to Driving School </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OAK LAWN, Ill. (AP) -- An 18-year-old woman who drove a car into  
a suburban Chicago home, killing a teen-age boy as he watched 
television, was sentenced to an eight-hour driving school course. 
</P>
<P>
	The driver, Karee Krutilla, of Chicago Ridge, had been ticketed  
for negligent driving and failure to reduce speed to avoid an 
accident in the Nov. 28 collision that killed 17-year-old Joseph 
Seminara. 
</P>
<P>
	Krutilla says she lost control when she swerved to avoid an  
oncoming car that was weaving. 
</P>
<P>
	A judge on Thursday turned down a request by the prosecutor to  
impose the maximum $1,250 fine. Instead, Krutilla will have to pay 
only a $115 fee for the driving school course. 
</P>
<P>
	The sentence Thursday further angered the boy's family, who  
accused police of going easy on Krutilla because she is the 
grandniece of an Oak Lawn detective. 
</P>
<P>
	``The charges against this girl should have been more severe.  
This doesn't even amount to a slap on the wrist,'' said Kelly 
Takaki, his mother. 
</P>
<P>
	Police spokesman Lt. Robert Smith denied that Krutilla received  
any special treatment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
