<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- U.S. financial markets, government offices and  
banks will be closed Monday in observance of Memorial Day. 
Financial markets will be open in other countries. 

</P>
<P>
	Personal Income Rises 0.5 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Money is burning a hole in Americans' pockets.  
Once again, consumers in April spent nearly as much as they earned, 
helping to push the nation's savings rate to an all-time low. 
Spending climbed 0.4 percent last month, a tad lower than the 0.5 
percent increase in Americans' personal income, the Commerce 
Department reported today. The income figure includes wages, 
interest and government benefits. ``Consumers have good reason to 
be out there spending, economist Mark Zandi said. ``They've got 
jobs, their incomes are rising, confidence is high and the stock 
market is booming.'' So far this year Americans are spending more 
than they earned. 

</P>
<P>
	Kodak-Fuji Film Price War Flares  
</P>
<P>
	ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) -- A photographic film price war between  
Eastman Kodak Co. and Japanese nemesis Fuji is flaring up as the 
peak summer season nears, and Kodak appears to be losing ground on 
its home turf once more. Kodak insists, however, that its seemingly 
sharp drop in market share in April is no more than a blip in its 
effort to rebound from a 1997 assault by Fuji Photo Film Co. that 
led to the elimination of 19,900 Kodak jobs. In the U.S. market, 
two retail surveys show that Tokyo-based Fuji grabbed 5 percentage 
points in unit sales at Kodak's expense during the first four 
months of 1999. Most of the gains came in April. But even with the 
decline, Kodak still accounts for about two-thirds of the rolls of 
film sold in this country. Eastman Kodak shares were down 1 3/16 at 
67 5/8. 

</P>
<P>
	United Customer Service OKs Pact  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- United Airlines' 19,000 newly organized customer  
service employees have overwhelmingly ratified a contract that 
provides pay raises and signing bonuses. About 70 percent of those 
voting during the past few weeks approved the one-year pact the 
airline negotiated with the International Association of Machinists 
and Aerospace Workers, United said today. The agreement covers 
ticket counter workers, reservationists, air freight agents and 
others. UAL Corp. stock was up 2 at 67 1/4. 

</P>
<P>
	Court Overturns US Air Union Vote  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federal court panel ruled today that a 1997  
union election in which US Airways passenger service employees 
decided to join the Communications Workers of America should be set 
aside. The Circuit Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia 
ruled that a lower court judge was wrong to throw out a prior 
election in which the employees voted against joining the CWA. 
Following the earlier election, the National Mediation Board ruled 
that the airline had tainted the vote by holding employer-employee 
roundtable discussions. The three-judge appeals court panel found 
that ``the board's order unconstitutionally restrained US Airways' 
speech leading up to the rerun election.'' US Airways stock was at 
48 9/16, up 1 1/4. 

</P>
<P>
	Navy May Oppose Shipbuilding Deal  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Pentagon is likely to recommend that the  
Justice Department oppose Litton Industries Inc.'s proposed $1.8 
billion purchase of Newport News Shipbuilding Inc., Defense 
Secretary William Cohen said today. Cohen said the Navy had made a 
``preliminary determination'' that the Litton bid for Newport News 
would excessively limit competition in naval shipbuilding. But he 
said the Navy had determined it would not oppose Litton's $500 
million cash offer for Avondale Industries Inc. Newport News stock 
finished at 27 1/2, down 5 1/4, while Litton's was up 2 7/16 at 65 3/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Fox Agrees With Affiliates on Ads  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Fox Broadcasting Co. has reached an agreement  
with its affiliates under which the network will take back 20 
commercial spots each week that the stations had been allowed to 
sell themselves. The affiliates had protested the network's 
original plan to cut the amount of 30-second spots that each local 
station can sell every week from 90 to 70. Under a slightly revised 
plan announced, the network promised not to take back any spots 
during prime time or National Football League games. The move will 
mean less revenues for the 200 Fox-affiliated TV stations around 
the nation and more for the network. 

</P>
<P>
	Ford Denies Lorain Plant Closure  
</P>
<P>
	CLEVELAND, Ohio (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. is denying reports it may  
close its Lorain plant with 1,875 workers and shift production to a 
plant in Avon Lake. Ford said today that the company has no plans 
to close the Lorain Assembly Plant, located 25 miles west of 
Cleveland. Workers at the plant install interior and mechanical 
pieces in Ford's Econoline vans after the bodies are made in the 
Avon Lake plant. 

</P>
<P>
	Internet Rule Group Hits Snags  
</P>
<P>
	BERLIN (AP) -- An international group crafting rules to manage  
the Internet is stuck over how to give individuals a say in key 
debates such as how Web addresses are assigned. The nonprofit 
Internet Corporation for Assigned Names and Numbers said today it 
has drawn resistance from Internet denizens leery that any topdown 
decision-making process will crimp the collegial nature of the Web. 
The ICANN board appointed the Domain Names Supporting Organization 
to advise it on oversight of the domain name system. 

</P>
<P>
	VW Said To Plan French Bugatti Plant  
</P>
<P>
	BRAUNSCHWEIG, Germany (AP) -- Volkswagen isn't giving up the  
luxury car idea, even if it may have lost last year's battle for 
the Rolls-Royce nameplate to rival BMW. VW chairman Ferdinand Piech 
told a newspaper that the ``people's car'' company planned to 
revive the legendary Bugatti marquee at a new factory to be built 
in Molsheim, France -- where the original Bugattis were made. 

</P>
