<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brazilian Co. Unveils New Planes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAO JOSE DOS CAMPOS, Brazil (AP) -- The newest defenders of the  
Amazon rain forest rolled out of their hangars Friday, accompanied 
by the ``Star Wars'' theme and high expectations from Latin 
America's largest aircraft manufacturer, Embraer. 
</P>
<P>
	The two new military planes -- the EMB145 SA and the ALX light  
attack jet fighter -- are expected to play a key role in the $1.2 
billion Amazon Surveillance System, known as SIVAM, being developed 
by U.S. company Raytheon Corp. But Embraer also sees a broader 
market. 
</P>
<P>
	``The defense sector has always been one of our targets,'' said  
Embraer President Mauricio Botelho. ``These planes will stimulate 
... our military business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The EMB145 SA is a junior version of the AWACS surveillance  
plane, consisting of a surveillance system manufactured by Sweden's 
Ericsson mounted on an Embraer ERJ145, a 50-seat commuter jet. 
</P>
<P>
	The ALX light attack jet fighter is modeled on Embraer's own  
Super Tucano military trainer. Designed for border patrols and 
Amazon missions supporting SIVAM, the $6 million jet carries 
air-to-air missiles, bombs, cannon and 12.7 millimeter machine 
guns. 
</P>
<P>
	The planes are the latest coup by Embraer, a former  
government-run company and chronic money-loser that turned around 
after it was privatized in 1994. Last year Embraer turned a profit 
of $102.9 million -- the first in its 30-year history. 
</P>
<P>
	The new military planes boost Embraer's standing as one of the  
continent's premier manufacturers of military hardware and a 
much-needed source of hard currency. The dollars Embraer earns will 
add to Brazil's cash reserves, an important indicator as the 
country emerges from months of economic turmoil. 
</P>
<P>
	Leading the comeback was the ERJ145, perhaps the world's premier  
commuter jet. Embraer delivered 60 of the $17 million planes last 
year, more than half of the total 116 planes it sold. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, Embraer announced a $420 million deal to sell 21  
ERJ145s to England's Brymon Airways, a subsidiary of British 
Airways. Brymon placed seven firm orders and has options to buy 14 
more. 
</P>
<P>
	Embraer now has 255 firm orders for the plane, of which 124  
already have been delivered, and 242 options to buy spread out 
among 17 clients in 10 countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
