<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Milosevic Meets With Russian Envoy  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Despite no signs of any breakthrough  
developments, a Russian envoy was ``very satisfied'' after nine 
hours of face-to-face talks with Yugoslav President Slobodan 
Milosevic. Emerging from the talks, Viktor Chernomyrdin urged a 
pause in NATO's bombing campaign to give peace negotiations a 
chance. But the United States is insisting that Chernomyrdin is in 
Belgrade representing only Russia and not NATO. Meanwhile, the 
alliance took advantage of good weather to hit a wide range of 
targets on its 66th day of airstrikes. 

</P>
<P>
	Albanian Army Stages War Games  
</P>
<P>
	KUKES, Albania (AP) -- The Albanian army today simulated a  
defense of its territory against a cross-border strike by Serbian 
forces, firing hundreds of artillery shells and rockets toward the 
embattled Kosovo frontier. The war games involved tanks, howitzers 
and 1,200 ground troops maneuvering several miles from the border, 
where Serbian forces have clashed with guerrillas of the Kosovo 
Liberation Army in recent days. NATO tried unsuccessfully to stop 
the exercise, fearing a Serbian military response in an area packed 
with more than 100,000 Kosovo refugees and international aid agency 
personnel. 

</P>
<P>
	India-Pakistan Fight Worries U.S.  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Efforts by the United States and other nations  
to promote restraint between nuclear rivals India and Pakistan is 
being threatened by renewed skirmishing over the disputed frontier 
region of Kashmir. The two nations have already fought three wars, 
two of them directly related to the Kashmir conflict. The latest 
flareup has resulted in an Indian helicopter gunship being shot 
down today, a day after Pakistan's armed forces said they had shot 
down two Indian jet fighters on the Pakistani side of the border 
that divides the province. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Stinger Missile Used Worldwide  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- At about 35 pounds, the shoulder-fired,  
U.S.-made Stinger missile that India claims Pakistani forces used 
to shoot down two aircraft in the disputed Kashmir region is a 
favorite of soldiers, terrorists and guerrillas worldwide. They're 
deadly and difficult for pilots to target from the air. They are 
also relatively cheap, with a black market price of $50,000 to 
$80,000 each. 

</P>
<P>
	Rwanda Declares Cease-Fire in Congo  
</P>
<P>
	KIGALI, Rwanda (AP) -- Rwanda declared a unilateral cease-fire  
today in Congo, where it has been backing the rebels fighting to 
oust Congolese President Laurent Kabila. The declaration appeared 
to challenge Kabila to comply. Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni 
and Kabila signed a cease-fire agreement on April 18 that was 
mediated by Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi. But Rwanda and the 
Congolese rebels rejected the deal as premature and said it was 
reached without their consultation. 

</P>
<P>
	MCI WorldCom Buys Skytel for $1.3B  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- MCI WorldCom Inc. is buying the paging company  
SkyTel Communications Inc. for nearly $1.3 billion in stock. MCI 
WorldCom said today it would pay stock worth $21.24 for each share 
of SkyTel, filling a gaping wireless hole in an otherwise broad 
list of telecommunications businesses. MCI WorldCom, the nation's 
No. 2 long-distance phone company and a major owner of the 
circuitry that makes up the Internet, will also absorb about $725 
million in debt from SkyTel. 

</P>
<P>
	Judge Upholds Late-Term Abortion Ban  
</P>
<P>
	MADISON, Wis. (AP) -- A federal judge ruled today that a  
Wisconsin law that bars a type of late-term abortion is 
constitutional. In his ruling, the judge said the law, aimed at 
what critics call ``partial-birth abortions,'' does not place an 
undue burden on women and that the state does have a valid interest 
in banning the procedure. Under the law, doctors who perform the 
procedure would be subject to first-degree murder charges and life 
in prison if convicted. Patients would not be punished. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks End Higher; Dow Up 92.81  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rebounded today from yesterday's steep  
selloff as new economic data showing slower-than-expected growth 
helped calm fears about rising inflation and higher interest rates. 
The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 92.81 at 10,559.74. 
Advancers on the NYSE outnumbered decliners 1,964-975. The Nasdaq 
closed up 51.26 to 2,470.41. 

</P>
<P>
	Mac vs. Sosa in Cubs Win  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Sammy Sosa seized the day in his first  
face-to-face meeting this season with friend and rival Mark McGwire 
as the Chicago Cubs beat the St. Louis Cardinals 6-3. The Cubs' 
star homered in his final at-bat -- his 17th of the season and 13th 
in the last 22 games -- and Henry Rodriguez belted two home runs. 
McGwire went 0-for-4 and struck out twice. He has 14 homers and had 
hit six in the previous eight games. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  
