<HEADLINE> Pinehurst Prepares for U.S. Open  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PINEHURST, N.C. (AP) -- Officials have closed Pinehurst's No. 2  
course to give maintenance crews nearly three weeks to prepare it 
for the 99th U.S. Open. 
</P>
<P>
	The course, which is open to the public, was shut down Thursday.  
The tournament runs June 17-20. 
</P>
<P>
	``From our perspective, we're just going to try and manicure the  
course,'' said Brad Kocher, the chief superintendent of the eight 
courses at the Pinehurst Resort and Country Club. ``When the 
players set foot on this, it's going to be a pretty pure golf 
course. As pure as we can make it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kocher said No. 2 is closing at least a week earlier than most  
Open courses do before serving as host to the event. Officials say 
they're concerned about Bermuda grass around the putting surfaces, 
which was chemically treated in February, but has been slow to grow 
this spring. As a result, Pinehurst has spliced sod into several 
areas in recent weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	During play this week, the newly sodded areas were deemed  
off-limits as ground under repair. That's something tournament 
officials would like to avoid during the Open, said Tom Meeks, the 
director of the USGA rules and competition staff, which is 
overseeing the course's preparation for the tournament. Meeks is 
scheduled to arrive at Pinehurst on June 10. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm a little concerned about all the sodding they're doing  
down there,'' Meeks said from his New Jersey office. ``If I get 
down there and don't like what I see, we'll have to go to the white 
paint.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The paint would outline unplayable areas from which players  
would be given relief. 
</P>
<P>
	``Pinehurst doesn't want to see any white paint, and neither do  
I, but if we have to, we will,'' Meeks said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
