<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Internet Rule Group Hits Snags </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BERLIN (AP) -- An international group drawing up rules to keep  
the Internet running smoothly conceded Friday that it is having 
difficulty finding the best way to represent the little guy in 
deciding questions such as how Web addresses are assigned. 
</P>
<P>
	The nonprofit Internet Corporation for Assigned Names and  
Numbers (ICANN) was set up in October after the U.S. government 
announced it wanted out of the business of managing the nuts and 
bolts of the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	But in drafting formal policies, a process to be completed by  
September 2000, ICANN has faced resistance from some Internet 
denizens unhappy at seeing the collegial nature of the global 
network's early days replaced with a topdown decision-making 
process. 
</P>
<P>
	ICANN's interim chairwoman, Esther Dyson, defended her mission  
by noting the explosive growth of the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Internet has been a tremendous success, but it's doubling  
each year,'' she said in an interview. ``When you increase the 
scale of something you do need to change the structure of how it's 
managed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Simple questions such as who gets the rights to use what name  
can turn into expensive battles given the increasingly commercial 
nature of the Internet. Is it first-come, first-serve in 
registering so-called domain names like ford.com, or does the 
automaker have special rights to its trademark in cyberspace as 
well? 
</P>
<P>
	While ICANN won't decide such questions itself, ``we are setting  
the policies for resolving that dispute,'' Dyson said. 
</P>
<P>
	At a two-day meeting in Berlin, the ICANN board appointed the  
Domain Names Supporting Organization (DNSO) to advise it on 
oversight of the domain name system. 
</P>
<P>
	Businesses and national registries were given seats, but the  
board deferred a decision on granting representation to 
``noncommercial interests'' because of conflicts within the Net 
community itself on who should represent it. 
</P>
<P>
	``There needs to be a role for individuals with ICANN,'' Dyson  
said. ``But our goal is not to recognize a group of people but a 
set of rules.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Among the problems, she said, was that some individuals actually  
represent commercial or national interests. There were also those 
who believed the interests of Net users would be best represented 
through the general membership, which gets to choose three of the 
board's 19 seats, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	But one activist who traveled from New Zealand to attend the  
meeting, Job Tanstra, said that was unrealistic. ``It's unlikely 
that we'll have a large at-large membership simply because there's 
not a large awareness of ICANN,'' Tanstra said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dyson said the board hoped to attract more attention by holding  
open meetings around the globe. In March, it met in Singapore; the 
next one, on Aug. 26, is in Santiago, Chile. 
</P>
<P>
	But ultimately, ICANN will likely remain in the background for  
most Web-surfers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our mission is to keep the Internet working smoothly so that  
they don't need to pay attention to us,'' Dyson said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990528.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 00:51:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Students, Staff Returning to School </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) -- For Emily Stepp, it's a matter of  
finding her car keys, a calculator and maybe closure. 
</P>
<P>
	She and hundreds of other Columbine High School students will be  
allowed back into the bomb-damaged building Tuesday to retrieve 
belongings left when they fled in terror of two teen-age gunmen. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be really sad, but I've got to go back in  
there,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The return is expected to be so upsetting that counselors will  
be available and parents have been invited, said Marilyn Saltzman 
of the Jefferson County School District. 
</P>
<P>
	The school has been closed since April 20 when seniors Eric  
Harris and Dylan Klebold killed 12 students and a teacher and 
wounded 21 others before taking their lives in the library. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators are turning the Columbine building back over to  
the school district, which will spend the summer renovating the 
rooms damaged by bombs, bullets and water. Only the library, the 
scene of many shootings, will remain closed to school officials 
while investigators continue to examine it. 
</P>
<P>
	``Kids are really anxious to get their belongings,'' Saltzman  
said. ``They have purses, glasses, credit cards and keys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Students and parents will be escorted to classrooms to retrieve  
their property. Items left in lockers, the commons or the library 
will be available in the auditorium or gymnasium, Saltzman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Stepp, who graduated last week, was in a publications office  
eating lunch with a friend when they heard shots. They tried to run 
out a front door but fled when gunfire shattered the glass. 
</P>
<P>
	Stepp then ran into an English department office where teachers  
were eating. They moved filing cabinets in front of the doors as 
bombs and gunfire erupted around them. 
</P>
<P>
	She said she was glad her parents, Paul and Ruth Selzman, will  
accompany her Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be hard because that was my last day in there as  
a senior,'' she said. ``Most kids' last day in their school is 
happy.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990528.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 15:36:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kashmir Infiltration Stunned India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KARGIL, India (AP) -- At first, an army patrol saw a few  
suspicious black-clad men on a high ridge in India's closely 
watched Kashmir frontier region. Within days, reports were gushing 
in: The mountain ranges were swarming with infiltrators. 
</P>
<P>
	As the magnitude of the incursion near the Pakistani frontier  
became clear in the second week of May, the Indian military was 
stunned. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the years, Islamic guerrillas have frequently tried to  
cross into Indian-held areas of Kashmir to fight for independence 
for the Muslim-majority region. 
</P>
<P>
	But never before had so many infiltrators -- as many as 600 --  
crossed into India at once. Never before had they seized territory, 
apparently with the intention to hold it or die trying. 
</P>
<P>
	Days after Indian patrols first spotted the infiltrators on May  
6, India was engaged in escalating fighting along a 94-mile line. 
This week, for the first time since the last war with Pakistan in 
1971, India deployed aircraft in combat and lost at least three. 
</P>
<P>
	Both India and Pakistan claim all of Kashmir, a dispute spilling  
over from when Britain granted independence to colonial India in 
1947 and partitioned the territory into two nations. 
</P>
<P>
	For the last 10 years, India has battled an insurrection by  
Kashmiris seeking to sever the state from India, where Hindus are 
the majority. India says Pakistan supports the insurgents, and 
artillery shelling across the cease-fire line has become routine. 
</P>
<P>
	Accounts of how the fighting developed this month, from the town  
of Bitalik in the east to Kaobal valley in the west, emerged from 
military officers and fighters, none of whom could be identified by 
name. 
</P>
<P>
	The first clashes between Indian troops and the infiltrators  
came as early as May 8 near Dras, one of a half dozen towns on the 
highway that runs parallel to the Line of Control, as the 
cease-fire line is known. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the next three days, the army realized it was facing an  
extraordinary situation. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Bitalik region, infantry units moved swiftly to isolate  
the militants on a 16,000-foot mountain peak, closing off escape 
and supply routes. 
</P>
<P>
	An army captain from a forward unit said he saw 30 or 35 men on  
the ridge, all ready for a fight, armed with mortars, 
rocket-propelled grenades and heavy machine guns. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were surprised. We never expected them to cross the Line of  
Control,'' said the officer. ``The sanctity of the Line of Control 
had to be maintained.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Officers said it was clear the operation had been planned for  
months, even while India and Pakistan were engaged in a diplomatic 
thaw. In February, the countries' prime ministers had drawn out a 
blueprint to ease military tension after both countries tested 
nuclear weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	The militants set ambushes for Indian patrols. Casualties were  
taken on both sides in close-quarter fighting, officers said. 
Several early Indian attempts to retake positions with ground 
forces were repulsed, with the defenders having the advantage of 
high ground. 
</P>
<P>
	Conditions were harsh for both sides. The peaks were still  
covered with snow, three or four feet deep. Temperatures were well 
below freezing. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had no firewood, no petrol. The first 10 days we had only  
four meals,'' said a young captain, his nose and cheeks burnt from 
the snow-reflected sun. 
</P>
<P>
	The intruders retreated to higher peaks after a few days of  
fighting, but maintained control of the highway from the Kashmir 
valley that is the lifeline of this region. 
</P>
<P>
	After Indian artillery failed to dislodge the militants, the  
Indian Air Force on Wednesday launched their first airstrikes in 28 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	But army officers say the only way to evict the intruders is to  
send ground forces to sweep them out, in what could be a bloody 
campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has to be done,'' said one senior officer. ``They can't  
survive the winter up there, but we can't leave them there for the 
next five of six months.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
