<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 06:11:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Back Pain Pill Ordered To Fix Ads </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Nearly three years after the maker of Doan's  
back pain pills stopped running certain ads under pressure from the 
Federal Trade Commission, the agency wants the company to take 
action to erase lingering misbeliefs that the product is better 
than other pain relievers. 
</P>
<P>
	In a 4-0 decision Thursday, the commission ordered Novartis  
Consumer Health, maker of Doan's, to carry the following message 
for one year on its packaging and advertising for Doan's: 
``Although Doan's is an effective pain reliever, there is no 
evidence that Doan's is more effective than other pain relievers 
for back pain.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Novartis says it may appeal the decision to a federal court.  
</P>
<P>
	The FTC filed its initial complaint in 1996, alleging that the  
advertising for Doan's was deceptive and made unsubstantiated 
claims that the product was better than other over-the-counter back 
pain relievers. 
</P>
<P>
	The company ceased such advertising in May 1996, but the  
commission ruled that such misbeliefs about the product persist. 
</P>
<P>
	Novartis spokeswoman Kate King said the company strongly  
disagrees with the FTC's findings that Doan's advertising ever 
claimed the pill is better than other products. 
</P>
<P>
	``Never did we say something about Doan's being superior,'' said  
King. ``This disagreement is really based on consumer perception of 
those claims.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She said the company only claimed that Doan's is effective and  
that it contains an active ingredient that other analgesics do not 
have. Neither of these claims have been challenged, King said. 
</P>
<P>
	The FTC has long held that Doan's implied superiority with such  
slogans as: ``If nothing seems to help, try Doan's. It relieves 
back pain no matter where it hurts. Doan's has an ingredient these 
pain relievers don't have.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The commission noted that the company spent $65 million, mostly  
in 15-second television and radio ads over eight years, to promote 
its original message. It ordered the company to spend as much in 
the corrective advertising as it did in an average year on the 
earlier ads. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, an administrative law judge upheld the FTC's 1996  
ruling that Doan's ads were unsubstantiated, but the judge refused 
to order the company to run corrective ads. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
