<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> No End Near to IRL-CART Feud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Don't count on Michael Andretti and Al Unser  
Jr. returning to the Indy 500 just yet. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite talks aimed at bringing the two sides together, Indy  
Racing League president Tony George gave a discouraging State of 
the Feud address Thursday, saying the IRL is no closer to an 
agreement with rival CART. 
</P>
<P>
	George, in his most extensive comments on the 4-year-old split  
in American open-wheel racing, accused CART of leaking reports of a 
reconciliation to boost its stock price, soothe sponsors and divert 
attention from the Indianapolis 500. 
</P>
<P>
	The scathing words came a couple of hours after the final  
practice for Sunday's race. 
</P>
<P>
	The IRL's new tether system, designed to keep the wheels and  
suspension parts from flying into the crowd during a wreck, was 
used for the first time on Carburetion Day. There were no crashes. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to be the first to test it,'' Buzz Calkins said.  
</P>
<P>
	The system was introduced after debris killed three fans and  
injured eight others at an IRL event in Concord, N.C., on May 1. 
</P>
<P>
	George conceded it would be difficult for IRL and Championship  
Auto Racing Teams to survive as rivals. But he got no indication of 
common ground at a meeting last week with Andrew Craig, CART's 
chief executive officer. 
</P>
<P>
	``As long as we have different philosophies, we're never going  
to strike any kind of accord,'' George said. ``I can't say I'm 
encouraged by anything we talked about.'' 
</P>
<P>
	George, also president of the Indianapolis Motor Speedway, began  
the IRL in late 1995 as a low-cost, ovals-only alternative to CART. 
The older organization responded by boycotting the Indy 500, 
stripping the world's most famous race of open-wheel stars like 
Andretti and Unser. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not going to compromise ourselves just to get them back  
here,'' said George, preparing for his fourth 500 without CART. 
``It's as simple as that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	CART, which holds the Motorola 300 at Madison, Ill., on  
Saturday, is making plans to expand its 20-race schedule to other 
overseas markets. But Craig, sounding more conciliatory than 
George, said a return to Indy also is a priority. 
</P>
<P>
	``All we are attempting to do is to act in good faith for what  
we believe is in the best interest of the sport and the fans,'' 
Craig said after being told of George's comments. ``We have made no 
secret of the fact that all our teams would like to race in 
Indianapolis.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The two sides face major hurdles, such as totally different  
chassis and engine specifications. 
</P>
<P>
	George said he met with Craig in March and they got together  
again last week in Indianapolis. George also has met with NASCAR 
chief Bill France Jr., portrayed as the potential broker of a deal 
between the two open-wheel series. 
</P>
<P>
	George said his talks with Craig focused on their general  
support for open-wheel racing, but didn't focus on specifics for 
bringing the two sides together. 
</P>
<P>
	Clearly, George feels he has the upper hand because the IRL has  
the Indy 500. He said talk of a merger is merely an attempt to 
bolster CART, which is a publicly traded company on the New York 
Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	``They need to continue to give some glimmer of hope that  
something is in the offing to help keep their stock price where 
they want it to be,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	George's right-hand man, IRL executive director Leo Mehl, also  
gave little hint of a compromise Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I call it the May whine,'' Mehl said. ``Those CART guys are  
very concerned with what's going on here. If they come back here 
with the same engines we use, the same chassis, they'll get their 
doors blown off.'' 
</P>
<P>
	George and Mehl said there would be no attempt to reach a deal  
that would allow the CART teams to return to the Indy 500 unless 
they run the other 10 IRL races, too. 
</P>
<P>
	The IRL moved forward with its plans to improve safety beyond  
Sunday's race, announcing a change in engine rules beginning with 
the June 12 event at Texas Motor Speedway. 
</P>
<P>
	Engines must operate at no more than 10,000 rpms after the Indy  
500, a reduction from the current limit of 10,300. The change will 
reduce the cars' horsepower and should slow speeds by at least 5 
mph. 
</P>
<P>
	In preparation for the last event under the current rules, Sam  
Schmidt had the fastest lap in practice at 222.458 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	``We certainly didn't go out there to have the fastest time of  
the day,'' Schmidt said. ``It just so happened I had a clear lap 
and popped off a good one.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The only starter who did not practice was Robby Gordon, who was  
in Madison, Ill., preparing for a CART race Saturday. Greg Ray, his 
Menard teammate and a front-row starter between polesitter Arie 
Luyendyk and Billy Boat, was second-fastest at 221.822 in his own 
car and third-fastest at 221.790 in Gordon's car. 
</P>
<P>
	Luyendyk, the two-time champion who will retire after Sunday's  
race, was next at 221.380. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
