<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Trinidad Sheds 18 Lbs. for Tune-up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) -- IBF welterweight champion Felix  
Trinidad has lost 18 pounds to reach the division limit of 147 
pounds for his fight Saturday night against Colombia's Hugo Pineda. 
</P>
<P>
	Trinidad was up to 164 pounds according to his doctor, Roberto  
Munoz Zayas. He will go into this bout at 146 and is favored to 
remain undefeated and set up a big-money September date with Oscar 
De La Hoya. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't lose this fight because it means I would miss my  
chance to knock out De La Hoya,'' Trinidad said. ``I have to win 
against Pineda to seek out this other fight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	De La Hoya, the WBC champ, is looking forward to the  
welterweight unification bout. ``Let's get it on,'' he said in Las 
Vegas earlier this week. ``It will be the fight of the century.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The deal for the bout has been bogged down by a money dispute  
between Trinidad's father, who is also his manager, and promoter 
Don King. They are arguing about how to split the $10.5 million 
purse and the split of the closed circuit television rights, with 
Trinidad seeking 75 percent of the TV profits. 
</P>
<P>
	The two men are expected to meet Sunday, after the fight, to  
continue negotiations, but both sides seem confident that the two 
fighters will meet in Las Vegas Sept. 18. 
</P>
<P>
	First, Trinidad, 34-0 with 28 knockouts, has to deal with  
Pineda, who has won 36 fights but has just one knockout. 
</P>
<P>
	The fight begins 11 p.m. EST in San Juan, the Puerto Rican  
capital and will be broadcast on HBO with purses of $2 million for 
Trinidad and $12,000 for Pineda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
