<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> CART Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MADISON, Ill. (AP) -- Were it not for the fill-'er-up theory on  
Michael Andretti's final pit stop last year, he might be the 
defending champion of Saturday's CART Motorola 300. 
</P>
<P>
	The blink of an eye was the difference between winning and  
chasing Alex Zanardi as he took the checkered flag. Andretti 
finished in second place, 0.573 seconds back with fuel to spare and 
a definite feeling of emptiness. 
</P>
<P>
	``They pulled it all apart and basically we were too  
conservative,'' Andretti said. ``They waited so they got every drop 
of fuel in. It was such a shame.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both drivers stopped for tires and fuel on the 175th of 236  
laps. Zanardi took a chance by not quite filling up the tank, and a 
caution flag allowed him to finish without problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Andretti had a faster car that day, but there aren't a lot of  
opportunities to pass on the 1.27-mile oval track at Gateway 
International Raceway. Most of the action takes place in turns 1 
and 3, but Andretti knows sometimes the best place to make a move 
is in the pits. 
</P>
<P>
	``Track position is king,'' Andretti said. ``I was a little  
quicker than Zanardi, I just couldn't get by him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Andretti led for 133 laps last year and a race-high 66 laps in  
1997, the inaugural event at Gateway International Raceway. He 
finished 11th that year because of another fuel strategy that 
backfired and forced him to pit on green. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *TETHER TALK:* Some drivers are a bit worried about the tire  
tethers the front wheels will be equipped with for the first time 
on Saturday. The step that has been taken to prevent fan injuries 
could end up hurting them. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm a little concerned what's going to happen if something  
occurs and the wheel is still connected,'' Richie Hearn said. 
``Normally you hit the wall two or three times because you lose 
control of the car and I'm a little concerned about what the wheel 
is going to be doing. I trust the engineers have got it right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Christian Fittipaldi also will believe the tethers work when he  
sees it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to be the one to try them,'' he said. ``It's a  
very delicate issue because you want to take care of the fans, but 
at the same time it might be better if the wheel just came off the 
car.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The tethers are being added in the wake of a crash during an  
Indy Racing League event on May 1 in Concord, N.C., where three 
fans were killed and eight injured by a wheel and suspension parts. 
There have been no additional steps taken at Gateway such as 
raising the height of the fences or the overhangs at the top of the 
fences. Gateway is not a banked track like the Concord track, so 
it's generally thought that it's less likely there will be 
problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike the IRL, which will have tethers on all four wheels at  
the Indy 500 on Sunday, CART is equipping only the front wheels for 
now due to a shortage in the space-age material used to make the 
cables. It's planned to add tethers to the back wheels in the 
future. 
</P>
<P>
	Most drivers agree that tethers probably will be a good thing.  
</P>
<P>
	``We've done a lot of things to help the safety of the  
drivers,'' Max Papis said. ``This will allow people to come to the 
race without thinking of their lives being in danger.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *NO REGRETS:* Rookie sensation Juan Montoya is quite content  
going for his fourth straight CART victory in front of some 70,000 
fans rather than giving it a try in at Indy, which still draws 
close to 400,000 fans despite losing some of its luster. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone says it's a great experience and a great race, and  
I've enjoyed watching it on television,'' Montoya said. ``But you 
can't miss something you've never done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Montoya isn't enamored of Indy's extended schedule, which in  
years past covered the entire month of May. Now the regimen is more 
like a week-and-a-half of testing, practicing and qualifying, but 
that's still a lot longer than the CART routine. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most places we come in, test one day, qualify the next and  
race,'' Montoya said. ``That (Indy) would be very different, and I 
don't know whether I'd like it.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *BLUNDELL'S RIDE:* Mark Blundell, who cracked a vertebrae when  
he crashed in testing at Gateway earlier this month, is hoping to 
return to the circuit for the Budweiser/G.I. Joe's 200 June 20 in 
Portland, Ore. 
</P>
<P>
	Blundell is being replaced this weekend by Roberto Moreno, who  
is attempting to double at the Motorola 300 and Indy on Sunday. 
X-rays scheduled to be taken next week are the key to his 
timetable. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going to come back unless I'm 100 percent because this  
injury can be very bad if it happens again,'' Blundell said. ``If 
my boys had taken me out the wrong way, they could have killed 
me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Blundell said it's tough watching.  
</P>
<P>
	``There's nothing you can do but wait, and you know race drivers  
have no patience,'' the Englishman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
