<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Talks in Pebble Beach Sale Heat Up  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. (AP) -- An investment group headlined by  
Arnold Palmer, Clint Eastwood and Peter Ueberroth hopes to close a 
deal soon for the purchase of the famed Pebble Beach golf course. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard Ferris, formerly United Airlines' chief executive, is  
also aligned with the group discussing the purchase of the seaside 
links, which are among the world's premier golf properties. 
</P>
<P>
	``The guys are out there talking and that's pretty much it,''  
Palmer said Friday in a phone interview with The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	Palmer indicated a deal could come at any time.  
</P>
<P>
	``I've been waiting to hear something the last couple of days,''  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	If the sale occurs, it would mark the second time in the past 10  
years that Pebble Beach has been sold by Japanese interests. 
</P>
<P>
	Lone Cypress, an Japanese investment partnership, paid Minoru  
Isutani an estimated $500 million for Pebble Beach in 1992. Isutani 
lost a reported $350 million on his deal, having paid an estimated 
$850 million to a partnership led by oilman Marvin Davis for the 
resort in 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	Palmer would not discuss the price but there has been  
speculation the Pebble Beach resort could go for between $800 
million and $1 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Stilwell, executive vice president of the Pebble Beach Co.,  
did not immediately return a phone call Friday seeking comment on 
the latest sale negotiations. 
</P>
<P>
	Ueberroth and Ferris were said to be traveling and unavailable  
for comment and Eastwood did not return a phone call to his Los 
Angeles production office. 
</P>
<P>
	The resort properties include four golf courses -- the Pebble  
Beach Golf Links, Spyglass Hill, The Links at Spanish Bay, Del 
Monte Golf Course, along with two luxury hotels and the spectacular 
17-Mile Drive that winds through Pebble Beach and nearby Del Monte 
Forest. 
</P>
<P>
	The 99th U.S. Amateur will be played at Pebble Beach Golf Links  
and Spyglass Hill on Aug. 16-22, and Pebble Beach will play host to 
its fourth U.S. Open next summer. 

</P>
</TEXT>
