<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NEC Posts Record Loss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- NEC Corp. posted its biggest yearly loss ever --  
$1.31 billion -- in the latest fiscal year because of weak demand 
for its telecommunications equipment, sagging semiconductor prices 
and a writeoff involving its U.S. affiliate, Packard Bell NEC Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's largest computer maker reported Friday it lost 157.95  
billion yen in the fiscal year that ended March 31 compared to a 
net profit of 41.30 billion yen for fiscal 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales fell 2.9 percent to 4.76 trillion yen, or $39.49 billion,  
from 4.90 trillion yen a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	NEC, which makes products ranging from personal computers to  
fiber-optic networks, blamed the country's recession for the 
decline in sales. 
</P>
<P>
	``Japan's economy saw a freeze in private-sector capital  
investment and a wide-scale decrease in consumer spending,'' the 
company said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The loss ballooned because of a one-time write-off of  
undisclosed proportion on the operations of NEC's U.S. personal 
computer affiliate Packard Bell, and a decline in the yen-based 
value of foreign assets because of a rise in the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The Packard Bell division, based in Sacramento, Calif., lost  
$500 million last year as its share of U.S. personal computer sales 
dropped, NEC said earlier this year. 
</P>
<P>
	NEC said in February that it plans to cut 15,000 jobs, or nearly  
10 percent of its work force, over three years in an attempt to 
boost profits. 
</P>
<P>
	Friday's earnings announcement was the latest in a series of  
miserable reports from Japanese technology companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this week, Fujitsu Ltd. Toshiba Corp., Hitachi Ltd., and  
Mitsubishi Electric Corp. also said they lost money last year. 
</P>
<P>
	All of the companies are major computer chip makers forecasting  
that rising prices this year will drive a recovery in earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	NEC forecast a net profit of 25 billion yen and sales of 5.05  
trillion yen for the fiscal year ending March 31, 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
