<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Firm Says Trademark Was Violated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- RE/MAX, one of the nation's largest real estate  
firms, contends a real estate agent is improperly using the 
company's name and its balloon logo to sell properties in Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
	The company has asked the State Department to intervene in the  
dispute with the Cuban company, set up by Stephen Marshall, RE/MAX 
president Daryl Jesperson said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an illegal and unauthorized use of our trademark. We have  
a responsibility to the members of the RE/MAX system to protect our 
prestige,'' Jesperson said. 
</P>
<P>
	One of Jesperson's main concerns is that the Cuban advertising  
splashed with RE/MAX and its trademark red, white and blue balloon 
will anger Cuban-Americans in Florida, the company's No. 1 market. 
</P>
<P>
	Marshall did not immediately return an e-mail seeking comment  
and did not list a phone number on his Web page. 
</P>
<P>
	A State Department official said the government is looking into  
the trademark complaints. 
</P>
<P>
	Marshall told The Miami Herald that he paid $75,000 to RE/MAX's  
Caribbean subfranchiser to use the name and open five offices in 
Cuba. The company has been doing business for at least 1 1/2 years. 
</P>
<P>
	RE/MAX executives ``thought their attorneys had found the magic  
agreement to get around U.S. laws,'' Marshall said, referring to 
the U.S. embargo on business with Cuba. ``They knew full well I was 
here. Now they've had some sort of memory loss.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jesperson said his company never received any money from  
Marshall and only learned of the Cuban firm's existence several 
months ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
