<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft May Buy Into Telekom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- Microsoft Corp. wouldn't be averse to  
taking a stake in Deutsche Telekom, Germany's former telephone 
monopoly, as it looks for new ways to sell its products, the 
software giant's president said in Friday's Handelsblatt newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	Steven Ballmer told the German business daily that a stake in  
Telekom isn't Microsoft's main aim, but ``it would be all right'' 
if talks to secure new distribution channels lead to an investment. 
</P>
<P>
	Telekom Chairman Ron Sommer, in an interview in Die Welt  
newspaper Friday, declined to comment on contact with the U.S. 
company. ``Microsoft is of course an interesting partner -- one with 
whom we already cooperate on a number of projects,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Speculation that Microsoft and Telekom, which is in the process  
of being privatized, are in talks have made the rounds for a while. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, the chairman of German media conglomerate  
Bertelsmann, Thomas Middelhoff, said in a speech that his firm was 
considering a joint bid with Microsoft for Telekom's cable 
television network, which is up for sale. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither company was willing to comment directly on the  
discussions, but a spokesman for Microsoft said then that all three 
``are part of a circle which meets regularly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The weekly magazine Der Spiegel has reported that Bertelsman and  
Microsoft were prepared to offer up to $5.6 billion for the cable 
network, just above the $5 billion that rival bidder Deutsche Bank 
is believed to be willing to pay. 
</P>
<P>
	Telekom said at the start of the year it would split its  
17-million-subscriber network into nine regional companies, 
possibly maintaining a stake in some. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
