<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> TWA Makes Final Offer to Machinists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Trans World Airlines on Friday presented what  
officials called a greatly improved, but final, offer to 
International Association of Machinists and Aerospace Workers. 
</P>
<P>
	The three-year contract offer comes less than two weeks before  
the 16,000 union workers could legally walk off the job on June 10. 
The union has threatened to strike after two years of failed 
negotiations. 
</P>
<P>
	The St. Louis-based airline made the offer during negotiations  
in Washington between TWA chairman William Compton and union 
negotiators. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's our best and final offer,'' TWA spokesman Jim Brown said.  
``There will be no better offer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Union officials did not immediately return phone calls from The  
Associated Press. But Brown said IAM leaders agreed to submit the 
company's offer for a ratification vote as soon as possible. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're certainly hopeful that's a good sign,'' Brown said.  
</P>
<P>
	As TWA has struggled financially over the past decade, employees  
have taken several pay cuts needed to keep the airline afloat. As a 
result, the workers earn far less than their counterparts at other 
major airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	TWA's previous proposal would have taken employees to 90 percent  
of the industry pay standard by the end of 2001 -- the airline says 
it can't afford full parity. Brown said the new offer gets to 90 
percent six months faster, by mid-2001. 
</P>
<P>
	The new plan also includes a new wrinkle -- cash payments for all  
workers covered by the IAM. The payments would be $4,600 for 
mechanics, $4,100 for ramp workers, $2,100 for passenger service 
and reservations employees, and $5,000 for flight attendants. The 
money would be paid over 1-3 years, in two or three payments, 
depending on the job. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal calls for mechanics to get an 18 percent raise over  
the three years of the contract. Ramp workers would get a 10 
percent raise, passenger service/reservations workers a 14 percent 
raise, and flight attendants a 27 percent raise. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1998, the airline lost almost $5 per paying passenger for  
every 1,000 miles. TWA has lost money every year since 1989, for a 
total of more than $2 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The airline employs 21,500 people, including 8,700 in St. Louis  
and 3,500 in Kansas City. The airline also carries about 75 percent 
of all commercial traffic in and out of Lambert Airport in St. 
Louis, its domestic hub. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
