<HEADLINE> AP Clarifies Lamar Alexander Story </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- In a May 14 speech reported on by The  
Associated Press, Republican presidential candidate Lamar Alexander 
singled out Cendant Corp. in his call for teachers unions to pull 
their pension fund investments out of companies that produce 
violent video games. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander described Cendant as the creator of Phantasmagoria,  
one of the games he cited. 
</P>
<P>
	Cendant at one time owned Sierra On-Line, the software company  
that created Phantasmagoria. Elliot Bloom, Cendant's vice president 
for corporate communications, said the company had already sold its 
consumer software division at the time of Alexander's remarks. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
