<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 11:10 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Personal Income Rises 0.5 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Americans' personal income rose again in April  
but their spending followed fast on its heels, contributing to an 
all-time low in the nation's savings rate. Personal income -- which 
includes wages, interest and government benefits -- rose 0.5 percent 
last month, the Commerce Department said today. Spending climbed by 
0.4 percent. Americans' income has grown every month so far this 
year, climbing 0.3 percent in March, 0.5 percent in February and 
0.6 percent in January, according to the latest government 
estimates. However, spending has also risen steadily, and more 
quickly. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Move Higher; Dow Up 89.29  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks moved higher this morning as investors  
brushed off concerns over rising inflation and higher interest 
rates and jumped at the chance of picking up shares at cheaper 
prices as a result of this week's slump on Wall Street. Just before 
11 a.m. EDT, the Dow Jones industrial average was up 89.29 to 
10,628.04. The Nasdaq Composite Index was up 15.10 at 2,434.25. 

</P>
<P>
	Markets Are Closed Monday  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- U.S. financial markets, government offices and  
banks will be closed Monday in observance of Memorial Day. 
Financial markets will be open in other countries. The weekly 
auction of U.S. Treasury bills will be held on Tuesday instead of 
Monday because of the holiday. In advance of the holiday, bond 
markets will close early, at 2 p.m. EDT today Some commodity 
trading also will end early today, while stock markets will 
maintain regular hours. 

</P>
<P>
	NASD Board OKs Longer Trading Hours  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The National Association of Securities Dealers,  
which governs Nasdaq, has approved a plan to extend trading hours 
from the current 9:30 a.m.-4 p.m. Eastern time schedule. A second 
session of the day would likely start at 5:30 p.m. and end at 9 
p.m. or 10 p.m. The changes are expected to take effect around 
September, after a review by the Securities and Exchange Commission 
and discussions with industry leaders. Stocks would still have a 
final, closing price reported at the 4 p.m. end of the daytime 
session. Any after-hour trades would count toward the following 
day's stock price. Initially, trading would be limited to Nasdaq's 
100 largest, nonfinancial companies, led by Microsoft and including 
such other well-known stocks as Intel Corp., Northwest Airlines 
Corp. and MCI WorldCom Inc. 

</P>
<P>
	Asian Stock Markets Close Lower  
</P>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian stock markets ended the week sharply  
lower Friday on the back of a tumble overnight on Wall Street. 
Tokyo's 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average lost 204.51 points, or 1.26 
percent, to finish the day at 15,972.68. The Jakarta Stock 
Exchange's Composite Index fell 19.467 points, or 3.2 percent, to 
583.649. In Hong Kong, the blue-chip Hang Seng Index fell 2 
percent, or 249.28 points, closing at 12,059.25. 

</P>
<P>
	NEC Posts Record Loss  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- NEC Corp. posted its biggest yearly loss ever --  
$1.31 billion -- in the latest fiscal year because of weak demand 
for its telecommunications equipment, sagging semiconductor prices 
and a writeoff involving its U.S. affiliate, Packard Bell NEC Inc. 
Japan's largest computer maker reported Friday it lost 157.95 
billion yen in the fiscal year that ended March 31 compared to a 
net profit of 41.30 billion yen for fiscal 1997. Sales fell 2.9 
percent to 4.76 trillion yen, or $39.49 billion, from 4.90 trillion 
yen a year earlier. NEC, which makes products ranging from personal 
computers to fiber-optic networks, blamed the country's recession 
for the decline in sales. 

</P>
<P>
	Microsoft May Buy Into Telekom  
</P>
<P>
	FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- Microsoft Corp. wouldn't be averse to  
taking a stake in Deutsche Telekom, Germany's former telephone 
monopoly, as it looks for new ways to sell its products, the 
software giant's president said in Friday's Handelsblatt newspaper. 
Steven Ballmer told the German business daily that a stake in 
Telekom isn't Microsoft's main aim, but ``it would be all right'' 
if talks to secure new distribution channels lead to an investment. 
Telekom Chairman Ron Sommer, in an interview in Die Welt newspaper 
Friday, declined to comment on contact with the U.S. company. 

</P>
<P>
	Japanese Auto Exports Fall  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's exports of cars, trucks and buses fell 11.1  
percent in April from a year earlier, as rises in shipments to the 
United States and Asia were more than offset by declines to Latin 
America and the Middle East. The Japan Automobile Manufacturers 
Association said Friday the drop to 337,845 vehicles was the third 
consecutive monthly decline. Shipments to crisis-hit Asia rose for 
the first time in 19 months as the economies of some countries in 
the region appeared to be bottoming out. Japan's vehicle exports to 
the United States were also up, rising 11.1 percent to 116,898. 

</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong Economy Keeps Shrinking  
</P>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Hong Kong's economy contracted further in the  
first quarter, but at a slower rate, the government said today. 
Hong Kong's gross domestic product shrank 3.5 percent in the first 
three months of 1999, the fifth consecutive quarter of contraction, 
as most analysts had expected. But the contraction was less severe 
than the 5.8 percent decline in the final quarter of last year and 
5.1 percent contraction for all of 1998. 

</P>
