</P>
<P>
	CHANDLER, Ariz. (AP) -- A $90 million Motorola expansion, delayed  
by a slump in the semiconductor industry, is about to go ahead. 
Motorola said yesterday it is beginning construction that's 
expected to add about 500 jobs. ``When completed (in 2002), the 
Chandler facility will be our largest manufacturing campus in the 
world,'' said William Seiferth, chief of staff for Motorola's 
Semiconductor Products Sector. The expansion will triple the number 
of processors, microcontrollers and other devices made in Chandler. 
During the past year, under pressure of the Asian economic crisis 
and the related semiconductor slump, Motorola eliminated 2,075 jobs 
in metro Phoenix. Analysts say the slump has bottomed out. 

</P>
