<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bonds Up a Bit in Shortened Trading / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices moved slightly upward Friday -- if  
they moved at all -- as traders set aside recent inflation and 
interest rate concerns in pre-holiday dealings. 
</P>
<P>
	Trading was light in an abbreviated session in advance of the  
three-day Memorial Day holiday. The market closed early at 2 p.m. 
EDT. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond rose 9/32  
point, or $2.81 1/4 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves 
in the opposite direction, fell to 5.83 percent from 5.84 percent 
late Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The gains were less pronounced among shorter-term issues, which  
finished unchanged to up 1/32 point. Intermediate-term issues were 
unchanged, according to Bridge Telerate, a financial information 
service. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today's activity captures the anxieties in the fixed-income  
arena as May comes to a close,'' William V. Sullivan Jr., senior 
economist for Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the Federal Reserve Board is expected to tighten  
monetary policy in late June if the economic data for May coming 
out after the holiday indicate growth is too strong or that 
inflation is accelerating. 
</P>
<P>
	If the Fed moves to boost short-term rates, it would have its  
greatest impact on short-term Treasury securities whose prices 
would fall, Sullivan said. 
</P>
<P>
	But he said the 30-year bond could benefit from such a move  
because a rate rise may keep inflation in check. Rising inflation 
erodes the value of long-term bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	Sullivan said a government report Friday that Americans'  
personal income rose 0.5 percent in April while spending rose 0.4 
percent had been expected and had little impact on bond trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills were steady at 4.63 percent  
as the discount held at Thursday's late level of 4.51 percent. 
Six-month yields rose to 4.82 percent, as the discount gained 0.01 
percentage point to 4.64 percent. One-year yields were unchanged at 
4.96 percent as the discount held at 4.71 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, held at 4.87 1/2 percent, the same as late Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds up 7/32 to 121 27/32. The average yield to 
maturity fell to 5.37 percent from 5.39 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
