<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	India Denies Deploying Top Jets  
</P>
<P>
	DRAS, India (AP) -- India denied a report that it rushed its top  
fighter jets to the disputed region of Kashmir on Friday to enhance 
airstrikes against alleged Islamic guerrillas. The private STAR TV 
news channel said the Indian air force dispatched its Sukhoi 
fighter jets to beef up its strike capability. The move comes one 
day after two Indian MiG jets crashed in Pakistan. A military 
spokesman in New Delhi, S.K, Mulik, said, however, that the report 
was ``a false statement made by somebody.'' Pakistan had accused 
India of escalating hostilities in the mountainous frontier with 
the reported deployment. 

</P>
<P>
	Russian Envoy Flies to Belgrade  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- A Russian envoy flew to Yugoslavia  
Friday for talks on ending the crisis in Kosovo after hopes for a 
deal were dampened by the indictment of Yugoslav President Slobodan 
Milosevic. Viktor Chernomyrdin's trip comes amid criticism from 
both Russia and Yugoslavia that the indictment of Milosevic was 
ill-timed and undermined any chance of reaching a peace deal soon. 
The U.N. war crimes tribunal in The Hague, Netherlands, indicted 
Milosevic and four top aides Thursday. They are accused of crimes 
against humanity for planning and carrying out war crimes against 
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	Progress Made in Eradicating Polio  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Substantial progress has been made in eradicating  
polio worldwide, but federal health officials said Thursday that 
much more work is needed in India and parts of Africa. The World 
Health Organization's goal is to eradicate the crippling virus by 
2000. But the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention said that 
will require a ``major acceleration'' of polio-fighting efforts in 
some places. Polio cases reported in southeast Asia increased last 
year to 4,673, up from 2,827 in 1997. The CDC said the rise is 
likely due to improved reporting and surveillance of the virus. 

</P>
<P>
	Chickenpox Vaccine Recommended  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- All states should require chicken pox  
vaccinations for children entering day care or elementary school, 
federal health officials said. The requirements are recommended 
because the highly contagious disease is most prevalent among 
children ages 1 to 6, the Centers for Disease Control and 
Prevention said Thursday. Some 4 million Americans, mostly 
children, get chickenpox every year. Caused by the varicella virus, 
it typically just causes severe itching and rash in children. 

</P>
<P>
	Poll: Clinton Help May Hurt Gore  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A CNN/USA Today/Gallup poll released Thursday  
indicates the public, by a 52-to-29 percent margin, says President 
Clinton's active help in Vice President Al Gore's campaign for 
president would make them less likely to vote for Gore for 
president. Gore has a 2-to-1 lead in the poll among Democrats and 
those leaning Democratic against former New Jersey Sen. Bill 
Bradley. But four out of 10 of all respondents say there is no 
chance they would vote for Gore. 

</P>
