<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China Puts 3 Dissidents on Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- Three Chinese labor-rights campaigners have gone  
on trial for subversion for trying to organize workers laid off 
from a state-run firm, a human rights group and officials said 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The trial of Yue Tianxiang, Guo Xinmin and Wang Fengshan opened  
Thursday in the central city of Tianshui, 700 miles west of 
Beijing, the Information Center of Human Rights and Democratic 
Movement in China said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hearings also were held Friday, said officials at the Tianshui  
Intermediate People's Court who refused to give their names. They 
did not say when a verdict was expected. 
</P>
<P>
	If convicted of leading a subversive group, the three could be  
sentenced to 10 years or more in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	The trial comes as authorities step up detentions and  
surveillance of dissidents to prevent public commemorations of next 
Friday's 10th anniversary of the military assault that ended the 
Tiananmen Square democracy movement. More than 50 dissidents have 
been taken in by police and at least 15 are still being held. 
</P>
<P>
	China's communist leaders are nervous that dissidents will use  
the anniversary to whip up anger among millions of unemployed 
workers whose once-guaranteed lifetime jobs have been sacrificed to 
free-market reforms. 
</P>
<P>
	Dissidents have applied to police in two cities for permits to  
hold gatherings to mark the crackdown, with 90 registering in the 
central city of Xi'an, New York-based Human Rights in China said. 
The Hong Kong-based Information Center said police rejected an 
application by 50 others in Hangzhou. 
</P>
<P>
	The charges against the three labor-rights organizers are among  
the stiffest used against dissidents. They were accused of 
subverting state power by setting up a group to protect workers' 
rights, of organizing protests by laid-off workers and of receiving 
$400 from an unidentified U.S.-based organization, the Information 
Center said. 
</P>
<P>
	They also were accused of having contacts with ``enemy''  
organizations in Hong Kong and the United States, and of belonging 
to the illegal China Democracy Party, the center said, quoting a 
lawyer for one of the defendants. 
</P>
<P>
	Yue, 44, and Guo, 43, worked for the Tianshui City Transport  
Company in western Gansu province, but they and 1,800 others were 
let go, the center said. 
</P>
<P>
	Even as the firm racked up losses of $6.8 million in three years  
and stopped paying unemployment benefits, executives bought 
themselves apartments and spent $65,000 on entertainment, including 
a junket to the southeastern city of Guangzhou, the group said. 
</P>
<P>
	On Jan. 4, Yue and Guo founded the Chinese Workers Monitor to  
try to organize their colleagues to put pressure on the firm, but 
were arrested a week later, it said. Wang, an engineer in another 
firm, acted as an adviser to the other two, the center said. 
</P>
<P>
	Tianshui Transport's problems are typical of many state  
companies. Although state firms are supposed to provide minimum 
stipends for their laid-off workers and pensions for their 
retirees, many have no money to do so and go unpunished by the 
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
