<DOCNO> APW19990528.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 13:21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Speed Limit in Montana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HELENA, Mont. (AP) -- With the flashing lights of a Montana  
Highway Patrol car in his rearview mirror, Jody Darcy made history 
Friday morning as one of the first motorists stopped for violating 
the state's new speed limit. 
</P>
<P>
	Once the only state without a daytime speed limit, Montana's  
status as an American autobahn ended at dawn Friday when a 75 mph 
limit, day or night, took effect. 
</P>
<P>
	Montana Highway Patrolman Michael Schmauch clocked Darcy going  
90 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's ticket time,'' Schmauch said as he closed in at nearly  
100 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	Darcy nodded sheepishly when asked if he was aware of the new  
speed limit. He got a $20 ticket, half what could have been 
written. 
</P>
<P>
	For the last three years, drivers in Montana were allowed to go  
as fast as they wanted, as long as it was ``reasonable and 
prudent'' based on traffic, road and weather conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers revived limits this year after the state Supreme Court  
ruled that the so-called ``basic rule'' was unconstitutionally 
vague. 
</P>
<P>
	The limit on interstate highways now is 75 mph and the maximum  
on most two-lane roads is 70 mph. Fines start at $20 for up to 10 
mph over the limit; the maximum is $100, for speeds of 106 mph and 
over on the interstate or 101 mph on other roads. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite being nailed, Darcy offered no complaints over the new  
law. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think you need a speed limit,'' Darcy said. ``I imagine  
there will be fewer wrecks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He was among four drivers Schmauch stopped in a 90-minute span.  
</P>
<P>
	Some, like Brian Giordano, were let off with warnings even  
though they were clocked at 80 mph and above. Giordano was stopped 
for going 84 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	``I haven't been pulled over in two to three years,'' he said.  
``It's time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schmauch, an 18-year veteran of the patrol, said he welcomed the  
return of the speed limit. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were getting people daily out here at 100 mph or more,'' he  
said. ``You'd look at them and they'd just go by. It was a little 
bit frustrating.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
