<DOCNO> APW19990528.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 00:21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.Y., Calif. Transit Aid May Be Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A California lawmaker is fighting a Senate  
provision that would cut federal mass transit aid to two big states 
and boost it for the other 48. 
</P>
<P>
	The language was included in a $49 billion transportation bill  
for the coming fiscal year that the Senate Appropriations Committee 
approved Thursday, 27-1. The sole dissenting vote was cast by Sen. 
Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., because of the transit provision. New 
York has no senators on the panel. 
</P>
<P>
	At issue was what is called in the bill the ``transit equity  
provision,'' which would limit each state to a maximum of 12.5 
percent out of $5.1 billion in federal mass transit spending. Any 
funds a state would be due above the limit would be distributed 
equally to the other states. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, only two states exceeded that figure: New York's 15.9  
percent, or $813 million, and California's 13.6 percent, or $696 
million. Underlining the large share of the funds those two states 
receive, the next closest state was Illinois, which got 6.7 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Feinstein said the proposal could cost California $117 million  
next year and New York $160 million. She said that together, the 
two states have nearly half the nation's transit riders: New York 
has 34 percent, and California has 14 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``Transit is and should be a needs-based program,'' Feinstein  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The House Appropriations transportation subcommittee approved  
its own $50.7 billion bill Thursday without any similar limits on 
how mass transit money is distributed to states. That means there 
is a good chance the Senate language will not make it into a 
compromise House-Senate bill later this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., chairman of the Senate  
Appropriations transportation subcommittee, defended the proposal. 
He said he was protecting smaller states from the big states' 
ever-growing use of the transit funds. 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter to Senate Appropriations Committee Chairman Ted  
Stevens, R-Alaska, White House budget director Jacob Lew said the 
administration ``strongly opposes'' the state limits on transit 
funds. 
</P>
<P>
	Reflecting a larger fight between the White House and Congress  
over proposed spending, the letter also said the bill's overall 
price tag is ``simply inadequate to make the necessary investments 
that our citizens need and expect.'' The letter, however, did not 
threaten a presidential veto. 
</P>
<P>
	Shelby dropped provisions he included earlier this week that  
would have required airlines to give passengers more information 
about bargain fares and expected late arrivals. He said he would 
watch voluntary efforts by the airlines to improve information 
provided to passengers and might revive the provisions later. 
</P>
<P>
	Shelby said he eliminated the language after being lobbied so  
heavily this week by the airline industry that ``it felt like my 
office was a chalet at the Paris air show,'' an annual event 
heavily attended by airline company representatives. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate panel also approved a $21.6 billion energy and water  
projects bill that would increase spending for security at Energy 
Department facilities in the wake of revelations of Chinese spying. 
It would also cut administration requests for improving water 
quality in the San Francisco Bay area and Florida's Everglades. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990528.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 15:02:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ford Denies Lorain Plant Closure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND, Ohio (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. is denying reports it may  
close its Lorain plant with 1,875 workers and shift production to a 
plant in Avon Lake. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford spokesman Nick Sharkey said Friday that the company has no  
plans to close the Lorain Assembly Plant, located 25 miles west of 
Cleveland. Workers at the plant install interior and mechanical 
pieces in Ford's Econoline vans after the bodies are made in the 
Avon Lake plant. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have 1,875 employees who do the final production on the  
Econoline vans in Lorain and we fully expect them to continue doing 
that,'' Sharkey said. ``We have no plans to close that plant.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ford is considering having the Avon Lake plant do all of the  
Econoline production if the company decides to stop building the 
Mercury Villager and Nissan Quest minivans there, The Plain Dealer 
reported Friday, citing auto industry sources it did not identify. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford and Nissan North America Inc. are discussing ending  
production of those vehicles at the plant in 2002, the newspaper 
reported. The companies have a contract to produce vehicles there 
until 2004. 
</P>
<P>
	Jason Vines, Nissan's vice president for corporate  
communications, said his company does not want to end the contract 
early and that a decision is expected in several weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford does not plan to end its contract with Nissan early,  
Sharkey said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We fully expect the contract to go to 2004 and continue  
operating the plants as we have been,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Union leaders at both plants said they were unaware of any plans  
to change production of the Econoline vans. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, Ford eliminated 1,600 jobs by closing the part of the  
Lorain plant that built the Ford Thunderbird and Mercury Cougar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990528.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 15:49:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cohen Confident on Kosovo Outcome </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Defense Secretary William Cohen said today he  
is increasingly confident that NATO's air campaign will succeed in 
restoring ethnic Albanian refugees to their homes in Kosovo before 
winter sets in. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview on Day 66 of Operation Allied Force, Cohen told  
reporters there is no consensus in NATO for turning the conflict 
into a ground war, and he insisted the air campaign is succeeding. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am increasingly confident, given the amount of damage we are  
doing day by day,'' Cohen said. He also asserted there are 
``signals'' of declining morale and increasing discontent within 
the ranks of the Serb army in Kosovo, and he noted sporadic reports 
of anti-war demonstrations in some Serb towns. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're just going to intensify this until such time as we're  
satisfied that this can be brought to a successful conclusion,'' 
Cohen said. He emphasized that the Clinton administration has no 
intention of introducing ground troops into Kosovo until there is a 
peace settlement with Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen also predicted that Milosevic eventually will be brought  
to justice to face the war-crimes charges announced this week by an 
international tribunal. ``One day he will,'' the defense secretary 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, the top intelligence officer for the Joint Chiefs  
of Staff said NATO's bombing has destroyed large chunks of the 
Serbian military while strengthening and emboldening a rebel 
militia on the ground in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kosovo Liberation Army has tripled in size from about 5,000  
guerrilla troops at the start of the air campaign in March to 
between 15,000 and 17,000 now, Rear Adm. Thomas Wilson said 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	While far fewer than the estimated 40,000 Serb army and police  
troops in Kosovo, the KLA is effective at attacking Serb forces 
essentially pinned down by the NATO bombing, Wilson said. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO insists the ethnic Albanian KLA is not a partner in the  
fight against Milosevic and his Serb forces in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	But Wilson said NATO wants to help take out Serb tanks, armored  
personnel carriers and artillery because the equipment represents a 
major advantage that Serb forces now have over the KLA. 
</P>
<P>
	``So we believe that it's important to continue to destroy that  
equipment and also to try to make it immobile and keep them kind of 
out of the fight, because it tends to level the playing field 
between the KLA and the army,'' Wilson said at a briefing for 
reporters at the Pentagon. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilson also gave a detailed assessment of the damage inflicted  
so far on Serb forces, including a 35 percent reduction in 
broadcast capability of Serb television and radio. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilson said the Serb air defense forces have lost about half of  
their more sophisticated surface-to-air missiles, the 
Soviet-designed SA-3s and SA-6s. 
</P>
<P>
	Bombs have destroyed more than 20 Serb early warning radars, and  
seven of the nine major military airfields in Serbia are out of 
commission, Wilson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilson said the war-crimes indictment of Milosevic announced  
Thursday will not change NATO's military objectives. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton said the charges against the Yugoslav leader  
and four other top Serb officials ``will help to deter future war 
crimes by establishing that those who give orders will be held 
accountable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The indictment alleges a long list of crimes against ethnic  
Albanians in the disputed Serb province of Kosovo, including 
causing an exodus of refugees. Ethnic Albanians were a majority in 
Kosovo before the war began, but a minority elsewhere in Serbia. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Gen. Henry Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of  
Staff, said refugee camps outside Yugoslavia are being readied for 
the NATO campaign to continue into cold weather. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking at a news conference in North Carolina where he was  
getting an award, Shelton said, ``Winterization of the camps will 
enable (bombing) to go right on into the winter if that is 
required.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shelton said the air attacks are proceeding as military planners  
expected and that achieving goals would take time. 
</P>
<P>
	The KLA is successfully recruiting among ethnic Albanian  
refugees now congregated in camps in neighboring Balkan countries, 
Pentagon officials have said. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO has tried to keep the KLA at arm's length throughout the  
fight over Kosovo, leery of close association with a guerrilla 
force with different aims and possibly unsavory tactics. 
</P>
<P>
	The KLA is fighting for Kosovo's independence from Serbia, while  
NATO has favored autonomy for the province but not outright 
independence. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, it is obvious that even a ragtag army on the ground could  
be helpful to NATO as the alliance relies exclusively on air power 
to rout the Serbs. 
</P>
<P>
	``They appear to be a resurgent group which has taken advantage  
of NATO airstrikes, a general western sympathy and a groundswell of 
volunteer fighters,'' Wilson said. 
</P>
<P>
	The KLA is also benefiting from more organized leadership and  
improved supply lines, Wilson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said Wilson was not implying a  
new coziness with the KLA. 
</P>
<P>
	``He just stated the obvious, which is that after 64 days of  
pounding, the (Serbs) have been diminished in their capability,'' 
Bacon said. ``Our goal has never been to empower the KLA to create 
more fighting. Our goal has been to end fighting in Kosovo.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
