<DOCNO> APW19990528.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 13:21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Up on Weather News / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean future prices surged Friday on  
the Chicago Board of Trade as weather forecasts held the attention 
of investors. 
</P>
<P>
	In a session shortened to get a jump on the three-day Memorial  
Day weekend, corn and soybean prices were boosted by reports of a 
possible high-pressure ridge forming next week in the Midwest, 
which could result in hot, dry conditions for corn and soybeans. 
</P>
<P>
	But Dick Loewy, president of AgResource Co. in Chicago, said  
there was little evidence of a drought pattern and believes the 
rally was due to an oversold market as traders tried to even things 
up before the long weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat continued to recover from new contract lows set on Monday  
as prices were supported by the prospects of more rain-induced crop 
disease. Hail also did severe crop damage in Oklahoma this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for July delivery settled 2 1/4 cents higher at $2.52 1/4 a  
bushel; July corn rose 3 cents to $2.19 1/2 a bushel; July oats rose 2 
cents to $1.23 a bushel; July soybeans rose 4 1/2 cents to $4.61 3/4 a 
bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Livestock prices were higher on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.  
</P>
<P>
	June live cattle was .75 cent higher to 64.25 cents a pound;  
August feeder cattle rose .82 cent to 75.52 cents a pound; June 
lean hogs climbed .78 cent to 52.95 cents a pound; July pork 
bellies was up .65 cent to 53.37 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
