<DOCNO> APW19990528.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 06:41:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Economy Keeps Shrinking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Hong Kong's economy contracted further in the  
first quarter, but at a slower rate, the government announced 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong's gross domestic product shrank 3.5 percent in the  
first three months of 1999, the fifth consecutive quarter of 
contraction, as most analysts had expected. 
</P>
<P>
	But the contraction was less severe than the 5.8 percent decline  
in the final quarter of last year and 5.1 percent contraction for 
all of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's true the pace of recovery is slow, but the direction is  
the same,'' government economist Tang Kwong-yiu told a news 
conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Most analysts and economists agree that the worst was over, but  
a full economic recovery will take time. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would hesitate to use the word `recovery' but the Hong Kong  
economy has already bottomed out,'' said Shamus Mok, economist at 
the Bank of East Asia. 
</P>
<P>
	In a report, Tang blamed the continuing recession on worsening  
unemployment, lower consumer spending, declining exports and lower 
investment spending because of high interest rates and the banks' 
cautious corporate lending. 
</P>
<P>
	But the narrowing trade deficit, continued revival in tourism  
and increased consumer spending should pull Hong Kong out of 
recession by the end of this year, it said. 
</P>
<P>
	The government maintains an earlier forecast that that the  
economy will grow by 0.5 percent this year, Tang told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not being overly optimistic,'' Tang said. ``The latest  
figures cannot deny one thing: The pace of recovery is slow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tang said Hong Kong's exports to the United States -- the  
territory's largest trading partner -- would be affected by any 
trade restrictions imposed by the United States in the wake of 
recent allegations of Chinese military spying. 
</P>
<P>
	Tang added, however, that Hong Kong's exports to the United  
States were currently consumer goods and therefore ``not sensitive 
nor need to be restricted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But he said Hong Kong ``should worry about the overall economy''  
of the United States and the uncertainty over the effect of higher 
U.S. interest rates on Hong Kong's financial markets. 
</P>
<P>
	Because of Hong Kong's currency peg with the U.S. dollar, Hong  
Kong interest rates normally follow the movements of U.S. rates. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent months, a series of interest rate cuts in Hong Kong  
has helped pull in a cascade of liquidity into the markets, 
stabilizing the stock market and property market, Tang said. 
</P>
<P>
	Guonan Ma, an economist at Merrill Lynch, said although investor  
confidence, stable markets, and increased consumer spending has 
improved sentiment, the Hong Kong economy is still weighed down by 
a weak trade balance, high costs, and rising unemployment. 
</P>
<P>
	``We may still see a decline in GDP by the end of the year,'' Ma  
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
