<HEADLINE> School Calls Poison Ivy a Weapon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WESTERVILLE, Ohio (AP) -- An eighth-grader was suspended for the  
rest of the school year for rubbing poison ivy on her science 
teacher's chair. 
</P>
<P>
	The teacher, Tom Northrup, did not develop a rash.  
</P>
<P>
	Angela Pham, 14, got a 10-day suspension, beginning Monday, for  
violating the district's policy against the use of a weapon. 
</P>
<P>
	The girl did it because the believed the teacher treated her  
differently because she is Asian, said her mother, Angie Pham. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Schultz, principal of Heritage Middle School, said the  
district's definition of a weapon includes a dangerous object or 
chemical. 
</P>
</TEXT>
