<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 10:11:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Colo. Panel Issues Death Sentence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) -- For the first time since being given the  
power to decide punishment in capital cases, a three-judge panel 
has opted to give a convicted murderer the death penalty. 
</P>
<P>
	The sentence handed down to 25-year-old Francisco Martinez on  
Thursday is the first death verdict by a panel of judges since a 
controversial 1995 Colorado law designated them to make sentencing 
decisions in death-penalty cases in the state. Previously, juries 
decided such sentences. 
</P>
<P>
	In two earlier cases, the three-judge panels had opted for life  
sentences. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters say the new law puts death penalty decisions in the  
hands of a more impartial panel, while defense attorneys argue the 
process will lead to more appeals and political pressure on judges 
up for retention. 
</P>
<P>
	Martinez was convicted in September for his role in the slaying  
of 14-year-old Brandaline Duvall, who was gang-raped and tortured 
in May 1997 after being picked up at a Denver bus stop. Miss 
Duvall's body was found in a ditch near a creek. She had been 
stabbed 28 times. 
</P>
<P>
	Martinez's lawyers did not dispute their client played a role in  
Miss Duvall's death, but argued the state's main witness, Sammy 
Quintana, killed her. The defense also urged the judges to consider 
Martinez's abusive upbringing by an alcoholic, psychotic mother and 
a violent father who abandoned the family when Martinez was 4 years 
old. 
</P>
<P>
	Quintana was sentenced to 96 years in prison as part of a plea  
bargain. Two other defendants received life sentences for murder, 
and three others faced lesser charges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990528.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 19:41:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                            *Alice Adams    	
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Alice Adams, a longtime short story writer  
for The New Yorker and a novelist whose ``Superior Women'' became a 
best seller, died Thursday at age 72. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Adams, well known for 10 novels and five short story  
collections, had been treated for heart problems earlier in the 
week and apparently died in her sleep, said her editor, Victoria 
Wilson. 
</P>
<P>
	One more novel, ``After the War,'' will be published next year.  
</P>
<P>
	Her first novel, ``Careless Love,'' was met with mixed reviews,  
but after publishing her first story for The New Yorker in 1969, 
Ms. Adams became one of the magazine's most distinctive voices. 
</P>
<P>
	Her 1975 novel ``Families and Survivors,'' about a woman who  
moves from the South to San Francisco, as Ms. Adams herself did, 
established her as an important literary presence. ``Listening to 
Billie'' followed in 1978, then came the short story collection 
``Beautiful Girl.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Superior Women,'' which traced the lives of five Radcliffe  
women, in 1984 became a best seller. 
</P>
<P>
	Known for her wry perspective on life, Ms. Adams once ruminated  
on the difficulty of writing as one ages: ``Some smart person once 
said that what happens is your critical standards rise, and your 
talent does not necessarily increase in a commensurate way.'' 

</P>
<P>
                        *Kent Hollingsworth    	
</P>
<P>
	LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) -- Kent Hollingsworth, who shaped The  
Blood-Horse weekly magazine into one of the thoroughbred racing's 
most respected trade journals, died Wednesday at age 69. The cause 
of death was not known. 
</P>
<P>
	Hollingsworth served as editor, then publisher of The  
Blood-Horse from 1963-86. When he became editor, the magazine had a 
circulation of 6,800 and a staff of 30. When he departed as 
publisher 23 years later, the circulation had reached 21,700 and 
the staff numbered 101. 
</P>
<P>
	Under his leadership, the magazine expanded its reputation as an  
authoritative source of information, commentary, statistics and 
analysis on thoroughbred racing and breeding. He wrote the highly 
respected ``What's Going On Here?'' column. 
</P>
<P>
	Hollingsworth also was a lawyer and teacher. In recent years, he  
returned to the practice of law and served as a Distinguished 
Lecturer in equine law in the Equine Industry Program at the 
University of Louisville. 
</P>
<P>
	He began his journalism career as a news photographer and sports  
writer for the Lexington Leader in 1954. He also has authored five 
books. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include his wife, six children, a sister and a  
brother. 

</P>
<P>
                          *David Paul Kane    	
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Kennedy, Cabot &AMP; Co. founder David Paul Kane,  
who named his discount brokerage after John F. Kennedy to appeal to 
Democrats and Henry Cabot Lodge to lure Republicans, died Tuesday 
from complications of a stroke. He was 82. 
</P>
<P>
	Kane was a former lobster importer and car wash owner who made a  
fortune in the discount brokerage business. He also broadcast stock 
market commentaries for two decades on local KWHY-TV. 
</P>
<P>
	He sold the remainder of his interest in Kennedy, Cabot &AMP; Co. in  
1997 for $155 million to Waterhouse Investor Services Inc., the New 
York brokerage arm of Canadian banking giant Toronto-Dominion. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Ed Peterson    	
</P>
<P>
	BOISE, Idaho (AP) -- Ed Peterson, inventor of the alarm that  
beeps to warn people when trucks and heavy machinery are backing 
up, died Wednesday. He was 78. 
</P>
<P>
	Peterson also invented collapsible luggage carriers, home  
security alarms and automotive electrical devices. 
</P>
<P>
	In the mid-1960s, he invented the Bac-A-Larm, marketing it  
initially to international construction and engineering giant 
Morrison Knudsen Corp., which, like Peterson's company, was based 
in Boise. 
</P>
<P>
	The system is used worldwide now, and the company he founded  
with his brother, Peterson Rebuild and Exchange Co., or Preco Inc. 
as it is known today, is the world's largest supplier of reverse 
warning systems. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990528.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 06:58:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  NATO Insists Milosevic Is Losing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Charles Wald was reviewing yet another F-16  
fighter jet's video tape of yet another 2,000-pound NATO bomb 
turning yet another Serb army barracks into yet another fireball in 
Kosovo -- yet more evidence, he claimed, that NATO is winning and 
Slobodan Milosevic is losing. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've got to wonder how much more he can take,'' mused the  
Air Force major general in what sounded like a hint of frustration. 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, after more than nine weeks of bombing, what more can  
NATO do, short of a ground war, to break the Yugoslav leader? 
</P>
<P>
	Milosevic's indictment by a United Nations tribunal for  
atrocities in Kosovo might make Milosevic even less likely to 
capitulate, retired Marine Corps Lt. Gen. Bernard Trainor said 
Thursday. That, in turn, raises the likelihood that NATO will have 
to go beyond airstrikes alone, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	If NATO cannot break Milosevic's will to resist, what then? At  
some point, many argue, the cumulative damage from bombing Serbia 
end to end will virtually paralyze Serb military and police forces 
in Kosovo. They will lose the ability to fight effectively either 
the Kosovo Liberation Army or a NATO-led international force that 
might enter Kosovo to return refugees to their homes. 
</P>
<P>
	Britain is making a case to its NATO partners -- without complete  
success, so far -- that when this point is reached, a NATO-led force 
on Kosovo's perimeter could move in and finish off the Serb 
military without resorting to full-scale warfare. They say it could 
be done by summer's end, in order to get the hundreds of thousands 
of displaced ethnic Albanians back into their villages before the 
onset of winter. 
</P>
<P>
	Trainor, who co-authored ``The Generals' War,'' on the 1991 Gulf  
War, called the British approach ``clever and very doable,'' 
although the NATO force should assume the Serbs would not just roll 
over. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. intelligence officials claim Milosevic's military advisers  
have told him they could hold out against a NATO-led ground force 
for months by using guerrilla tactics of hit-and-run attacks in 
Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Milosevic is spending much of his time in bunkers supplied with  
food, water and electricity, according to American intelligence 
reports that say he has lost touch with the reality of conditions 
facing the Serb population. 
</P>
<P>
	Wald, too, wonders if Milosevic's military commanders are giving  
him the full picture of the bomb damage, but he doubts it would 
make much difference even if they did tell him how badly Serbia is 
being pummeled. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a lot more willing to sacrifice his people and  
capabilities,'' Wald said. ``So once again, it's hard to judge his 
will, but it certainly isn't hard to judge how much of his 
capability is being destroyed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For now, the Clinton administration still hopes Milosevic will  
cave -- either agree to NATO's demands or simply to give up and pull 
his troops out of the southern Serbian province, allowing the 
refugees to return under the protection of a peacekeeping force. 
</P>
<P>
	In pursuit of that aim, NATO warplanes are accelerating the pace  
of attacks and taking the war closer to Milosevic. On several 
recent days, NATO bombs have targeted a presidential villa outside 
Belgrade that includes what Wald called a command and control 
bunker. Milosevic apparently was not there, but Wald said the 
attacks would alert him to the fact that NATO is hitting hard at 
his levers of power. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the NATO bombing began in March, many in the Clinton  
administration had believed that bombing threats alone would bring 
Milosevic back to the bargaining table to settle the Kosovo crisis. 
When that didn't happen, they expected that a few days or weeks of 
bombing would do the trick. Wrong again. 
</P>
<P>
	As far back as April 6, Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said of  
Milosevic: ``He's rattled.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Six days later, Wald proclaimed: ``He's starting to hurt.''  
</P>
<P>
	On April 27, the NATO commander, Gen. Wesley Clark, said: ``The  
noose ... is tightening.''	   And on May 24, NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana told an 
interviewer Milosevic was ``cracking.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gen. Dennis Reimer, the soon-to-retire Army chief of staff, said  
in an interview that he had doubts from the outset that air power 
alone would achieve NATO's political goals. More than nine weeks 
into the campaign, it remains unclear how close NATO is to pushing 
Milosevic over the edge, Reimer said. 
</P>
<P>
	``You just don't know if you're an hour away from him  
capitulating or whether you're months away,'' said the four-star 
general. ``And so that's the difficulty that I think everybody has 
in this whole thing.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990528.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 06:58:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
