<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Scottish Soccer Rivalry Resumes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GLASGOW, Scotland (AP) -- Authorities hope to prevent any  
resumption of violence when this city's bitter soccer rivals meet 
in Saturday's Scottish Cup final. 
</P>
<P>
	Glasgow Rangers, bidding to add the championship to the league  
title and League Cup championship they have already won, go up 
against Glasgow Celtic, which is completing a disappointing season. 
</P>
<P>
	It will be the fifth time the teams have played this season with  
each side winning once and two matches ending in draws. 
</P>
<P>
	The last game, won by the Rangers 3-0 at Celtic Park to clinch  
the league title, was nasty. 
</P>
<P>
	Referee Hugh Dallas handed out three red cards and crowd  
violence was directed at him, with a coin thrown from the stands 
striking him in the head. More than 100 people were arrested, 
including three Celtic fans who ran onto the field. The next day, a 
mob attacked Dallas' home in Glasgow. 
</P>
<P>
	Dallas will be the referee again for Saturday's game.  
</P>
<P>
	Security at neutral, 52,000-seat Hampden Park will be unusually  
tight, with opposing fans segregated. The game has an early 3 p.m. 
start to cut down drinking time. Rangers' fans are mostly 
Protestant, while Celtic supporters are mainly Catholic. 
</P>
<P>
	Hampden Park, hosting its first game since a $100 million  
refurbishment, has been fitted with 58 closed-circuit television 
cameras to monitor the stadium and surrounding streets. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't want a repeat of the scenario which developed last  
time,'' said Celtic captain Tom Boyd. ``But all that matters is 
getting our own game right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This will be the 13th time the two so-called ``Old Firm'' rivals  
have met in the Scottish Cup final and Celtic has won the last 
three -- all 1-0. Celtic holds a 7-5 edge in Scottish Cup finals 
against Rangers. 
</P>
<P>
	Celtic has had a miserable season, with injuries and early exits  
from European Champions Cup qualifying and the UEFA Cup. The season 
highlight was a 5-1 drubbing of Rangers on Nov. 21. 
</P>
<P>
	Rangers captain Lorenzo Amoruso knows a victory would make  
Celtic's season. But he knows how important the game is to the 
Rangers, too. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will be really hard because Celtic will be desperate to  
stop Rangers winning everything,'' Amoruso said. ``But we are 
desperate as well. Coping with the pressure could be the key to the 
game, neither side wants to lose the game and each wants to give 
the other a bad time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Giovanni Van Bronckhorst, who came to the Rangers this season on  
a $8.4 million transfer from Feyenoord, is hoping for a 
trouble-free final. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a lot riding on this game and both sides will stand  
up to each other and give it their best,'' he said. ``Everyone just 
hopes that the troubles off the pitch are not repeated.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
