<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 13:21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Parcells Tells Jets To Keep Heads </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. -- In the wake of the Jets' 23-10 loss to the  
Denver Broncos in the AFC title game in January, coach Bill 
Parcells has heard all the breathless forecasts about his club's 
potential for the coming season. 
</P>
<P>
	His response? Big deal.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's so much bull,'' Parcells said Friday of the favorable  
predictions about the Jets' chances, especially following the 
retirement of Denver quarterback John Elway. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's part of the game, I know that. I don't look at the  
prognostications with a degree of resentment, but I also know what 
it represents, and that's nothing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The veteran coach has history on his side. Of the 10 losers of  
AFC title games from 1988 to '97, only one team -- the 1994 
Pittsburgh Steelers -- reached the conference title game the 
following year. Additionally, seven of the clubs failed to get past 
the following year's wild-card round, and four failed to reach the 
postseason. 
</P>
<P>
	With that in mind, Parcells told players earlier in the week  
that they should not ``be seduced by expectations.'' Of the six 
teams favored to win division crowns last season, he stressed, only 
one, the Broncos, actually did. The coach also has delivered 
motivational jabs to players coming off impressive seasons, 
including quarterback Vinny Testaverde and wide receiver Wayne 
Chrebet. 
</P>
<P>
	``I told Vinny, `You could be like chickens falling off a cliff,  
Testaverde, falling off so fast,' '' Parcells said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Shoot, he told me that there wouldn't be a parachute big  
enough if I fell off the cliff anytime,'' said the undersized 
Chrebet, a record-setting performer despite his 5-foot-9 build. 
</P>
<P>
	Testaverde, who last year at this time was waiting for the  
Baltimore Ravens to release him, has taken Parcells' jabs to heart. 
Despite rebounding with the Jets to post record-setting numbers en 
route to the Pro Bowl, he's wary of taking anything for granted. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any of us who thought at all about skipping a day of working  
out, running or whatever, I think he's let us know that won't be 
acceptable,'' Testaverde said. ``I think you have to have high 
expectations, but it has nothing to do with what you did a year 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just because we went to the AFC championship has no bearing on  
expectations. When I was in Tampa early in my career, I came in 
with high expectations every year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Jets, coming off their first AFC East crown and only their  
second berth in the AFC title game since the AFL-NFL merger in 
1970, are expected to be Super Bowl contenders thanks to a roster 
bolstered by free agent additions including free safety Steve 
Atwater, tight end Eric Green, linebacker Roman Phifer and punter 
Tom Tupa. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't allow my team to get caught up in that,'' Parcells  
said. ``I know what these kids have been hearing all winter. I know 
because I've been hearing the same thing. People walk up to me all 
the time saying, `This is the year.' 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't allow yourself to really begin to believe that. I  
just told the team, `We're starting over.''' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990528.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 13:51:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Michigan Investigating Booster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANN ARBOR, Mich. (AP) -- The University of Michigan is  
investigating allegations that a booster had dealings with men's 
basketball players after he was banned from associating with the 
team in 1997, according to newspaper reports. 
</P>
<P>
	Provost Nancy Cantor said Thursday that a four-member faculty  
committee would review athletic department reforms begun in 1997 as 
a result of an NCAA-mandated probe of Ed Martin's contacts with 
former players and coaches, the Detroit Free Press reported Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The school also will review safeguards implemented by the  
athletic department. 
</P>
<P>
	Cantor said athletic director Tom Goss requested the review last  
week after published reports about a federal investigation of 
whether Martin -- a Ford Motor Co. retiree -- ran an illegal numbers 
operation at Detroit-area Ford plants. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of that probe, the FBI reportedly is examining whether  
Martin gave large amounts of cash and loans to several former 
Wolverines players, dating to the Fab Five era in the early 1990s. 
</P>
<P>
	Published reports have suggested that wiretaps recorded  
conversations between Martin and several former Wolverine 
standouts, including Chris Webber, Louis Bullock, Robert Traylor 
and Maurice Taylor, according to a person familiar with the 
investigation. School officials have said the FBI told them that no 
evidence had surfaced of gambling on Wolverines games. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to make sure the policies are tough enough and make  
changes if necessary,'' Ms. Cantor said. ``We believe we put in 
place very strong policies, but we want to make sure they are 
working.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cantor told The Ann Arbor News Thursday that she hopes to get  
the committee's initial report within a month. She will then 
discuss it with Goss and Marvin Krislov, the university's vice 
president and general counsel. The committee is being chaired by 
Jerome Miller, an adjunct professor of psychology at the school and 
director of the Center for the Child and the Family. 
</P>
<P>
	Other members include Suellyn Scarnecchia, assistant dean for  
clinical affairs in the law school; Derrick Gragg, the school's 
NCAA rules compliance coordinator; and Paul Edwards, an attorney in 
the office of the general counsel. 
</P>
<P>
	The committee arises in the wake of new concerns over Martin's  
activities. Federal authorities searched his home on April 28. 
Agents from the FBI and the Internal Revenue Service, who also 
raided 11 other homes that day, seized more than $150,000 in cash, 
10 handguns and gambling paraphernalia. 
</P>
<P>
	A person familiar with the investigation told the Free Press  
that among the points the committee will examine are whether Martin 
has been seen around the team since he was banned in March 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin was a target in a 1997 investigation of the university's  
basketball program that prompted his being banned, Goss' firing of 
coach Steve Fisher and minor NCAA sanctions. 
</P>
<P>
	School President Lee Bollinger said he and Goss decided to take  
another look at the procedures after learning about the federal 
investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	``On these sorts of matters, you can never rest,'' Bollinger  
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
