<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 5 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Milosevic Meets With Russian Envoy  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Russia's Balkan envoy met  
face-to-face with Slobodan Milosevic for nine hours today, 
declaring the Yugoslav president key to a Kosovo peace plan despite 
complications caused by his indictment for war crimes. Viktor 
Chernomyrdin again urged a pause in NATO's bombing campaign to give 
peace negotiations a chance. But his U.S. counterpart was critical 
of the effort, emphasizing the Russian sponsored proposal 
represents Moscow -- not the alliance. Meanwhile, NATO took 
advantage of good weather to hit a wide range of targets on its 
66th day of airstrikes. 

</P>
<P>
	Pakistan Celebrates Nuclear Tests  
</P>
<P>
	ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) -- Pakistan celebrated the one-year  
anniversary of its nuclear tests today against a backdrop of 
blistering artillery duels and downed Indian aircraft on its 
volatile Kashmir frontier with neighboring India. Giant posters 
proclaimed Pakistani scientists as ``nuclear heroes.'' President 
Rafiq Tarar warned India against further escalation of hostilities 
in the disputed Kashmir region, where Pakistan said it shot down 
two Indian jet fighters yesterday. India says it will continue its 
operations to flush out Islamic militants, who New Delhi charges 
are backed by Pakistani troops. 

</P>
<P>
	No N. Korea Nuclear Violations Found  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The State Department said today that a U.S.  
inspection of a complex in North Korea yielded no evidence that the 
nation is in violation of a 5-year-old nuclear agreement. Spokesman 
James P. Rubin also said that while special envoy William Perry did 
not meet with North Korean President Kim Jong Il, his delegation 
was ``well received'' in Pyongyang. Addressing speculation that 
nuclear-related equipment might have been moved out before U.S. 
inspectors arrived, Rubin said, ``It was at a stage of construction 
prior to the time when any relevant equipment other than 
construction equipment would be expected to be present.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Judge Upholds Late-Term Abortion Ban  
</P>
<P>
	MADISON, Wis. (AP) -- A federal judge ruled today that a  
Wisconsin law that bars a type of late-term abortion is 
constitutional. In his ruling, the judge said the law, aimed at 
what critics call ``partial-birth abortions,'' does not place an 
undue burden on women and that the state does have a valid interest 
in banning the procedure. Under the law, doctors who perform the 
procedure would be subject to first-degree murder charges and life 
in prison if convicted. Patients would not be punished. 

</P>
<P>
	Father Pleads Guilty in Kidnap Case  
</P>
<P>
	CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) -- Florida socialite Stephen Fagan pleaded  
guilty to kidnapping today and was spared a prison term after 
admitting he abducted his two daughters 20 years ago and told them 
their mother was dead. Under the deal, Fagan, who invented a life 
for himself and his girls in Florida, was fined $100,000. The money 
will be given to a Boston orphanage, a charity chosen by his 
ex-wife, Barbara Kurth. The daughters, Rachael and Lisa Martin, now 
25 and 22, thanked their father in court for his sacrifices. 

</P>
<P>
	New Speed Limit in Montana  
</P>
<P>
	HELENA, Mont. (AP) -- With the flashing lights of a Montana  
Highway Patrol car in his rearview mirror, Jody Darcy made history 
this morning as one of the first motorists stopped for violating 
the state's new speed limit. Once the only state without a daytime 
speed limit, Montana's status as an American autobahn ended at dawn 
today when a 75 mph limit took effect. Fines start at $20 for up to 
10 mph over the limit; the maximum is $100 for speeds of 106 mph 
and over on the interstate. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Medal of Honor Winners Honored  
</P>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Nearly 100 Medal of Honor winners gathered  
today for the unveiling of the first monument recognizing the more 
than 3,400 recipients of America's highest distinction for military 
valor. The Medal of Honor Memorial consists of 27 curved glass 
panels that rise above the canal that splits downtown Indianapolis. 
The panels bear the names of all Medal of Honor winners from 15 
military conflicts dating to the Civil War. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks End Higher; Dow Up 92.81  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rebounded today from yesterday's steep  
selloff as new economic data showing slower-than-expected growth 
helped calm fears about rising inflation and higher interest rates. 
The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 92.81 at 10,559.74. 
Advancers on the New York Stock Exchange outnumbered decliners 
1,964-975. The Nasdaq composite index was up 51.26 to 2,470.41. 

</P>
<P>
	Holyfield-Lewis Fight in November  
</P>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- Evander Holyfield and Lennox Lewis will fight a  
rematch for the undisputed heavyweight title in Las Vegas in 
November. Exactly when and where, though, remains to be decided. A 
new deal between boxing promoter Don King and a major casino 
operator means the fight will take place in Las Vegas, most likely 
on Nov. 13. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by GABRIEL MADWAY  
</P>
