<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) -- The government is investigating  
reports that an incursion of Colombian guerrillas has frightened 
Panamanian villagers into fleeing their homes, officials said 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Government Minister Mariela Sagel and Police Chief Jose Luis  
Sosa flew Friday to the Puerto Obaldia region, where Panama borders 
Colombia along the Atlantic Ocean. 
</P>
<P>
	Local newspapers have reported that Kuna Yala Indians from the  
area have been fleeing their villages because of men presumed to be 
Colombian rebels. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials said they have not been able to confirm an incursion,  
but national education director, Mirna Vallejos, said teachers and 
students from the Puerto Obaldia area had been relocated due to 
fear of a guerilla incursion. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	LIMA, Peru (AP) -- Customs agents seized four pre-Incan mummies,  
pre-Incan tapestries, ceramics, baskets and fishing nets set to be 
smuggled to Miami, customs officials said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The artifacts were found Thursday in a container along with a  
1982 truck set to be shipped from Lima's port of Callao, customs 
officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	National Culture Institute specialists said customs officials  
became suspicious of the container when they noticed that its cargo 
-- the truck -- was valued at $455, less than a third of the cost of 
the export duties. 
</P>
<P>
	Peru suffers from widespread looting of its archaeological  
sites, with much of the loot smuggled abroad. It was the home of 
the pre-Columbian Inca, Moche, Chavin and Nazca cultures. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the cultures sacrificed young people to the gods, and  
the remains were preserved by dry desert or cold mountaintop 
conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	LIMA, Peru (AP) -- Japan's Princess Sayako arrived Friday in Lima  
amid tight security to start a 15-day trip to Peru and Bolivia 
commemorating the 100th anniversary of Japanese immigration to the 
South American nations. 
</P>
<P>
	Peru has 15,000 police protecting Sayako, also known as Princess  
Nori, an Interior Ministry spokesman said. Sayako is the only 
daughter of Emperor Akihito and Empress Michiko. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese officials asked for the special security after the 1996  
raid by leftist Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement rebels on the 
Japanese ambassador's residence in Lima and the subsequent 126-day 
hostage standoff, local newspapers reported. 
</P>
<P>
	President Alberto Fujimori is of Japanese descent and has  
strengthened Peru's ties to Japan since being elected president in 
1990. More than 45,000 people of Japanese descent live in Peru, 
which has a population of 25 million. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) -- Former dictator Alfredo Stroessner  
continues to possess the title of ``honorary president'' of the 
long-governing Colorado Party, a party deputy said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Stroessner, now 85, was toppled in a February 1989 coup that  
ushered in the restoration of democratic rule in this South 
American nation. The former strongman has lived in exile in Brazil 
for the past decade. 
</P>
<P>
	Enrique Riera, the ruling party deputy, told local television  
that Stroessner continues to carry the honorific title despite his 
ouster and exile. ``The party never expelled him,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Colorado Party has governed the past half-century in  
Paraguay through both dictatorship and democracy. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- President Andres Pastrana on Friday  
pledged tougher controls on a massive southern region where all 
government troops were withdrawn to facilitate peace talks with 
leftist guerrillas. 
</P>
<P>
	The commitment comes two days after a widely respected political  
veteran resigned as defense minister to protest Pastrana's refusal 
to set a time limit on the military evacuation from Colombia's 
southern zone. 
</P>
<P>
	Emerging from an all-day session with the military high command  
at an army base in the central state of Tolima, Pastrana defended 
his decision while promising to establish clear ``rules of the 
game'' governing rebel activities in the 16,200 square-mile zone. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's never been a (successful peace) process in the world  
that has put a deadline on the negotiations,'' Pastrana said. 
</P>
<P>
	Pastrana has yet to name a replacement for former Foreign  
Minister Rodrigo Lloreda, who stepped down Wednesday over what he 
called excessive government concessions to leftist rebels. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- A bus carrying the crew for the Spanish  
pop-rock duo Duncan Dhu crashed on the highway from Mexico City to 
Acapulco on Friday, killing a sound technician and injuring six 
people, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Guerrero state police said the driver apparently became drowsy  
and lost control of the tour bus, which plunged down a 150-foot 
embankment, according to the Televisa television network. 
</P>
<P>
	The two members of Duncan Dhu, Mikel Erentxun and Diego Vasallo,  
were not in the bus, a group spokeswoman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Duncan Dhu was popular in Spain in the late 1980s and early  
1990s before Erentxun and Vasallo split up for solo careers. They 
reunited last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
