<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Az. Motorola Expansion Moves Ahead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHANDLER, Ariz. (AP) -- A $90 million Motorola expansion, delayed  
by a slump in the semiconductor industry, is about to go ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	Motorola said Thursday it is beginning construction that's  
expected to add about 500 jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	``When completed (in 2002), the Chandler facility will be our  
largest manufacturing campus in the world,'' said William Seiferth, 
chief of staff for Motorola's Semiconductor Products Sector. 
</P>
<P>
	The expansion will triple the number of processors,  
microcontrollers and other devices made in Chandler. 
</P>
<P>
	During the past year, under pressure of the Asian economic  
crisis and the related semiconductor slump, Motorola eliminated 
2,075 jobs in metro Phoenix. Analysts say the slump has bottomed 
out. 
</P>
<P>
	Motorola, the world's No. 3 chip manufacturer, already has  
completed basic construction of the buildings on the 80-acre 
campus. As part of the $1.1 billion expansion, Motorola said it 
will now spend $50 million on robots and other technology to fully 
equip its new plant. Some equipment is already in, and production 
has begun in the area. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, Motorola will spend $40 million to complete the interior  
construction of another building. Plans call for installing 
heating, piping, gas lines and other equipment. The building then 
will be equipped next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Work is to begin in the next few weeks.  
</P>
<P>
	The expansion project has already created about 60 jobs and is  
expected to add 60 more by the end of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of Motorola's furloughed employees will not be eligible to  
rejoin the company since most accepted voluntary severance packages 
that prevent them from returning to work for the company for two 
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
