<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Manager a National Hit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NISHINOMIYA, Japan (AP) -- In a nation beset by economic gloom,  
Japan could use a hero now. And it may have found one in Katsuya 
Nomura, the potbellied, grim-faced manager of perhaps the country's 
worst baseball team. 
</P>
<P>
	Nomura's appeal is his reputation for pulling victory out of  
defeat. And that's a talent most of Japan, stuck in its worst 
recession since World War II, longs for these days. 
</P>
<P>
	The popularity of Nomura, in his first season as manager for the  
Hanshin Tigers, is hard to miss. First, are the beer commercials. 
Then there are the T-shirts, key chains and pens. There are even 
tea, wine and box lunches with a Nomura motif. 
</P>
<P>
	``Manager Nomura can stop the recession,'' gushed a recent  
headline in the Sankei, a major newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	A study by the Sakura Institute of Research, a Tokyo think tank,  
found that the economic lift from Nomura's Tigers was phenomenal, 
totaling more than $107 million -- through rising game attendance, 
hotel revenue from out-of-town fans, not to mention the sales of 
newspapers and magazines carrying the latest on the Tigers as well 
as the Nomura-theme goods. 
</P>
<P>
	It doesn't hurt that the Tigers, the perennial losers, are  
having a great season -- surging to second place in the six-club 
Central League and stirring hopes they may even win the pennant. 
</P>
<P>
	For several years, Nomura has been seen as more than just a  
baseball guru in a team-oriented nation that stresses the group 
over the individual. 
</P>
<P>
	In an annual survey of young government workers, Nomura has for  
the past three years been rated one of the top five people they 
would most like to work for. 
</P>
<P>
	He was No. 1 in 1994, a year after his former team, the Yakult  
Swallows, won the Japan Series, the nation's equivalent of the 
World Series. 
</P>
<P>
	``The people here love him,'' said Tigers third baseman Mike  
Blowers, an American import who has played with the Los Angeles 
Dodgers, Seattle Mariners and Montreal Expos. 
</P>
<P>
	When Nomura accepted his job as Tigers' manager, the 63-year-old  
portrayed himself as an older man just trying to hang on -- like so 
many others in a workforce increasingly characterized by downsizing 
and voluntary retirement. 
</P>
<P>
	``I consider it a privilege to be wanted in my 60s,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	The story of Nomura's life is a rags-to-riches Japanese dream.  
When Nomura was 3, his father was killed in a war with China. From 
then on, Nomura grew up in a poor, single-parent home. 
</P>
<P>
	A struggled as a catcher in the pros.  
</P>
<P>
	``I was beaten so many times by my coaches because I didn't look  
like I was trying,'' he recalled. 
</P>
<P>
	But he emerged in the 1950s as one of the country's greatest  
players. He was the MVP five times and Triple Crown winner in 1965, 
and led his league in home runs for nine seasons. He remains second 
on the career home run list with 657, trailing Sadaharu Oh. 
</P>
<P>
	His reputation for leading underdogs to victory started with his  
previous club, the Yakult Swallows. 
</P>
<P>
	Until Nomura arrived in 1990, the Swallows won the Japan Series  
only once in the series' five-decade history. They won it three 
times under Nomura. 
</P>
<P>
	A typical Nomura-style game -- like Japanese management in  
general -- isn't all flash and home runs. It's more about smarts. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sometimes it's hard to understand his decisions while you're  
playing,'' Tigers infielder Hiroshi Yagi said. ``But later, you 
really see his point. I think he's fantastic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese believe that club managers -- as well as corporate  
bosses-- set the tone for the entire group. And it is team effort, 
never individual heroism, that leads to victory. 
</P>
<P>
	Books on baseball, newspaper articles and TV commentators often  
break down Nomura's strategy, likening it to corporate management 
styles. 
</P>
<P>
	So great has Nomura's popularity grown that even his wife has  
been catapulted to TV and lecture-circuit stardom. The flamboyant 
Sachiyo is also gossiped about on talk shows and is followed by 
cameras wherever she goes. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, not everyone is sure Nomura can magically turn around the  
Tigers. 
</P>
<P>
	``No matter how brilliant he is, it's the players who have to  
play the game,'' said Keiji Masui, a fan of the Tokyo Yomiuri 
Giants, the Tigers' longtime rivals. ``It'll be a while yet before 
the Tigers win the pennant.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
