<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 16:41:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> MCI WorldCom Buys Skytel for $1.3B </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- MCI WorldCom Inc. is buying the pager company  
SkyTel Communications Inc. for nearly $1.3 billion in stock, 
announcing the deal just days after the companies scuttled rumors 
they were discussing a merger. 
</P>
<P>
	MCI WorldCom said Friday it would pay stock worth $21.24 for  
each share of SkyTel, partially filling a gaping wireless hole in 
an otherwise broad list of telecommunications businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	MCI WorldCom, the nation's No. 2 long-distance phone company and  
a major owner of the circuitry that makes up the Internet, will 
also absorb about $525 million in debt from SkyTel, which is one of 
the few profitable companies in the paging industry. 
</P>
<P>
	While the purchase represents a major foray into the wireless  
business, the equipment and the part of the radio spectrum used by 
paging networks aren't good for carrying voices or high-speed data. 
</P>
<P>
	So for now, MCI WorldCom essentially remains a non-player in the  
wireless calling market, reselling other cellular services under 
its own name to a small number of customers. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, shares of SkyTel shot higher after an Internet  
service named Company Sleuth reported that MCI WorldCom had 
reserved the Web site domain name ``skytelworldcom.com.'' 
</P>
<P>
	MCI WorldCom quickly played down the significance of that move,  
saying it routinely reserves domain names that might have value, 
and that the registration for the SkyTel-related name was the work 
of an overzealous employee. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement announced Friday comes amid a frenzy of  
deal-making that's reshaping the communications industry, with 
phone companies like Bell Atlantic and GTE merging and AT&AMP;T 
spending about $100 billion on cable TV properties it plans to use 
for phone calls and Internet access. 
</P>
<P>
	For MCI WorldCom, the SkyTel deal comes after two failed  
attempts to buy its way into the $33 billion wireless 
communications industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Just weeks ago, talks to acquire Nextel Communications, the  
largest independent wireless company, unraveled after the companies 
failed to agree on price. In January, MCI WorldCom dropped out of a 
bidding war to buy AirTouch Communications. 
</P>
<P>
	MCI WorldCom didn't rule out a future acquisition, but didn't  
disclose any specific plans. 
</P>
<P>
	``We see a lot of opportunity for growth in the overall wireless  
market, and over time, we expect to be a broader participant in 
that market,'' said Frank Walter, a spokesman for MCI WorldCom. 
</P>
<P>
	SkyTel and MCI WorldCom, both based in Mississippi, have  
long-standing business ties. MCI WorldCom is the largest reseller 
of the SkyTel's messaging services. 
</P>
<P>
	SkyTel, with about 1.6 million customers, has been a leader in  
the move toward two-way pagers that enable customers to exchange 
messages directly with other pagers or via the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	MCI WorldCom president and chief executive Bernie Ebbers said  
the acquisition is an important building block in the company's 
overall wireless strategy. 
</P>
<P>
	``SkyTel is the industry leader in wireless messaging, and is  
ahead of the curve in developing and implementing wireless data 
applications,'' said Ebbers. ``SkyTel also brings a talented 
management team with a wealth of experience in wireless 
communications.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The deal, expected to be completed in six to nine months, was  
announced after the close of financial markets Friday. Shares of 
SkyTel rose $1 to $20.31 1/4, while shares of MCI WorldCom rose $1.43 3/4 
a share to $86.37 1/2, both on the Nasdaq Stock Market. 




</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
