<HEADLINE> Japanese Stocks Close Sharply Lower / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Fears that America's economic boom may be faltering  
sent Japanese stock prices sharply lower today. The dollar 
retreated against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average lost 204.51 points,  
or 1.26 percent, to finish the day at 15,972.68. On Thursday, the 
Nikkei index shed 53.33 points, or 0.33 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 120.52 yen, down 1.91 yen from late Thursday  
in Tokyo but above its late New York level of 120.38 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, investors worried about a possible slowdown  
in the U.S. economy following Thursday's plunge in New York stock 
prices. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wall Street overnight, the Dow Jones industrial average sank  
235.23 points to 10,466.93, its worst single-session decline of the 
year and its lowest level since April 20. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo stock prices fell sharply in the morning as investors  
dumped export-oriented shares such as telecommunications and 
electronics issues after their U.S. counterparts fell. 
</P>
<P>
	But in the afternoon domestic institutional investors began  
buying shares seen as having strong earnings potential, pulling the 
market off its lows. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market is at a difficult stage,'' said Kunihiro Hatae,  
general manager of stock trading at Tokyo Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Another negative factor was a sharp decline in near-term June  
Nikkei futures prices Thursday on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, 
traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hideyuki Okoshi, deputy manager at Chuo Securities, said the  
Nikkei 225 was likely, however, to find support between 15,700 and 
15,900 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors were also discouraged by a stronger yen against the  
dollar. A higher yen makes Japanese exports more expensive abroad 
and thus less competitive, cutting into earnings at export-led 
Japanese companies. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was down 10.10 points, or 0.78 percent, to 1,292.07 
points. The TOPIX closed down 1.15 points, or 0.09 percent, 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Activity was sparse as investors grew cautious ahead of the  
Memorial Day holiday Monday in the United States, which will close 
markets there. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume on the First Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange was  
estimated at 416.73 million shares, up slightly 396.41 million 
shares Tuesday. Retreating issues outnumbered advancers 941 to 236, 
while 118 issues were unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar's relative strength from its  
New York levels came as investors hunted for bargains and covered 
short, or oversold, positions. 
</P>
<P>
	The greenback tumbled to a low of 119.70 yen in New York  
overnight -- the first time it broke through the 120-yen mark since 
May 3 -- as market players took cues from the sell-off in the Dow 
Jones industrial average. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar ranged between 120.22 yen and 120.81 yen in today's  
trading. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 126.08 yen, down  
from 127.58 yen late Thursday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 213 10-year Japanese government  
bond dipped to 1.4900 percent from 1.4950 percent late Thursday, 
driving its price up to 99.21 yen from 99.17 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
