<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Father Pleads Guilty in Kidnap Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) -- Florida socialite Stephen Fagan pleaded  
guilty to kidnapping Friday and was spared a prison term after 
admitting he abducted his two daughters 20 years ago and told them 
their mother was dead. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the deal, Fagan, who invented a life for himself and his  
girls in Florida, was fined $100,000. The money will be given to a 
Boston orphanage, a charity chosen by his ex-wife, Barbara Kurth. 
</P>
<P>
	Kurth was in court, but chose not to speak. It was the first  
time she, her daughters and her ex-husband had been in the same 
room together since he kidnapped the girls from her home. 
</P>
<P>
	Fagan received a suspended three-to-five-year prison sentence  
and must serve probation for five years. He also was ordered to 
perform 2,000 hours of community service at the Department of 
Veterans Affairs Medical Center in West Palm Beach, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	Fagan could have been sentenced to 20 years in prison if  
convicted of two counts of kidnapping. 
</P>
<P>
	``This has been a tragic, difficult and wrenching case for  
everyone who has been victimized by Mr. Fagan's unlawful conduct,'' 
Middlesex Superior Court Judge Peter Lauriat said in accepting the 
plea agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	In a strong, deep voice, a haggard-looking Fagan told the judge  
he took his girls without their mother's consent. 
</P>
<P>
	Rachael and Lisa Martin, now 25 and 22, thanked their father in  
court for his sacrifices. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do not feel victimized by our father,'' Rachael Martin told  
the court. ``We are convinced that his actions were from his 
heart.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In October 1979, Fagan kidnapped his daughters, then 2 and 5,  
from Massachusetts and moved them to Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	Fagan, 57, who has been free on $250,000 bail, claimed he  
rescued them from an unfit and alcoholic mother. The courts at the 
time, he said after his arrest, didn't look kindly on a father 
seeking custody. 
</P>
<P>
	Kurth, who was divorced from Fagan in 1978, denies the charge  
and said she was suffering from narcolepsy, an illness that causes 
sudden, deep sleep. 
</P>
<P>
	Fagan was living under the assumed name Dr. William Martin when  
he was arrested in his Palm Beach, Fla., mansion last year after 
eluding authorities for 19 years. Authorities had caught up with 
him after Massachusetts state police got a telephone tip that he 
was living in Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time of his arrest, Fagan, who had married a prosperous  
land developer, was driving expensive cars and was a member in some 
of the most exclusive clubs in Palm Beach. 
</P>
<P>
	Kurth, now a biologist at the University of Virginia, has been  
unsuccessful thus far in reuniting with her daughters, her lawyer 
has said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some legal observers questioned whether prosecutors would be  
sending the wrong message with such a lenient deal. 
</P>
<P>
	``Kidnapping is a very serious offense and it's not less serious  
because a parent commits the act,'' said Wendy Murphy, a former 
prosecutor and legal analyst. 
</P>
<P>
	Just because the daughters don't want to see their father  
imprisoned doesn't mean Fagan automatically deserves to remain 
free, Murphy said. 
</P>
<P>
	The fact that the kidnaping happened two decades ago doesn't  
lessen the seriousness of what he did, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``He would have been in a huge pile of trouble had we caught him  
sooner,'' said Murphy, who heads the Victim Advocacy and Research 
Group. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
