<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Deputy Prime Minister Quits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- In the biggest blow yet to Russian Prime Minister  
Sergei Stepashin, one of his top two deputies resigned Friday less 
than a week after being appointed. 
</P>
<P>
	The resignation of First Deputy Prime Minister Mikhail Zadornov  
marked the second power struggle the new prime minister has lost 
since being appointed by President Boris Yeltsin just over two 
weeks ago, and led to speculation that Stepashin might be next to 
step down. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Zadornov's new post was a promotion, he also had wanted  
to maintain control over the Finance Ministry, which he had headed 
in the past three governments. 
</P>
<P>
	``My stance is that the Finance Ministry should play a key role  
in the government,'' he told reporters, explaining that the 
government needed a ``unified economic bloc'' to realize its main 
economic tasks. 
</P>
<P>
	``Unfortunately, my position did not find support from the  
president or his administration staff,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, in an interview on NTV television, Zadornov said he had  
not been able to speak directly with Yeltsin about his resignation 
plans. 
</P>
<P>
	Zadornov had been a strong proponent of reform in the  
government, and he spoke with pride Friday about his ministry's 
achievements, including keeping the government within its budget 
for the past eight months. 
</P>
<P>
	His departure was a visible defeat for Stepashin, whom Yeltsin  
appointed prime minister May 12 after sacking Yevgeny Primakov. 
</P>
<P>
	Stepashin had proposed that Alexander Zhukov, the head of the  
budget committee in the lower house of parliament, be appointed 
first deputy premier in charge of economic policy and that Zadornov 
remain at the helm of the Finance Ministry. Yeltsin rejected that 
recommendation. 
</P>
<P>
	As speculation about his political weakness has grown, Stepashin  
has tried hard to project an air of authority -- although, being the 
fourth prime minister in just 14 months, he knows well that Yeltsin 
can fire him any time. 
</P>
<P>
	But on Friday he delicately confirmed that a behind-the-scenes  
struggle was holding up a final decision on the makeup of his 
government. 
</P>
<P>
	Stepashin, looking grim, asked reporters covering his meeting  
with Norwegian Prime Minister Kjell Magne Bondevik to stop asking 
questions about the drawn-out formation of the Cabinet. 
</P>
<P>
	``You know yourselves how it's going,'' he said with a long  
face, confirming at least some of the media speculation about 
infighting among Yeltsin's underlings. 
</P>
<P>
	Both the newspaper Vremya and the Interfax news agency predicted  
that Stepashin might be the next to resign. 
</P>
<P>
	All week long, Russian newspapers and airwaves had buzzed with  
theories about powerful forces at work on the Kremlin's picks for 
key Cabinet posts. 
</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin's daughter Tatyana Dyachenko, business mogul Boris  
Berezovsky and veteran reformer Anatoly Chubais were all believed 
to have a part in the decision-making, at Stepashin's expense. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest struggle has been over the post of finance minister.  
Initially, last Tuesday, the Kremlin had said Zadornov would stay 
in the post. Later the same day, another official, Mikhail 
Kasyanov, was appointed instead. 
</P>
<P>
	Communist Party chief Gennady Zyuganov said Friday that the  
mixed signals reflected a struggle among Chubais, Berezovsky and 
Yeltsin's family, and called the president ``a hostage to these 
string-pullers,'' Interfax reported. 
</P>
<P>
	``They seem to be at odds about who will take over the best  
Cabinet seats, embezzlement-wise,'' Interfax quoted him as saying. 
</P>
<P>
	Vremya noted that the struggle over who would oversee the  
Finance Ministry was over much more than a single Cabinet seat. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today, one compact financial-industrial group, elbowing out  
competitors, is getting control in fact over all the key posts in 
the executive,'' the newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
	Vremya was referring to Berezovsky, who appears to be the  
biggest winner in the Cabinet struggle. Yeltsin named a Berezovsky 
protege, Nikolai Aksyonenko, one of two first deputy prime 
ministers, and Aksyonenko has made it clear he'll take as much 
power as he can. Kasyanov and the new customs chief, Mikhail Vanin, 
are also believed to have ties to Berezovsky. 
</P>
<P>
	In his NTV television interview, Zadornov refused to be drawn  
into criticism of any other Cabinet appointments or of the people 
believed to be calling the shots in the Kremlin. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope that this whole story will help build up trust in the  
prime minister to do what he's responsible for: leading the 
government,'' Zadornov said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
