<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kodak-Fuji Film Price War Flares </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) -- A photographic film price war between  
Eastman Kodak Co. and Japanese nemesis Fuji is flaring up as the 
peak summer season nears, and Kodak appears to be losing ground on 
its home turf once more. 
</P>
<P>
	Kodak insists, however, that its seemingly sharp drop in market  
share in April is no more than a blip in its effort to rebound from 
a 1997 assault by Fuji Photo Film Co. that led to the elimination 
of 19,900 Kodak jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	In the U.S. market, two retail surveys show that Tokyo-based  
Fuji grabbed 5 percentage points in unit sales at Kodak's expense 
during the first four months of 1999. Most of the gains came in 
April. But even with the decline, Kodak still accounts for about 
two-thirds of the rolls of film sold in this country. 
</P>
<P>
	In a business made highly volatile by coupon discounts and other  
promotions, Kodak said a few weeks or even months are too brief a 
period to accurately reflect its market standing. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, the supermarket, drugstore and mass-merchant data, tracked  
by ACNielsen Corp. and Information Resources Inc., do not include 
manufacturers' sales and provide only a partial view of the photo 
industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Any Fuji inroads would be worrisome, however, at a time when  
Kodak seemed to be rebounding from two hard years of price battles. 
Some Wall Street analysts think Kodak will have to lower film 
prices to make up ground. 
</P>
<P>
	B. Alex Henderson of Prudential Securities Inc. noted last week  
in his monthly survey of stores in Philadelphia that Fuji's average 
price per roll of film fell 5.2 percent from April to May while 
Kodak's rose 2.2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Henderson says the Philadelphia data historically mirror trends  
in the national market. 
</P>
<P>
	Fuji said its recent success is driven by more than just  
discounts. 
</P>
<P>
	``We give the retailers better service and a better deal,'' said  
James Chung, director of financial relations at Fujifilm USA. ``As 
a retailer, you always try to push the product that is more 
profitable to you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, Kodak was initially slow to respond to Fuji's price  
cuts and then had to resort to the most severe cutbacks in its 
history -- hacking off 20 percent of its worldwide payroll of 
100,500. 
</P>
<P>
	Through deep discounts, it had regained nearly all of the market  
share it lost and vowed to counter Fuji more aggressively than 
before. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is clear to me that Kodak will not ignore an increase in  
the price differential of film in the same way they did as a 
company two years ago,'' said one Wall Street analyst whose company 
has a policy restricting employees from being quoted by name. 
</P>
<P>
	According to Chicago-based Information Resources, Kodak's unit  
share of U.S. film sales fell to 67.5 percent in April from 76.5 
percent in early January while Fuji's rose from 17.8 percent to 
22.3 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nielsen survey showed Kodak's unit share of 35mm, disposable  
and Advanced Photo System film sales dropped from 69.6 percent to 
64 percent while Fuji's share jumped from 18.4 percent to 23.4 
percent. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
