<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Euro Faalls to New Lows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar eked out gains against the euro  
Friday after the new currency dived to fresh lows despite efforts 
by senior European monetary officials to resuscitate their 
creation. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the euro was quoted at $1.0418, down  
from $1.0420 Thursday. During trading the euro fell to $1.0396, the 
first time it's fallen below $1.04. The euro has lost 10.7 percent 
since its launch in January and 1 percent for the week. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar rose to 121.43 yen from 120.38 yen, partially  
recovering from a nearly 2-yen fall on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the euro's steady decline since its January launch,  
European officials have mainly said they weren't worried and 
traders paid little heed. But traders paid attention Friday as a 
bevy of officials spoke out. 
</P>
<P>
	In a televised interview over CNN, Germany's central bank  
president-designate, Ernst Welteke, said he was worried about the 
recent decline. ``It has to stop,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder called the euro's  
fluctuations temporary, saying that ``excited reactions are 
completely superfluous.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The outgoing president of Germany's central bank, Hans  
Tietmeyer, said ``the euro has every potential to remain a stable 
currency.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I wouldn't be happy if there was any further decline'' in the  
euro, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro rose as high as $1.0487 while Tietmeyer spoke, as  
traders took the collective comments to mean that the European 
Central Bank was prepared finally to prop up the euro by 
intervening in foreign exchange markets. But investors waited in 
vain. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market in general made some intervention bets and the euro  
in fact has done nothing but drift lower'' to the new lows against 
the dollar, said Ricardo Gomes, head of foreign exchange at 
Republic National Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro started drifting upward in ever-decreasing volume,  
however, as traders went home early ahead of the three-day Memorial 
Day holiday weekend. Markets also will be closed in London for a 
bank holiday. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Friday, the dollar also was quoted at 1.5288 Swiss francs,  
up from 1.5238; and 1.4704 Canadian dollars, down from 1.4751. The 
British pound rose to $1.6003 from $1.5990. 
</P>
<P>
	The currencies of the 11 countries that have switched to the  
euro no longer are traded separately and are tied to the euro by a 
fixed rate. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on the euro's latest exchange rate, the dollar was worth:  
1.8781 German marks, up from 1.8769; 6.2964 French francs, up from 
6.2933; and 1,858.74 Italian lire, up from 1,858.22. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
