<HEADLINE> Japanese Auto Exports Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's exports of cars, trucks and buses fell 11.1  
percent in April from a year earlier, as rises in shipments to the 
United States and Asia were more than offset by declines to Latin 
America and the Middle East. 
</P>
<P>
	The Japan Automobile Manufacturers Association said Friday the  
drop to 337,845 vehicles was the third consecutive monthly decline. 
</P>
<P>
	Shipments to crisis-hit Asia rose for the first time in 19  
months as the economies of some countries in the region appeared to 
be bottoming out. Exports to Asia rose 6.2 percent to 23,866 
vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's vehicle exports to the United States were also up,  
rising 11.1 percent to 116,898. 
</P>
<P>
	But exports fell sharply to Latin America and the Middle East.  
</P>
<P>
	Latin America-bound exports tumbled 58.9 percent to 18,019  
because of economic troubles in the region. 
</P>
<P>
	Exports to the Middle East declined 34.3 percent to 16,972,  
following a deterioration in crude oil prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The April drop in exports followed a 1.9 percent year-to-year  
fall in March and a decline of 4.2 percent in February. 
</P>
<P>
	By automaker, Toyota Motor Corp.'s exports rose 2.9 percent to  
135,692 amid brisk exports to Europe and North America. 
</P>
<P>
	Toyota's European-bound exports were boosted by the Vitz compact  
model, while North-America-bound shipments were helped by the Lexus 
series and the Camry. 
</P>
<P>
	Nissan Motor Co. exports declined 14.7 percent to 42,767, those  
of Honda Motor Co. decreased 12.3 percent to 43,987, and Mitsubishi 
Motors Corp. shipments sank 49.3 percent to 19,447. 
</P>
<P>
	Mitsubishi's exports were hurt by falling shipments to Asia,  
Europe and the United States and as the automaker expanded 
production overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	Mazda Motor Corp.'s exports tumbled 36.4 percent to 30,423.  
</P>
</TEXT>
