<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 13:11:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cat Thief Looking for First '99 Win </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- D. Wayne Lukas is still trying to find the right  
race for Cat Thief, and he's hoping Saturday's Metropolitan Mile at 
Belmont Park is it. 
</P>
<P>
	Cat Thief, third in the Kentucky Derby and seventh in the  
Preakness, has failed to win in his last seven starts, and has just 
two wins in 13 career races. This year, the colt is 0-for-6. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the one-turn mile at Belmont is a perfect fit for  
him,'' Lukas said. ``We have the weights in our favor, Jerry Bailey 
up, and a perfect fit for our horse.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The $500,000 Met Mile allows for 3-year-olds to receive a weight  
allowance against older horses, and Cat Thief will carry 111 pounds 
compared to the 118-pound, high-weighted Affirmed Success. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though Cat Thief doesn't have many victories on his resume,  
the speedy son of Storm Cat has come close just about every time. 
Before his tough trip in the Preakness, the William T. Young-owned 
colt posted two second-place finishes and four third-places in his 
previous six races, 
</P>
<P>
	Cat Thief, a stablemate of Kentucky Derby and Preakness winner  
Charismatic in Lukas' barn, was just a co-third choice at 5-1 in 
the morning line, behind 2-1 favorite Affirmed Success. Sir Bear 
was the second choice at 7-2 in a formidable field of eight. 
</P>
<P>
	Affirmed Success is making his second start after a seven-month  
layoff. In his only start this year, he was a strong second to 
Artax on a day the winner broke a 30-year-old track record for 7 
furlongs at Aqueduct. 
</P>
<P>
	Trained by Richard Schosberg, Affirmed Success is 4-for-4 at  
Belmont Park. Jockey Mike Smith will be aboard the 5-year-old gray, 
who won four of eight races in '98. 
</P>
<P>
	Lil's Lad, who bled in the May 1 Churchill Downs Handicap, has  
been training well the past few weeks and trainer Neil Howard is 
optimistic his 4-year-old is back in top form. Lil's Lad, also 5-1, 
will be ridden by Joe Bravo. 
</P>
<P>
	The rest of the field includes Rock and Roll, winner of the  
Churchill Downs Handicap; Lord Grillo, Crafty Friend and Liberty 
Gold. 
</P>
<P>
	Lukas, who will be inducted into racing's Hall of Fame in  
August, is going for his fourth Met Mile win. His three winners 
were Gulch, Honour and Glory and Criminal Type. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a very prestigious race and the breeders love it,''  
Lukas said. ``Cat Thief is a homebred that they hope to stand one 
day, and if we get lucky and win it, it will dramatically affect 
his career at stud.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
