<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 06:11:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Panel Eyes Teen Abortion Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A woman who helped her grandson's girlfriend  
get an abortion says a House panel should reject a proposal that 
would make it harder for teens to get abortions because women like 
herself could wind up in jail. 
</P>
<P>
	``Please don't pass this law,'' an emotional Billie Lominick of  
Newbury, S.C., urged the House Judiciary constitution subcommittee 
at a hearing Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Lominick's state requires a parent's consent before an  
abortion can be performed on a minor. She said the 16-year-old 
girl, Mary, had been abused by her parents and feared involving 
them after learning about her pregnancy. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Lominick said she helped get the girl to Georgia for an  
abortion after attempts to petition the courts for permission for 
the operation failed. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I had not been with her, I don't know where she'd be  
today,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill would make it a federal misdemeanor for someone other  
than a parent or guardian to transport a minor out of state for an 
abortion if doing so would violate parental consent or notification 
laws in the child's home state. 
</P>
<P>
	But Eileen Roberts, of Fredericksburg, Va., was in favor of the  
bill. She said she didn't realize her 14-year-old daughter had had 
an abortion until she needed hospitalization for depression and 
$27,000 in follow-up medical treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am here today to ask this committee to reject the eccentric  
notion that any adult stranger has the right to abduct our 
minor-aged daughters and take them to another state for a secret 
abortion,'' said Mrs. Roberts. 
</P>
<P>
	She said an adult friend drove the girl 45 miles away from home  
for the procedure. Virginia requires that parents be notified when 
minors seek abortions. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Charles Canady, R-Fla., the panel's chairman, said the  
proposal's purpose is to uphold parental involvement laws in effect 
in more than 30 states. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters also say it would protect vulnerable girls from being  
spirited away by the self-serving, older men who get them pregnant. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill died in the Senate last year after passing the House by  
less than the margin required to overturn a threatened White House 
veto. 
</P>
<P>
	Canady said it was appropriate for Congress, with its powers to  
regulate interstate commerce, to pass such legislation. ``The 
safety of young girls and the rights of parents demand no less,'' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Rep. Maxine Waters, D-Calif., criticized the proposal as a  
``thinly veiled attempt to chip away at a constitutionally 
protected right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Abortion rights groups also oppose the bill, arguing that girls  
similar to the one in Mrs. Lominick's case may be forced to seek 
unsafe abortions instead of seeking the help of a friend when they 
are afraid to confide in their parents. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is H.R. 1218.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990528.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 11:41:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> VW Said To Plan French Bugatti Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRAUNSCHWEIG, Germany (AP) -- It may have lost last year's battle  
for the Rolls-Royce nameplate to rival BMW, but Volkswagen isn't 
giving up on luxury cars. 
</P>
<P>
	VW chairman Ferdinand Piech told a newspaper that the ``people's  
car'' company planned to revive the legendary Bugatti marquee at a 
new factory to be built in Molsheim, France -- where the original 
Bugattis were made. 
</P>
<P>
	``The first Bugatti model should be finished by the end of the  
year 2002,'' Piech was quoted as saying by the Braunschweiger 
Zeitung for its Saturday editions. ``We'll attack Rolls-Royce with 
that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bugattis were first built in Molsheim in 1909 and quickly gained  
fame with spectacular successes on European racetracks. The firm 
stopped making cars in 1963. 
</P>
<P>
	VW bought the rights to the nameplate last year for an  
undisclosed sum. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the newspaper, VW plans to invest at least $56  
million to build a new factory on the original site. About 200 
people will be employed building the exclusive cars with 
high-powered, 18-cylinder engines, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	Volkswagen showed a prototype Bugatti coupe at last year's Paris  
auto show and a four-door limousine in Geneva in March. At the 
time, it said no decision had been made whether to produce them for 
sale. 
</P>
</TEXT>
