<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 15:52:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Military Buys 9,000 Purple Hearts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOMBALL, Texas (AP) -- The Defense Department is buying 9,000  
Purple Hearts, the Pentagon's first order in eight years for the 
medals that are awarded to soldiers hurt during hostilities. 
</P>
<P>
	The order was made to replenish a diminishing supply rather than  
in anticipation that more would be needed because of the NATO 
attacks on Yugoslavia, said Frank Johnson, a spokesman for the 
Defense Logistics Agency in Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	``It should not be associated with that,'' Johnson said Friday.  
</P>
<P>
	He said orders to his office by U.S. military installations  
around the world have diminished his supply. 
</P>
<P>
	The 37,000 Purple Hearts in stock were refurbished in 1991 and  
``since then we've been eating inventory,'' Johnson said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said 7,000 were distributed to bases last year.  
</P>
<P>
	Graco Industries in the Houston suburb of Tomball is making the  
medals, which cost the government $6 apiece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990528.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 16:41:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Scientists Fear Backlash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Joel Wong is a Chinese-American scientist  
working at the Lawrence Livermore nuclear weapons lab. Lately, he's 
been feeling the chill wind of guilt by association. 
</P>
<P>
	With allegations that China has pursued an espionage campaign  
for U.S. nuclear secrets, he said there is a perception that ``An 
Asian is an Asian, no matter of whether they are an American 
citizen. They think we have our loyalty to the mother country, but 
they don't understand we're American just like everybody else.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His worries come after allegations that Taiwanese-born scientist  
Wen Ho Lee downloaded hundreds of classified files at the Los 
Alamos National Laboratory. Lee, who has not been charged with a 
crime, was fired in March. 
</P>
<P>
	This week, a congressional report concluded that China stole  
U.S. nuclear secrets over 20 years of concerted spying. China has 
denied it. 
</P>
<P>
	The backlash against Chinese-American scientists can be seen  
from bad jokes at work to comments by senators, said Wong, an 
industrial hygienist who was born in Hong Kong. 
</P>
<P>
	He and Raymond Ng, an Oakland native who works as a mechanical  
engineer at the California branch of the Sandia National 
Laboratory, recently took their concerns to Energy Secretary Bill 
Richardson. 
</P>
<P>
	At the labs, employees laughed when a man of Asian descent was  
introduced to lead a session on security, they said. An Asian woman 
at Los Alamos was told she could not transfer with her supervisor 
because of her ``characteristics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At Livermore, about 45 miles southwest of San Francisco, someone  
suggested deleting a photograph of an Asian from the lab's Web 
page, ``because people might suspect that we are spies,'' Wong 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	And the suspicion is not only in the labs.  
</P>
<P>
	An editorial cartoon by Pat Oliphant, for instance, showed a  
horde of tiny figures, many with the buck teeth and thick glasses 
of the most virulent anti-Asian portrayals, scurrying over a 
sleeping security dog at Los Alamos. In the corner a blurb read, 
``The Chinese eat dogs y'know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Oliphant was out of the country Friday, but Universal Press  
Syndicate Managing Editor Sue Roush defended his artistic license. 
``It's not an ethnic slur, it's a cartoon about Chinese 
espionage,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	When Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., talked about the spy scandal  
he made reference to ``a crafty people.'' A newsmagazine called to 
ask Livermore lab officials for a ``generic'' photograph of an 
Asian employee at work to illustrate a spy story. Lab spokesman 
Jeff Garberson declined the request. 
</P>
<P>
	Asians don't act as a homogenous lump, Wong said. And he and his  
colleagues ``don't condone spying on any level against the U.S. 
government,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	This week, Rep. David Wu, D-Ore., the House's first  
Chinese-American, sponsored a resolution saying it was wrong for 
Congress and Americans to stereotype people. 
</P>
<P>
	The resolution was backed by Rep. Christopher Cox, R-Calif.,  
whose special panel's report alleged Chinese theft of U.S. nuclear 
weapons secrets. 
</P>
<P>
	Managers at the national labs have responded positively to Asian  
concerns, Wong and Ng said. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking up was difficult, Wong said, because ``our cultural  
roots say, 'Well, you just do your work and keep quiet.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Sandia head C. Paul Robinson pointed out in a newsletter that  
white Americans such as himself weren't held responsible for the 
case of Aldrich Ames, the CIA agent who sold secrets to the 
Russians. ``Can we all please think extra hard about that?'' he 
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990528.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 11:31:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Botanical Art Creates DC Jungle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Determined to paint the elusive night-blooming  
cactus in bloom, artist Margaret Mee made 15 trips up the Amazon 
River before finally achieving her goal in 1988 -- the year she 
died. 
</P>
<P>
	The product of her determination went on display Friday in an  
exhibit of her 30 years of jungle artwork at the Smithsonian 
Institution's National Museum of Natural History. 
</P>
<P>
	The night-bloomer, selenicereus witii, doesn't bloom every year.  
And when it finally chooses to bloom, it does so for only one 
night. Mee kept an all night vigil to finally get a glimpse. 
</P>
<P>
	The British-born naturalist's three decades in Brazil weren't  
all spent waiting for one flower, though. 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, one of her paintings inspired John Kress, chairman of  
the museum's botany department, to travel to Brazil and search out 
the flower itself. 
</P>
<P>
	He later named it Heliconia var. Meeana in honor or her  
pioneering work, and her painting of it concludes the exhibit, 
which will remain at the museum until Aug. 20. 
</P>
<P>
	``These extraordinary paintings have a special power to convey  
the beauty of Amazonia and enable us to understand why this 
outstanding lady inspired so many scientists, conservationists and 
artists to take up the cause of protecting our fragile planet and 
its life-supporting fauna,'' said exhibit curator Ruth L. A. Stiff 
of England's Royal Botanic Gardens at Kew. 
</P>
<P>
	Mee studied and painted plants in their native surroundings,  
discovering several new species in the process. 
</P>
<P>
	``Margaret Mee: Return to the Amazon,'' opens with a videotape  
of an interview she did and, besides her art, includes descriptions 
of her life and adventures, among them falling from a boat during a 
flood and being fished from the murky water still gripping a metal 
cup and her toothbrush. 
</P>
<P>
	Mee painted with gouache, a system using opaque colors that  
produces the subtle glows of watercolors but with brighter, 
stronger shades to display the boldness and softness or her 
tropical plants. 
</P>
<P>
	Fifty-two paintings line a long hallway off the museum's second  
floor. Visitors see the bright reds and oranges of Neoregelia 
eleutheropetala. Nearby are the painted pinks and purples of 
Cattleya violacea. There is a lacy lavender of Heterostemom 
mimosoides and the spidery whites and grays of Philodendron 
arcuatum. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides paintings from the Smithsonian Institution, including  
one borrowed from the office of museum director Robert Fri, 
paintings are on loan from Kew Gardens, the Margaret Mee Amazon 
Trust, Fundacao Botanica de Sao Paulo in Brazil and private 
collections. The show opened in Houston, Texas and visited other 
cities before coming to Washington. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990528.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 15:18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Penguins' Buyout Proposal On Hold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- A proposal to buy the Pittsburgh Penguins was  
put on hold Friday while attorneys argue over whether the team's 
arena lease should be dissolved. 
</P>
<P>
	A bankruptcy judge Friday refused to grant preliminary approval  
to a buyout plan by Civic Arena landlord SMG Inc. and broadcaster 
Fox Sports Net Pittsburgh until the lease question is resolved. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a good day. Today the Titanic hit an iceberg,'' said  
attorney Doug Campbell, referring to SMG. 
</P>
<P>
	Campbell's client, retired Penguins center Mario Lemieux, has  
presented a competing plan to keep the team in Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Friday, U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Bernard Markovitz indicated  
he would allow the Penguins to set up an escrow account to protect 
season-ticket buyers if the team leaves town. He also said the 
National Hockey League does not have to reveal the name of a 
mystery buyer willing to pay $85 million to move the team. 
</P>
<P>
	Markovitz suggested SMG stands a chance of losing the lease,  
which was scheduled to continue through 2012. He added that the 
SMG-Fox buyout won't be approved until the lease issue is decided. 
He scheduled another hearing for next Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	If the SMG-Fox proposal fails, only Lemieux's buyout plan would  
remain to keep the team in Pittsburgh. An NHL plan would dissolve 
the team. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux, the team's former star center, said he would continue  
negotiating to try to find a plan to make everybody happy. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every day is very important from now on,'' he said outside  
court. ``I want to make deals with people to get this thing going 
within the next couple of weeks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He pointed to a noontime downtown rally Friday to ``Save the  
Pens'' in which fans presented an Internet petition bearing 63,000 
names asking city officials to keep the team in town. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think everybody gets the feeling they're running out of  
time,'' Lemieux said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux said he was happy that the judge gave credence to the  
team's request to end the SMG lease. 
</P>
<P>
	Penguins' lawyers contended the lease is actually a loan that is  
mostly paid off. 
</P>
<P>
	When Howard Baldwin bought the team in 1991, SMG provided $24  
million toward the purchase price. As a result, the team pays an 
estimated $6 million to $7 million per year to SMG, payments 
Penguins officials say helped drive the team into bankruptcy and 
are preventing a financial recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	SMG President Wes Westley has said player salaries and cash  
withdrawals by team owners were more significant causes of the 
Penguins' financial woes. 
</P>
<P>
	Penguins attorney Robert Sable calculated that the unpaid lease  
balance is under $3 million, assuming a 9 percent interest rate on 
the loan. 
</P>
<P>
	The Penguins' request to throw out the lease ``appears to have  
enough substance for further review,'' Markovitz said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990528.0260 </DOCNO>
